<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MexicoReform     12-19 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico Reform,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Plans Talks on Possible Electoral Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari on Monday
announced plans for talks on possible reforms to Mexico's electoral
laws, a key demand of opposition politicians from both right and
left.
   A statement from the president's office said the Federal Election
Commission will begin ``a great public consultation'' next month and
the Chamber of Deputies will discuss electoral reform at a special
June session.
   The opposition says election laws are designed and administered
to ensure continued rule by the Institutional Revolutionary Party,
which has held power since 1929.
   Manuel J. Clouthier, who ran for president as nominee of the
right-of-center National Action Party, has been on a public fast
since Thursday to dramatize his party's demand for electoral reform.
   Party president Luis Alvarez said Salinas' proposals do not go
far enough for Clouthier to stop his hunger strike.
   He complained that ``they still haven't set up a special
commission in the Chamber of Deputies to begin changing election
laws right now.''
   Salinas' announcement came after he met with representatives of
the leftist Authentic Party of the Mexican Revolution, which backed
runner-up Cuauhtemoc Cardenas in disputed July 6 elections.
Clouthier came third.
   It was Salinas' second meeting with an opposition party since he
took office Dec. 1. The day after his inauguration, he met National
Action Party officials.
</TEXT>
