<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SriLanka 7thLd-Writethru a0734 12-19 0677</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0734,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governing Party Candidate Leading In Presidential Voting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with new results; Restores
dropped first reference of election official. PICKS UP graf 7 pvs,
`In the north ...'
^LaserPhoto COL3</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Ranasinghe Premadasa
maintained his lead Tuesday in presidential elections marred by
attacks from Sinhalese extremists who killed at least 15 people,
officials said.
   Although the violence did not stop Monday's balloting in this
ethnically divided island nation, it kept droves of eligible voters
away.
   Turnout in reporting districts was below 50 percent of eligible
voters.
   With 104 of 182 polling districts counted, Premadasa of the
ruling United National Party had 1,155,594 votes, or 51 percent,
according to state television.
   His main rival, former Prime Minister Sirimavo Bandaranaike of
the opposition Sri Lanka Freedom Party had 1,001,572, or 44 percent.
   Ossie Abeygoonesekera, head of a coalition of four small leftist
parties, polled 99,129, or 4 percent. About 9.3 million people were
eligible to vote.
   Turnout in the reporting districts was about 47 percent of
eligible voters. Deputy Elections Commissioner Lakshman Perera
compared it with 80 percent nationwide in the last presidential
election six years ago. Sir Lanka has 9.3 million registered voters.
   In the north, where militants of the Tamil minority are fighting
for an independent state, many districts reported less than 10
percent turnout.
   And in the south, where Sinhalese extremists of the People's
Liberation Front oppose government concessions to the Tamils,
turnout ranged from 20-70 percent.
   All three candidates pledged to end ethnic strife that has
brought this former tourist paradise off the southern tip of India
to the brink of ruin.
   At least 8,500 people have been killed since separatists from the
Tamil minority began a civil war in 1983.
   ``This is a battle between the ballot and the bullet. The bullet
must not win,'' Premadasa said after voting in the capital, Colombo.
   Attacks by Sinhalese militants began after an agreement 18 months
ago that promised Tamils regional autonomy in the north and east and
introduced Indian troops to help disarm the rebels.
   Perera blamed violence and the People's Liberation Front threats
to kill voters for the low turnout. The front is made up of
Sinhalese extremists who oppose terms outgoing President Junius R.
Jayewardene offered for settlement of the Tamil war. They have vowed
to kill anyone who supported the government.
   All the presidential candidates are Sinhalese, a predominantly
Buddhist group that makes up 75 percent of the Sri Lanka's 16
million people and runs the government, judiciary and military.
Tamils, who are overwhelmingly Hindu and total 18 percent of the
population, claim discrimination by the Sinhalese.
   Hundreds of people have been killed in the violence blamed on
Sinhalese extremists.
   On Monday, police and military officials reported bomb and gun
attacks on five voting stations in the Sinhalese heartland near the
capital in southern Sri Lanka.
   Nine voters, a soldier and a policeman were killed and 25 people
were wounded, the officials said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   A police sergeant, an election official and a driver were killed
in ambushes of two jeeps carrying ballot boxes after polls closed in
the southern Moneragala district, the military said.
   Police in Ambalanagoda, 50 miles south of Colombo, reported an
officer killed.
   Military forces and police guarded polling places, particularly
in the south where the Sinhalese gunmen operate.
   Navy personnel with automatic rifles joined police on guard duty
at Kaluthra, 20 miles south of the capital. Soldiers were deployed
at such crowded public places as the town's main bus station.
   Premadasa campaigned as a champion of the poor and promised
monthly allowances equivalent to $75 for the poorest families but
did not explain how he would pay for it.
   He and Mrs. Bandaranaike, who was prime minister in 1960-66 and
1970-77, oppose the agreement with India under which 47,000 Indian
troops are in Sri Lanka, former known as Ceylon.
   Abeygoonasekera blamed both major parties for Sri Lanka's
economic and ethnic problems.
</TEXT>
