<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Assets     12-19 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Assets,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Value of Japan's Land and Structures Tops GNP For First Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spiraling real estate prices last year have boosted
Japan's actual assets past its gross national product for the first
time, the government said today.
   The value of Japan's actual assets _ its land and structures _
rose 20.2 percent to $3.04 trillion last year, while its GNP was
$2.87 trillion, said Economic Planning Agency chief Eiichi Nakao.
   Last year's soaring prices made land assets in Japan, a country
roughly the size of California, worth 4.1 times as much as all the
land in the United States, Kyodo News Service said. In 1986,
Japanese land value was calculated at 2.5 times that of the United
States.
   Financial assets such as equity and deposits also rose, to $23.2
billion _ a 15.6 percent increase over 1986, the agency said.
   ``Rapid rise in land prices and booming stock trading'' fueled
the explosion of assets, agency officials said.
   Urban land prices have stabilized somewhat in recent months
following a series of measures by the central and local governments
to control the spiral, but prices continue to rise in fast-growing
suburbs.
</TEXT>
