<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--QuakeConcert     12-19 0131</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Quake Concert,0133</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Concert Raised $660,000 For Armenia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quickly arranged concert by world-famous
musicians last week raised more than $660,000 to help victims of the
devastating earthquake in Soviet Armenia, organizers say.
   Cellist Mstislav Rostropovich, flutist James Galway, and
conductor Andre Previn joined the English Chamber Orchestra and
several other musicians for Saturday's concert at London's Barbican.
   The funds, to benefit the British Red Cross Armenian earthquake
appeal, came from video and record rights as well as ticket sales at
the soldout performance in the 2,026-seat hall, according to the
Armenia Appeal Committee.
   The concert was broadcast live by the British Broadcasting Corp.,
and the Soviet Union and five other nations televised it.
   The Dec. 7 earthquake killed an estimated 55,000 people and left
500,000 homeless.
</TEXT>
