<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Italy-Storm     12-19 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Storm,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winter Storm Leaves At Least Six Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A winter storm that locked much of Italy in an icy
grip of snow and frigid temperatures has left at least six people
dead and five others missing and presumed drowned, news reports said.
   About 30 small mountain villages in central and southern Italy
and 10 on the island of Sicily were still isolated Sunday by snow,
up to two six-feet deep in some places. The snow blocked blocked
roads and passes.
   Four of the missing were aboard the oceanography research vessel
Posillipo-Loran, missing and presumed sunk in the storm-tossed sea
off Naples. Waves as high as 21 feet hampered the search for the
crew.
   The body of a fisherman whose boat apparently was swamped during
the storm washed up on a beach near Rome early Sunday. Authorities
were still looking for the other man aboard the boat, who was
presumed drowned.
   Italian news reports said five other deaths from traffic
accidents and heart failure had been attributed to the snow and cold.
   The thermometer dipped as low as six degrees below zero in the
Dolomites in far northern Italy and to freezing as far south as
Sicily. None of the snow fell on Rome, but the city was gripped by
freezing temperatures.
   In Vatican City, Pope John Paul II on Sunday blessed nativity
dolls during a traditional ceremony at St. Peter's Square, where two
fountains that normally shoot streams of water were locked in ice.
</TEXT>
