<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSStudy     12-19 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Study,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Few New Yorkers Participate In AIDS Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal study to determine whether a drug can
fight the onset of AIDS in people who carry the AIDS virus may be
delayed because of a failure to attract enough volunteers in New
York City, according to a published report.
   Six New York medical centers participating in the study have
attracted only 257 volunteers, The New York Times reported Sunday.
Recruitment may be suffering because carriers of the AIDS virus do
not want to risk being among the volunteers given a placebo and not
the drug, it said.
   The study was designed to see whether AZT, or azidothymidine, can
prevent or delay the onset of AIDS in people who carry the virus but
have not developed symptoms of the disease. The antiviral agent has
already been shown to prolong the lives of seriously ill AIDS
patients.
   Some volunteers in the study are given AZT while others are given
a placebo.
   Clinics in other cities participating in the study have not
experienced serious recruitment difficulties. The University of
Minnesota had 166 patients enrolled in the study, while Cornell
Medical Center in New York City had just nine volunteers after five
months of recruitment through newspaper advertisements, doctors who
have large AIDS practices and gay organizations.
   The recruitment problems in New York, which has more AIDS
patients than any other city, could slow down the entire study, the
Times said.
   Some New York City study participants also may be cheating by
taking steps to find out if they are getting AZT or the placebo, and
then dropping out of the study or getting AZT from other doctors,
the newspaper reported. Some volunteers in the study also are said
to be taking anti-AIDS drugs that have not been approved for use, it
said.
   Act Up, an AIDS organization, has charged that other tests for
experimental drugs at three city medical schools have excluded the
poor, minorities and women by drawing their volunteers from private
hospitals, where most AIDS patients are white, middle-class men,
rather than from municipal hospitals, the Times said.
</TEXT>
