<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 0022EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PolygamistTrial     12-19 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polygamist Trial,0719</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Late Patriarch's Memory Lingers Over Murder Trial Of Trio</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COALVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The spirit of polygamist John Singer,
gunned down by lawmen nearly a decade ago, is a constant presence at
the murder trial of three young men who took up arms for his cause.
   It lives in his son, John Timothy Singer, who has spoken with
anguish of his father's death, and in the testimony of Addam Swapp,
husband of two of Singer's daughters and his father-in-law's
spiritual heir.
   And it is felt in the German immigrant's handmade buckskin coat,
worn by Addam's brother Jonathan, and in the volumes of Mormon
scripture the three defendants have brought each day to a courtroom
where closing arguments were scheduled today and the jury, after
nine days of testimony, was expected to begin deliberating.
   Singer and the Swapp brothers are charged with murdering a state
officer during a gunfight that ended the clan's 13-day standoff with
police at their Marion homestead last winter.
   The confrontation began after Singer and the Swapp brothers
bombed a nearby Mormon chapel on Jan. 16, the ninth anniversary of
the elder Singer's death, and retreated to the family compound.
   Clan leader Addam Swapp, 27, said the bombing was prompted by a
divine revelation.
   ``It has to do with the injustices perpetrated against our
family,'' he testified. ``John Singer was shot in the back, and
nobody cared.
   ``The truth has been trampled on more than once, and we took a
stand,'' Swapp said. ``We knew we had to do it. We knew we had to
take one day at a time and trust in our God.''
   Corrections Lt. Fred House, who had joined an FBI team in an
attempt to arrest the Swapps on Jan. 28, was ordering a reluctant
police dog to subdue the pair when he was shot in a volley of rifle
fire from the wheelchair-bound Singer.
   Singer, 22, admitted firing the fatal shot but contended he was
aiming at the dogs.
   Swapp, an excommunicated Mormon, married Heidi Singer in 1980 and
her sister Charlotte a few years later. The father of seven, he has
said he believed the bombing would trigger John Singer's
resurrection and the collapse of a ``wicked and corrupt'' church and
state.
   Singer's widow, Vickie, says her husband's death was the result
of a conspiracy between state authorities and church officials angry
at his open practice of polygamy and refusal to send his children to
public schools. The Mormon church officially abandoned polygamy in
1890.
   The Singers, also excommunicated Mormons, taught their children
at home to shield them from a system they believed was tainted by
sexual promiscuity, drug abuse and racial mixing.
   Finally, fearing the state would place his children in foster
homes, Singer, 48, holed up in the compound for 18 days before being
shot by officers in 1979. Police said he pointed a gun at officers
trying to arrest him.
   In an interview taped by federal agents and played for the jury,
John Timothy Singer said that his father was shot as he walked to a
mailbox.
   ``All these men zoomed in on him on snowmobiles, 10 men, what
I've heard,'' he said. ``And he pulled out his gun and he, you know,
(said) `Back off, I don't want any trouble now.' And he turned
around to run home, my sister saw this through binoculars, and as he
turned around to run home they shot him two to three times in the
back.''
   The younger Singer, a thin, quiet man left a paraplegic by a
logging accident four years ago, told of his mother's wrongful death
lawsuit, which was dismissed by a federal judge for insufficient
evidence.
   ``I mean, we couldn't get justice,'' he said. ``I mean, my dad's
been killed and shot, and it wouldn't even be tried.''
   If convicted, Singer and the Swapp brothers face five years to
life in prison.
   Addam Swapp already has been sentenced to 15 years in prison on
federal charges related to the bombing and standoff. Singer and
Jonathan Swapp were given 10-year sentences in the case, while
Vickie Singer was sentenced to five years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
