<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lights     12-19 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lights,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is looking for a dozen men
who wouldn't mind feasting on a diet of King salmon for 100 days.
They'd even get paid a $2,300 salary.
   But there's a catch for those who participate in the U.S.
Department of Agriculture study.
   ``We're talking about salmon with dill weed, broiled salmon,
baked salmon _ just like the fine restaurant food,'' said Gary
Nelson, project coordinator for the department's Western Human
Nutrition Research Center at the Presidio.
   He said the study should begin in January, and cautioned that it
might not be quite as tantalizing as it sounds because it entails
confinement, lots of physical tests and no conjugal visits.
   Participants will sleep, eat and drink at the center's hotellike
facility that has a pool table, compact disc player and television.
There will be daily walks and some organized activities, but no
monkey business allowed.
   ``We don't want anyone to sneak a candy bar or a beer,'' said
Nelson.
   The Agriculture Department originally wanted women for its study,
but couldn't find any takers.
   The study is intended to gauge the effect that a steady diet of
fish has on keeping arteries free of blood clots.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FRANKLIN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials decided to brighten the
holidays for the 1,170 residents of this rural Nebraska community by
paying their December electric bills.
   City Council agreed to forgive December bills totaling $41,069
when an audit showed a surplus in the city's electricity fund.
   City Clerk Dean Gartin said business and residential customers
were pleased to find out they didn't have an electric bill when they
came to City Hall to settle their monthly accounts.
   Helen Schmidt, director of the Franklin Senior Citizens Center,
said the electricity bonus was well-received.
   ``Senior citizens thought it was great because it saved
individuals approximately $50,'' Ms. Schmidt said. ``It was a
wonderful Christmas present to everyone and we are glad the city
passed it on to us.''
   Jim Wilsman, owner of Rightway Grocery, said the council's
goodwill saved him $1,200. It was ``like finding money on the
street,'' he said.
   The city purchases electricity for residences and businesses from
three utilities.
</TEXT>
