<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CarlucciFarewell     12-19 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carlucci Farewell,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outgoing Pentagon Chief Advises Tower to Stick to His Guns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outgoing Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci
served in the job little more than a year, but he has some advice
for his successor _ work with Congress but don't stop fighting for
an increase in military spending.
   Carlucci also says former Sen. John Tower shouldn't turn the
Pentagon on its head in the name of reforming the weapons-buying
process, despite a string of scandals under the Reagan
administration. Carlucci says the U.S. defense industry needs
stability and without it, the industrial base could collapse.
   He has called for a 2 percent increase in the Pentagon's budget
while President-elect Bush, faced with a huge federal deficit, has
talked of zero-growth.
   ``It's not a question of we can't afford it,'' Carlucci said.
   ``If you look at the domestic programs, they continue to go up at
a rate of about 8 percent. Therefore, using that yardstick, I see
nothing wrong with 2 percent in defense,'' he said.
   Asked if he thought a Democratic Congress would go along with an
increase, Carlucci replied, ``If you don't try it's not politically
doable.''
   The defense secretary said he thought Tower, a veteran Armed
Service Committee chairman in the Senate, could make the case ``the
world is coming our way'' in part because of a stronger military.
   Carlucci was interviewed last week in his Pentagon office as he
awaited Bush's announcement of the man who would replace him.
   There is no question Tower will have problems managing Pentagon
contracting, Carlucci said. Indictments could be returned any day in
the long-running Justice Department investigation into Pentagon
fraud.
   ``But the last thing the Defense Department needs is somebody to
come in and yank the procurement system out by the roots again and
say we're going to reform it or change it,'' Carlucci said.
   ``The best reform for the procurement system is stability,
predictability. The blueprint is laid out ... we've made a large
number of changes in the procurement system. Real changes are taking
place in the procurement system and I am proud of them.''
   He said he had instituted a ``total quality management program''
to impress on contractors the need for quality products as well as
ethical conduct.
   The 58-year-old defense chief said he was looking forward to
finding a job in the private sector but had yet to do so.
   He listed among his accomplishments ``establishing a good
rapport'' with his Soviet counterparts, protecting U.S.-flagged
Kuwaiti tankers in the Persian Gulf, and convincing Congress it was
time to close unneeded bases.
   He said in addition to the Pentagon purchasing problems, Tower
will have to help develop arms-control strategy and strengthen the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization while convincing European allies
to resist ``the seductive appeal'' of Soviet arms-control proposals.
   Carlucci, who replaced Caspar W. Weinberger as defense secretary
for the last 14 months of the Reagan administration, said he had
enjoyed the position but found it truly was ``a full-time job.''
   ``On a per-hour basis, I make about as much as my babysitter,''
he joked, adding the secretary's salary of $99,500 is ``lousy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
