<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0741,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Share Prices Fall</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs with final figures. PIckup 4th pvs, `The
index...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched down against the Japanese yen
Monday while share prices fell on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 124.02 yen, down 0.08 yen from Friday's
close of 124.10 yen. Opening higher at 124.20 yen, the currency
moved in a range of 123.93-124.33 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 169.04-point
loser Friday, lost another 66.63 points, or 0.23 percent, to close
at 29,470.08.
   The index rose 56.64 points in early trading but erased the gain
in directionless trading. A dealer with Daiwa Securities said
investors were staying on the sidelines amid concerns over a
possible hike in the U.S. discount rate.
   ``Trading was very thin in the first place, and a majority of
market players didn't have specific ideas on which issues to buy,''
he added.
   On the currency exchange market, the U.S. unit's stability
reflected higher U.S. interest rates and continuing market
expectations for an increase in the U.S. discount rate, dealers said.
   But the dollar's firm note is unlikely to continue because many
investors are considering selling the dollar on overseas markets
ahead of the Christmas holidays, said one dealer at a commercial
bank in Tokyo.
  
</TEXT>
