<NOTE>Eds: A version moved on sports wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An injury prevented hockey star Guy Lafleur from
suiting up for the game, but that didn't stop the crowd from giving
a lusty tribute to their returning hero.
   ``What I gave to them as a hockey player while I was here, they
gave back to me tonight by their encouragement,'' Lafleur said after
Saturday night's game between the Montreal Canadiens and the New
York Rangers.
   Lafleur, 37, who retired from the Canadiens in November 1984
after a 14-year career, is making a comeback this season with the
Rangers.
   In anticipation of watching him sweep down the ice again, some
fans among the crowd of 17,742 at the Montreal Forum paid as much as
$400 a ticket.
   But Lafleur was sidelined by a broken bone in his left foot
suffered in a game Dec. 10. His on-ice return to the Forum won't
occur until Feb. 4.
   The Canadiens decided to go through with a pre-game ceremony
honoring his election into the Hall of Fame in September, and the
crowd responded with a three-minute ovation and chants of ``Guy!
Guy! Guy!''
   Asked how disappointing it was not to be playing, Lafleur said,
``It's not big enough to cry about it, but for sure I'd much rather
be out on the ice. I feel sad for all the people who bought tickets
especially to see me play.''
