<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down Slightly, Stock Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched down against the Japanese yen
today, and share prices fell slightly on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 124.02 yen, down 0.08 yen from Friday's
close of 124.10 yen. The currency, which opened at 124.20 yen, moved
within a range of 123.93-124.33 yen.
   A dealer at Tokyo Bank said the dollar-yen rate today hardly
moved.
   ``The dollar slightly weakened toward the end of trading because
of position adjustment,'' but it did not lead to a strong
dollar-selling trend because ``the majority of traders are still
expecting the U.S. discount rate might be raised toward this
weekend,'' she said.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which lost 169.04 points
Friday, dropped an additional 66.63 points, or 0.23 percent, to
finish at 29,470.08. On Friday, the index closed at 29,536.71.
   The index rose 56.64 points in early trading but erased the gain
in directionless trading without fresh market-affecting news in
Tokyo, dealers said.
   Some market players were concerned the U.S. consumer price index
for November, due out Tuesday, might be an indicator of whether the
United States would raise its discount rate, said a trader with a
major securities firm.
   A dealer with Daiwa Securities said investors were staying on the
sidelines amid concerns over a possible hike in the U.S. discount
rate.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 450 million
shares.
</TEXT>
