<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka-Candidates     12-19 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka-Candidates,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Brief Look At The Presidential Contenders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Sri Lanka-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A past and present prime minister and a
political newcomer were the candidates in today's election for
president, the top government job. All are members of the country's
Sinhalese ethnic majority.
   Here are brief profiles:
   Ranasinghe Premadasa _ The 64-year-old prime minister is the
candidate of the United National Party, headed by President Junius
R. Jayewardene who is barred by law from seeking a third six-year
term. Premadasa campaigned as the champion of the common man. Unlike
most top Sri Lankan politicians who come from elite castes of
society, Premadasa was born in the slums of Colombo and struggled to
the top echelons of power. First elected to Parliament in 1954, he
has been Jayewardene's prime minister for the past 10 years.
However, he has had his differences with his political mentor.
Premadasa was an outspoken critic of the 1987 peace accord
Jayewardene signed in an effort to end the insurrection by Tamil
separatists.
   Sirimavo Bandaranaike _ Head of the Sri Lanka Freedom Party, Mrs.
Bandaranaike became the world's first woman prime minister in 1960.
Although well-educated, she never sought a political role of her own
until her husband, Prime Minister S.W.R.D. Bandaranaike, was
assassinated by a Sinhalese Buddhist monk in 1959. She served as
prime minister from 1960 to 1966 and again from 1970 to 1977 at a
time when the post was still the most powerful job in government.
Now 72, she says she would not return to the stringent economic
controls and nationalization policies that led to her downfall more
than a decade ago. She also opposes the Tamil peace accord.
   Ossie Abeygoonesekera _ The 38-year-old flagbearer of the United
Socialist Alliance is relatively new in politics but used to be a
member of Mrs. Bandaranaike's party. In 1983, he helped actor Vijaya
Kumaratunga found the Sri Lanka Mahajana Party, one of four small
leftist parties comprising the alliance. Kumaratunga, husband of
Mrs. Bandaranaike's daughter, Chandrika, was assassinated early this
year by Sinhalese extremists who vowed to disrupt the elections. In
1982, Abeygoonesekera was jailed for three months when the
government accused him of conspiring to overthrow Jayewardene.
</TEXT>
