<DOCNO> AP881219-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 0502EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Hoax     12-19 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Hoax,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Small Private Plane Did Not Crash Into The Seine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For a while this morning, it looked like the end of
the ``Black Baron,'' the mysterious pilot or pilots who have from
time to time flown illegally over Paris in small aircraft, violating
the prohibition on low-level flights over the capital.
   Responding to urgent telephone calls from ``witnesses,'' police
divers rushed to the scene and recovered the tail of an airplane
from the Seine River in southwest Paris. But that's all there was.
Only a tail. No body. From a plane that crashed two years ago. A
hoax.
   The joke had officials running for several hours.
   The first call came about 3:30 a.m. from a person who told police
that an aircraft was making low-level flights over the 15th and 16th
districts of Paris on the south and west side. A series of similar
calls were received by several police and security agencies.
   About 5:30, a ``witness'' reported he saw the wreckage of an
airplane in the river between the Sevres and Boulogne bridges.
   Several rescue teams were dispatched to the area. Divers pulled
the tail of a plane from the water, but found nothing else.
   The tail of the plane showed signs of rust. After checking the
identifying letters, GDPK, authorities discovered it belonged to an
aircraft that crashed Aug. 28, 1987 west of Paris.
   Police, recognizing they had been had, say the tail of the plane
obviously was thrown into the river by pranksters.
</TEXT>
