<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deep Freeze in Northern Florida; Snow in Great Lakes, Western
Mountains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures plunged below freezing across northern Florida early
today and snow was scattered in parts of the Great Lakes and the
mountains of the West.
   A hard freeze warning was posted for extreme northwest Florida
and a warning for freezing temperatures was extended over the rest
of the state's northern and central regions.
   At midnight Sunday, the temperature had dropped to 22 degrees at
Tallahassee, while Jacksonville reported 28 and Daytona Beach had a
reading of 31. In contrast, Havre, Mont., posted a relatively balmy
40 degrees.
   In the Great Lakes area, snow was falling early today from
Pennsylvania across western New York state and over the northeast
portion of Lower Michigan. A snow advisory was in effect for parts
of northwest New York, where northerly winds were expected to
produce more squalls.
   A winter storm watch was posted for northwest and north-central
Upper Michigan, where strong northerly winds could produce locally
heavy snow southeast of Lake Superior.
   Snow was falling on the mountains of northern Arizona and
southern Utah, and snow advisories were in effect for those areas as
well as the mountains of north-central New Mexico and southern
Colorado. There was some scattered rain in southern New Mexico.
   In the Northwest, snow in eastern Washington state changed to
rain at lower elevations of the state's central and western regions
and along the Oregon coast.
   A high wind watch was posted for eastern Wyoming.
   Today's forecast called for scattered snow from the mountains of
Arizona across the Rockies to the upper Missouri Valley. Strong,
gusty winds were forecast for the central Rockies and middle
Mississippi Valley.
   Highs were expected to be in the teens and 20s over northern New
England, northeast New York state and Upper Michigan; in the 30s and
40s from the remainder of New England to eastern Virginia, over the
rest of the Great Lakes and the lower Ohio Valley, the upper
Mississippi Valley, much of the northern Plains, the Rockies, the
Plateau and the northern Pacific Coast; and in the low 70s in
soutern Florida and much of Texas. Highs elsewhere generally were
predicted to be in the 50s and 60s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 6
degrees below zero at Houlton, Maine, to 57 degrees at the Naval Air
Station near Corpus Christi, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 31 fair; Boston 22 cloudy; Buffalo 23 snow;
Charleston, S.C. 33 fair; Cincinnati 35 fair; Cleveland 26 partly
cloudy; Detroit 24 cloudy; Miami 49 fair; New York 28 windy;
Philadelphia 28 cloudy; Pittsburgh 26 cloudy; Portland, Maine 15
fair; Washington 31 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 16 fair; Chicago 30 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 50
cloudy; Denver 43 fair; Des Moines 35 fair; Indianapolis 29 partly
cloudy; Kansas City 46 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 24 fair;
Nashville 35 fair; New Orleans 33 fair; St. Louis 47 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 43 cloudy; Anchorage 30 cloudy; Las Vegas 43
partly cloudy; Los Angeles 51 fair; Phoenix 55 partly cloudy; Salt
Lake City 23 foggy; San Diego 53 showery; San Francisco 50 cloudy;
Seattle 42 rain.
   _Canada: Montreal 10 partly cloudy; Toronto 25 snow.
</TEXT>
