<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     12-19 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls in Light Trading, Gold Slightly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against all major currencies except
the French franc in European trading this morning as volume began to
decline ahead of the Christmas holidays.
   Gold prices were slightly higher in quiet trading.
   ``We are getting well into the pre-Christmas session,'' said a
trader at a major West German bank in Frankfurt. ``The turnover is
dwindling and the trading interest is even lower than last week.''
   Traders said the dollar drifted lower in Asian trading but there
wasn't any push to sharply lower levels. They said central banks
have stayed out of the market and weren't expected to intervene
today.
   Foreign exchange dealers in Milan said they believed the U.S.
Federal Reserve Board eventually would have to increase the discount
rate, the interest rate it charges on loans to commercial banks. But
they added that the increase probably wouldn't come until next year.
   ``The Fed probably won't move before the New Year. But I still
see it hiking the discount rate up in the next few weeks,'' said one
trader in Milan with a major Italian commercial bank.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.08 yen to a closing 124.02 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at a higher rate of 124.15 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Friday:
   _1.7545 West German marks, down from 1.7635
   _1.4825 Swiss francs, down from 1.4895
   _6.0070 French francs, up from 5.9950
   _1.9796 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9805
   _1,294.90 Italian lire, down from 1,296.50
   _1.2018 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2035
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.8230, compared with
$1.8150 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $414.00 a troy ounce and
at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $413.65. Both were up from $412.25 bid late
Friday.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $413.90, up from $412.25 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 38 cents to close at a bid
$415.62.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.09 a troy
ounce, down from Friday's $6.12.
</TEXT>
