<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vanuatu     12-19 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vanuatu,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports Say President Under Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT VILA, Vanuatu (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of this South Pacific
nation was under arrest today following his attempt to replace the
prime minister with his nephew and dissolve Parliament, state-run
radio said.
   Soldiers manned roadblocks in the capital of 22,000 and liquor
sales were banned to prevent violence following the political
crisis, Australian Associated Press reported.
   AAP quoted police in Vanuatu as denying reports that President
George Solomanu was under arrest.
   The Associated Press made several attempts to contact officials
in Vanuatu, 1,200 miles east of Australia, but all calls went
unanswered or failed to connect.
   AAP also reported that the Supreme Court today ruled that
Sokomanu had violated the constitution on Friday when he announced
he had disbanded the 46-member Parliament and dismissed the elected
prime minister, Walter Lini.
   On Sunday, Sokomanu swore in his nephew, Barak Sope, and
appointed an interim government pending national elections in
February.
   Lini, the prime minister since independence in 1980, has been
locked in a yearlong power struggle with Sope. Lini and other
Parliament members refused to accept the president's action, and
Lini had Sope and his followers arrested.
   Radio reports monitored in Sydney indicated a total of 16
politicians were under arrest.
   Deputy Police Commissioner Harold Thompson told AAP that Sope and
others would be charged Tuesday.
   ``They will include unlawful assembly,'' he told AAP in an
interview. ``We are also looking at intention to overthrow the
present (Lini) government...that's a treason charge.''
   Lini called on Sokomanu to resign. Under Vanuatu's constitution
the president can only be removed on the vote of an electoral
college made up of politicians and regional leaders.
   Sokomanu, in an interview today with an Australian radio station,
admitted his action was unconstitutional.
   ``I believe I took the correct action although it was against the
constitution,'' he told the Australian Broadcasting Corp. ``I put it
his way, why should I wait for the advice of the government when I
know that things are not really going well.''
   Sope and Lini, who helped found the republic of Vanuatu in 1980
from the former Anglo-French New Hebrides, have been fighting for
control of the government for a year. The islands have a population
of about 130,000.
   Sokomanu dismissed Lini and dissolved Parliament after
by-elections last week that gave Lini's governing Vanu'aku party
two-thirds control of the 46-seat Parliament. The opposition
boycotted the vote, and Sokomanu said the Parliament was
unconstitutional because no opposition candidates were put up for
election.
   In Australia, Foreign Minister Gareth Evans said his government
had contigency plans prepared to evacuate about 400 Australian
tourists from Vanuatu if the situation there deterioriated.
   Evans described the events in Vanuatu as a ``political brawl.''
   ``Our view is there is no reason for concern,'' Evans told the
federal parliament in Canberra.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
