<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 0736EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Police-Beating     12-19 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Police-Beating,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eight Miami Cops Suspended Following Beating Death of Suspect</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Miami narcotics detectives suspended following
the fatal beating of a suspected drug dealer were on a police
department list of officers frequently involved in violent arrests,
according to a report published today.
   Detectives Pablo Camacho, Ronald Sinclair and Nathaniel Veal Jr.
were named in a July 1988 ``Early Warning System'' memo, which lists
officers who have five or more extraordinarily violent arrests in
two years, The Miami Herald reported.
   The men were among eight taken off duty with pay during the
investigation of the beating death of Leonardo ``Cano'' Mercado,
police said.
   Camacho, whose eight ``Early Warning'' incidents was the second
highest of the 22 officers on the list, had reputedly been targeted
for assassination under a contract taken out by Mercado, police said.
   Miami Police Chief Perry Anderson promised a swift investigation
of the Friday evening beating.
   ``There are serious issues that must be investigated,'' Anderson
said at a news conference Sunday. ``I don't know how to express to
you how we feel, how my administration feels. We are really saddened
by this incident.''
   Mercado, 35, died just days after Miami police received an
anonymous tip that he had put out a murder contract on Camacho.
   ``This thing was just a frenzy,'' said Sgt. David Rivero, a
police spokesman. He said Mercado died of internal bleeding caused
by ``blunt trauma to the torso.''
   Charges against the officers could include murder, he said.
   Six undercover officers, all members of a special unit set up to
fight street drug sales, confronted Mercado outside a relative's
home while on duty Friday, police said.
   Witnesses said the officers took Mercado inside his relative's
home, shut the door and pulled a curtain closed. The officers didn't
have an arrest warrant, police said.
   Mercado died Friday night at Jackson Memorial Hospital. Rivero
said the department decided to suspend the six officers and two
supervisors after an autopsy Saturday.
   On Friday, police had said Mercado was injured in a struggle that
broke out when three officers approached him for questioning and he
ran into the house and tried to grab a knife. On Saturday, Rivero
said a knife had been found, but he could not say whether Mercado
had brandished it.
   Police records show that from 1980 to 1988, Mercado was arrested
16 times on charges including drug offenses, assault and attempted
murder, but the outcome of the charges was not immediately known.
   Also relieved of duty were Detectives Andy Watson, Tommy Trujillo
and Charlie Haynes, all of whom were at the scene Friday, police
said.
   The drug squad's leader, Lt. Michael Christopher, and Sgt. Manuel
Orosa were suspended and accused of failing to protect a crime scene
and allowing key witnesses _ the six detectives _ to leave the scene.
</TEXT>
