<1ST_LINE>u i PM-France-Blast 1stLd-Writethru a0437 12-19 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Blast, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0437,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Blasts Tear Through Immigrant Workers' Residence</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throuhgout with details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   CAGNES-SUR-MER, France (AP) _ Two explosions ripped through a
four-story residence for immigrant workers in this Mediterranean
town early today, killing one person, injuring a dozen and seriously
damaging the building, police said.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility. The anti-racism
organization SOS-Racism, issued a statement saying it was ``deeply
shocked and indignant over this murderous attack.''
   The first blast pulverized a car parked at the entrance of the
building, which housed 97 people, mostly North African immigrants.
   Pieces of the car were thrown as far as 300 feet away and the
concussion broke windows in area buildings. Four other cars also
were destroyed and numerous vehicles damaged.
   Residents of the building were evacuating rapidly when a second
explosion occurred in the stairwell, police said.
   ``We were drinking coffee with a colleague when the explosion
blew out the door and all of the windows,'' said an employee of a
transportation company next door to the residence. ``We ran outside
and we saw that terrified residents of the center wanted to jump
from the windows.
   ``We shouted to them to remain in the building and we approached
it to help them. It was at that moment that the second explosion
happened. I was thrown 10 meters and my colleague was hit full in
the head by a piece of flying metal.''
   The dead man was identified as Georghe Yordachescu, 50, a
Romanian immigrant who worked as a delivery driver and had lived at
the residence for about four years.
   Six of the injured required hospitalization and were taken to
facilities in Cagnes or nearby Antibes.
   Cagnes-sur-Mer is about six miles west of Nice on the French
Riviera.
   The ground floor of the building suffered severe damage. Dozens
of rooms were devastated and enormous pieces of concrete were thrown
in all directions just as residents were fleeing the building.
   Some of the injured suffered broken bones and cuts. Some had
jumped from the windows.
   After an initial panic, the surviving residents regrouped around
a fire built in front of the building.
   ``We never received any threats,'' one of them said. ``Everything
was just fine at the center. We don't understand this attack.
   The prefect, or local governor, of the area, Jean-Pierre Pensa,
and Suzanne Sauvaigo, mayor of Cagnes-sur-Mer, went to the scene to
begin arranging emergency measures to house the survivors.
</TEXT>
