<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0482 12-19 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0482,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Proposes Action On Homelessness, Earthquake Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>PRECEDE NEW YORK</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Jackson comments today; pick
up 2nd graf, In a.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson said today that Soviet
officials have agreed to his proposal for an international telethon
to raise money for earthquake victims in Soviet Armenia, including
funds to rebuild churches.
   ``It is significant that (Soviet leader Mikhail S.) Gorbachev has
dispatched a minister of culture,'' Jackson said on ``CBS This
Morning.''
   ``And that is a significant breakthrough, that they would allow
us to rebuild churches, the center of hope for Armenia,'' Jackson
added.
   Jackson also called for federal laws to help the homeless in the
United States.
   In a joint news conference Sunday with Soviet Ambassador
Alexander Belonogov, Jackson said the telethon would be broadcast on
television in North America, the Soviet Union and Europe, with
toll-free telephone numbers provided in each country to accept
donations. It is tentatively planned for February.
   Entertainers Bill Cosby, Eddie Murphy and Cher have expressed
interest in the project, and Soviet entertainers would also
participate, he said.
   Telethon proceeds would be used ``specifically to help rebuild
churches in Armenia, to rebuild schools and to rebuild hospitals,''
Jackson said.
   Later in the day, Jackson attended a midtown Manhattan rally
against homelessness and told the crowd of marchers, estimated at
more than 5,000, that failure to provide people with a home should
be made a federal crime.
   ``We must make denial of the right to a house a federal crime,''
Jackson said. ``It must be illegal. ... We must join hands and march
to Washington by the tens of thousands and put housing legislation
on the books in the 1989 Congress.''
   Organizers bused in 2,000 homeless people from shelters and
welfare hotels around the city to join the protesters who marched in
the bitter cold along 57th Street, one of the city's fanciest
shopping thoroughfares.
   ``These streets suggest great wealth but people on other blocks
are freezing to death,'' said Paul Gorman, spokesman for Housing
Action Week, the coalition that organized the rally and six days of
events that preceded it.
   Organizers chose the week before Christmas to hold the march,
Gorman said, because ``this is the time of year when we celebrate
the birth of a homeless child to a homeless family.''
   Just as ``there was no room at the inn'' for Joseph and Mary, he
said, many poor families in New York are also homeless.
</TEXT>
