<DOCNO> AP881219-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 0912EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea     12-19 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roh Says South Korea Will Have Formal Ties With East Bloc by 1990s</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo said today he
believes South Korea, which has been staunchly anti-communist for
four decades, will establish formal diplomatic relations with most
East bloc nations by the early 1990's.
   ``We already have a permanent mission in Hungary, and I think
during my tenure of office, our relations with most other communist
nations would develop into such a level,'' Roh told the South Korean
news agency, Yonhap.
   Roh, whose term expires in February 1993, said South Korea's
trade and other non-diplomatic links with the Soviet Union, China
and other communist nations would continue to grow.
   Hungary in September became the first communist nation to open
diplomatic relations with South Korea and the two countries
exchanged permanent missions this year.
   Hungary's chief of mission in Seoul, Sandor Etre, told reporters
this weekend that he is optimistic that diplomatic relations between
the two nations will be upgraded to an ambassadorial level soon.
   He said Hungary, an ally of communist North Korea, felt it could
not ignore the ``splendid economic growth'' of more than 40 million
South Koreans.
   South Korea signed a contract last week to extend a $65 million
commercial loan to Hungary. Another contract will be signed later to
provide Hungary with $60 million in loans from a consortium of eight
South Korean banks, government officials said.
   South Korea's links with other communist countries also have
grown considerably in recent years. The Soviet Union and several
other East bloc coutries have either opened or agreed to open trade
missions in South Korea.
   More than 1,000 businessmen from South Korea visited communist
nations in the first half of this year, Yonhap said.
   The government's Economic Planning Board is seeking to change
trade and investment regulations it views as obstructing effective
economic cooperation with communist nations, Yonhap said, quoting
unidentified government sources. Yonhap said the government also
will amend trade-related regulations, including import procedures,
participation in international biddings and exhibitions.
   The government now allows only one South Korean business at a
time to participate in biddings offered by communist nations. A
competitive bidding system among South Korean firms will be
considered, the agency said.
   The South Korean diplomatic links with the East bloc represent a
major setback for North Korea. The two Koreas have been bitter
rivals since 1945, when U.S. and Soviet troops ended the Japanese
occupation of the Korean peninsula. The two sides fought the bloody
Korean War in 1950-53.
   The president said he would continue to seek summit talks with
his North Korean counterpart, Kim Il Sung. The summit, if held,
would be the first since the division of the peninsula.
</TEXT>
