<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-NaziTrial     12-19 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Nazi Trial,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Nazi Policeman Gets Life For World War II Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NUREMBERG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nuremberg court today convicted
a former Nazi policeman of killing six people in Poland during World
War II and sentenced him to life imprisonment.
   Wilhelm Wagner, 82, was found guilty of murder in the slaying of
three Jews, two elderly men and a woman while serving as a Nazi
policeman in Poland in 1942.
   The court ruled that justice must be carried out, although 46
years have passed since the crimes were committed.
   Wagner, who denied any involvement in the slayings, continued to
work in West Germany as a policeman after the war.
   Officials say the case against Wagner is one of the last against
those involved in Nazi atrocities, because most are now either dead
or too old and feeble to stand trial.
</TEXT>
