<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GangViolence     12-19 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gang Violence,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Killed In Weekend Gang Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUINN LOTA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four people, including a teen-ager shopping
for Christmas gifts, were killed and 13 were wounded over the
weekend in attacks police linked to gang violence.
   A 15-year-old boy was killed Sunday night in Hawaiian Gardens,
about 20 miles southeast of downtown. The teen-ager, who was not
identified pending notification of relatives, was standing on a
sidewalk when a car with five males stopped and yelled to him,
police Deputy Chris Wahla said.
   When the youth approached the car, he was shot with a shotgun,
Wahla said. He was pronounced dead at a hospital.
   Earlier Sunday, a man bearing gang tattoos was stabbed to death
in Pacoima, an unincorporated area 20 miles northwest of downtown in
the San Fernando Valley. Detectives said the victim's attackers
escaped.
   Two alleged gang members were booked for investigation of murder
after a teen-age bystander was killed in a gang shooting inside a
crowded shopping mall in Panorama City, police said.
   Sergio Alpuche, 16, of Van Nuys, who was not known to be a gang
member, was hit by a bullet in the chest Friday while shopping for
Christmas presents in the San Fernando Valley mall. He died the next
day.
   Arrested in the shooting were two young men, ages 22 and 18, both
believed to be gang members. Also arrested was a 16-year-old, police
said.
   The fourth gang killing occurred Friday night when Terrance Carl
Kennedy, 27, of Los Angeles was gunned down by rival gang members as
he walked with his girlfriend. She was unhurt.
   Two gang members were wounded by rivals early Sunday. Nine people
were wounded in five separate shootings Saturday night. Earlier
Saturday, two Pasadena teen-agers were wounded in a drive-by
shooting.
   At least 325 people have been killed in gang violence in Los
Angeles County this year, up from 284 in all of 1987.
</TEXT>
