<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TeacherShooting 1stLd-Writethru a0477 12-19 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teacher Shooting, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0477,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher Who Disarmed Teen-Ager Tried To Shield Students</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Police say ...' to CORRECT to Cobray, sted
Cabray.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teacher who disarmed a student
accused of killing one teacher and wounding another said he thought
it was a prank when he first saw the teen-ager wielding a
semiautomatic handgun.
   ``I thought it might be one of those Uzi-type water pistols,'' M.
Hutchins Matteson said. ``Then the glass was shot out and I knew it
was a reality.''
   Nicholas Elliott, 16, allegedly shot the window out of a locked
classroom door at Atlantic Shores Christian School in an effort to
reach a student he wanted to kill.
   ``My original thought was, `Oh my God, I'm going to be shot,''
Matteson said about the Friday incident. ``Then I remembered I had
38 students in there.''
   So Matteson stretched his arms in an effort to shield as many
students as possible while pleading with the teen-ager not to shoot.
   ``I cried out to him, `No, no, don't do it. This is no way.
Please don't do this,''' Matteson said.
   Police say Elliott fired two shots, including one that narrowly
missed Matteson, before his Cobray M-11 pistol jammed. Matteson
tackled Elliott and held him down while student Mark McNulty grabbed
the gun, a cheap imitation of a combat assault weapon.
   ``I've never been in a situation where I had to fight for my
life,'' said Matteson, 24. ``I thank God for giving me the presence
of mind and the physical ability to get the job done.''
   Police say that by the time Elliott reached Matteson's Bible
class, he already had killed Karen H. Farley, 40, and wounded Samuel
M. Marino, 37. Marino was in stable condition at Sentara Norfolk
General Hospital.
   Investigators said Elliott had gone to Ms. Farley's and Marino's
classrooms in search of a student who had been tormenting him.
   ``I think it's a classic case of the school bully vs. a meek and
mild kid and the boy finally got fed up with it and just snapped,''
a Virginia Beach detective told The Virginian-Pilot and The
Ledger-Star.
   The newspaper reported Sunday that authorities were saying
privately that racial insults may have ignited the boy's anger.
Elliott is one of four blacks in the student body of 510.
   Principal Fred Fuller said he was unaware of any racial friction,
but he could not rule it out. ``Let's face it, we're dealing with
kids and sometimes they go at it,'' Fuller said.
   Police were at a loss to explain why the student shot Ms. Farley,
who was alone in her portable classroom.
   Authorities said that moments after that shooting, the youth went
to Marino's classroom about 50 feet away and showed him the pistol.
Marino told the boy it was against the rules to bring a gun to
school and asked for the weapon before being shot in the shoulder.
   Elliott is being held on charges of first-degree murder,
attempted murder, malicious assault, use of a firearm in a felony
and firing into an occupied building.
   Relatives and friends have described Elliott as a quiet loner
with an affinity for guns. He spent most of his time playing with
his pet pigeon, watching television and reading gun magazines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
