<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites Sub a0423 12-19 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites, Sub, a0423,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st item to recast.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is looking for a dozen men
who wouldn't mind feasting on a diet of King salmon for 100 days.
They'd even get paid a $2,300 salary.
   ``We're talking about salmon with dill weed, broiled salmon,
baked salmon _ just like the fine restaurant food,'' said Gary
Nelson, project coordinator for the U.S. Department of Agriculture's
Western Human Nutrition Research Center at the Presidio.
   But there's a catch for those who participate in the study,
Nelson warned.
   The study also entails confinement, lots of physical tests and no
conjugal visits.
   Participants will sleep, eat and drink at the center's hotellike
facility that has a pool table, compact disc player and television.
There will be daily walks and some organized activities, but no
monkey business allowed.
   ``We don't want anyone to sneak a candy bar or a beer,'' Nelson
said.
   The Agriculture Department originally wanted women for its study,
but couldn't find any takers.
   The study, expected to begin in January, is intended to gauge the
effect that a steady diet of fish has on keeping arteries free of
blood clots.
</TEXT>
