<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1010EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CrashMemorial     12-19 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash Memorial,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Crash Relatives Decorate Disaster Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROMULUS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of people who died in the August
1987 crash of Northwest Airlines Flight 255 decorated the crash site
near Metropolitan Airport with holiday wreaths.
   About 25 family members brought decorated wreaths Sunday to the
site along Interstate 94 where 156 people died when the plane
crashed on takeoff. They prayed and joined hands to sing ``Silent
Night, Holy Night.''
   Some relatives reacted angrily to Northwest's proposal last week
that it would accept liability in the crash in cases where
plaintiffs declined to seek punitive damages.
   Families who accept could receive money by early next year for
compensatory damages. The plan must be approved by Northwest and
lawyers for the victims.
   ``If they tell us to accept now, there's no way,'' said Frankie
Langton of Carlton, whose daughter Hollins, 26, was killed along
with her fiance, Michael Zanger, 23.
   Betty Polec of Mount Clemens, who organized Sunday's service,
agreed. Her daughter and son-in-law, Lisa and Donald Klaft, were
killed in the crash.
   ``It stinks,'' Polec said. ``They don't want to admit liability
and bring out all the things that were really wrong. And that's
wrong.
   ``If you don't institute a lawsuit, you are forgiving them,
patting them on the back, when they've completely turned our lives
around. I want them punished. No deals for them, absolutely not,''
she said.
   Federal Aviation Administration investigators said pilot error
was the chief cause of the crash, which killed all aboard except a
young girl. A contributing factor was a failed warning system that
should have alerted the pilots that the jet's flaps were not set
properly for takeoff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
