<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1032EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChristmasBriefs     12-19 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Christmas Briefs,0546</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They sang ``Do You Hear What I Hear,'' but
shoppers at a Tulsa mall could hear the Christmas melody only in
their hearts.
   Hearing-impaired students from Edison middle and senior high
schools performed Christmas carols Saturday using sign language,
while Santa Claus also signed to hearing-impaired children a few
feet away.
   ``The choir is really just another dimension to the beauty of
Christmas,'' said Sharon Wade, director of the school's Deaf
Education Department. ``Watching the joy on their faces as they
share these songs makes you realize that Christmas really is for
everyone.''
   This was the second year the choir has performed at Southroads
Mall during the holiday, and the fourth year the signing Santa has
taken requests.
   ``We do this for everyone,'' Ms. Wade said. ``I think it helps
people to be more aware that these kids have something to share at
Christmas.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LUTHERVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At a middle school in this affluent
Baltimore suburb, it's the kids who play Santa Claus for a group of
underprivileged youngsters from the inner city.
   ``Before I became adviser, the person before me had kids bring
gloves and mittens in'' for needy youngsters, said Betty Carpenter
of Ridgely Middle School. ``I wanted to have more personal
involvement. Our kids are mostly well off, and just giving gloves
and mittens just wasn't personal enough.''
   For the past 20 years, the public school has held a Christmas
party. This year, 125 students volunteered as hosts, and many more
helped by donating money and old toys for gifts.
   The 35 guests, ranging in age from 4 to 11, were from St.
Michael's Catholic Church in East Baltimore. Each left with a large
box of presents.
   One of the hosts, 11-year-old Damian Salerno, found giving during
the holiday season to be rewarding.
   ``I think this is good because it makes people who are not as
fortunate as us feel the good of a Christmas most people take for
granted,'' the sixth-grader said. ``I feel good about this.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Santa Claus is supposed to know everyone
who is naughty and nice, but he apparently let someone slip past him.
   A thief snatched the cash box Sunday from a Santa Claus in a
shopping mall, while Santa and his helpers had their backs turned.
   ``Who could rob Santa at Christmastime?'' asked Kim Crowe, whose
7-year-old son, Steven, spoke to the Santa at Harding Mall. ``I
think it has to be terrible. It's worse than terrible. I can't even
think of words to describe it.''
   The cash box, containing about $158, was taken as one helper took
a break and another had her back turned, said police officer Rob
Forrest. The money was being collected by Santa Plus, a private
company that sells pictures of children sitting with Santa Claus,
Forrest said.
   The thief was last seen running toward a neighborhood behind the
mall, police said.
   Mike Hendrixson, who took his son, Jon, 3, to see Santa not long
after the robbery, said he thought the theft was ``cruel.''
   ``It's kind of sick. It's kind of morbid,'' Hendrixson said.
</TEXT>
