<2ND_LINE>PM-NIreland-Bomb, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0518,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Urges British To Stand Firm After IRA Attack</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to MOVE UP that attack was the fourth on
British army homes in the past month; PICKS up 3rd pvs, ``A
12-year-old ...'' DELETES 5th graf pvs, ``It was ...'' to CONFORM</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Neil Kinnock
today urged the families of British soldiers to stand firm against
IRA threats in the fourth bombing of British army homes in the
province in a month.
   The Labor Party leader, on a one-day visit to Northern Ireland,
spoke out in the Londonderry's housing project where more than 100
homes were destroyed or had their windows broken by Sunday's car
bombing, police said.
   A 12-year-old boy and his mother were taken to the hospital and
treated for shock, but no other injuries were reported.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army telephoned a warning about a
bomb at a housing project in Waterside, but it exploded 15 minutes
later, police said.
   The IRA, fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland and
unite it with the Irish Republic, on Friday gave wives and children
of British soldiers one week to get out of what it called the ``war
zone'' and return to the British mainland.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary, the province's police force, said
some army families lived in the Nelson Drive project, but the
majority of the residents were civilians with no military
connections.
   Kinnock said he opposed withdrawing the families of servicemen,
``great though the difficulties are.''
   ``No concessions must be made to terrorism and withdrawal of the
families would be that,'' he said.
   About 10,500 British troops are deployed in Northern Ireland.
Unofficial estimates say between 1,500 and 2,000 soldiers have their
families with them.
   Since the IRA intensified attacks on British servicemen in March,
44 soldiers have been killed, including four at British bases in
continental Europe and one at a base in London.
</TEXT>
