<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Hostage     12-19 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostage,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Group Claims To Hold Missing Belgian</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A previously unknown group has claimed
responsibility for the kidnapping in May of a Belgian physician and
accused him of being a spy.
   The statement by the group, the Soldiers of Justice, was
delivered Sunday to two Western news agencies in Beirut.
   ``The Soldiers of Justice Organization announces that it seized
Jan Marcel Maria Robert Cools, born 15-7-56 in the Belgian
Herk-de-Stad region, on 21-5-88,'' the group said in a typewitten
Arabic-language statement.
   The statement was accompanied by photocopies of Cools' identity
card, draft card, driving license and what looked like his passport.
   Cools, 32, disappeared May 21 after leaving his apartment in the
Rashidiyeh Palestinian refugee camp near the southern port of Tyre.
   He worked for the Norwegian humanitarian organization Norwac for
three months before he vanished.
   Belgian Charge d'Affaires Guebert Bioul confirmed that Cools was
born on the date listed and at the place cited in the statement.
   ``I can't say whether the photocopied documents with the
statement are authentic or not because I haven't seen them. But it's
probable that they are,'' he said in an interview. He declined
further comment.
   The language of the two-page statement indicated the group was
composed of Shiite Moslem militants. Similar pro-Iranian groups hold
most of the 14 other foreigners believed held hostage in Lebanon.
   The statement accused Cools of using his medical activities as a
cover for spying on anti-Israeli Shiite guerrillas in south Lebanon.
   ``After monitoring his suspicious movements and establishing
irrefutable evidence about the truth of his actitivities, our
mujahedeen (holy warriors) arrested him,'' the statement said.
   ``The board of our organization is examining the charges against
Cools to hand down just punishment. The verdict will be issued at a
later date,'' the statement concluded.
   The statement was issued the day after Swiss Red Cross official
Peter Winkler, kidnapped a month ago in south Lebanon, was freed in
the port city of Sidon. He arrived back in Switzerland Sunday.
   Fourteen other foreigners, including nine Americans, are missing
and believed held hostage in Lebanon. The longest held is Terry
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press,
who was abducted March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
