<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sudan-Captive     12-19 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan-Captive,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethiopian Rebels Free Italian Captive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian technician captured by
Ethiopian rebels last June has been released and may fly home today,
an Italian Embassy spokesman said.
   The former hostage, Giuseppe Micelli, was turned over to the
embassy Sunday and was staying at the residence of the ambassador,
Juan Carlo Farnilli, the spokesman said.
   ``A special plane has arrived from Italy to take him there,''
said the spokesman, who refused to be identified by name.
   A small, little-known Marxist-Leninist group called the Ethiopian
People's Revolutionary Army kidnapped Micelli on June 27 in the
Gojjam district of northwestern Ethiopia.
   Micelli had been working near Lake Tana on the Italian-financed
Tana-Beles Irrigation Project, designed to build a dike on the Blue
Nile and construct roads in the area.
   Micelli's capture, like earlier abductions of several Italians
and Ethiopians from the Tana-Beles work force, apparently was
intended to dramatize the rebels' opposition to the Marxist
government of President Mengistu Haile Mariam. All previous hostages
have been freed.
   An Italian Embassy source said last week that the Sudan
government had played a major role in getting the rebels to agree to
Micelli's release. The technician was to have been freed in the
first week of December, the source said, but this was delayed for
unspecified ``technical reasons.''
   The same source also said that rebel conditions for Micelli's
release were ``easily complied with. They (rebels) only asked that
the people in the (Tana) area benefit more from the irrigation
project.''
   The statement was taken as indicating the rebel request was
relayed to the Ethiopian government.
</TEXT>
