<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Greece-Papandreou     12-19 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Papandreou,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Papandreou Vows to Stay in Office Despite Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou, whose
scandal-ridden government won what he called a vote of confidence in
Parliament, today vowed he would remain in office until the June
election.
   ``I feel a special satisfaction and pride because my
parliamentary group, united, had not only approved the budget, but
as I interpreted it ... gave a vote of confidence in the program and
timetable for elections,'' Papandreou said after the votes were
counted Sunday night.
   With 296 deputies present in the 300-member chamber, Parliament
voted 156 to 138 in favor of the record $27.9 billion budget. Two
deputies abstained from the vote.
   All those voting in favor of the budget were from Papandreou's
governing Panhellenic Socialist Movement.
   Papandreou had said he considered Sunday's session a vote of
confidence in his government and would resign if the budget was not
approved.
   The opposition, led by the conservative New Democracy and the
Communist Party, rejected the budget on grounds that this year's
deficit was $2 billion more than last year's.
   The political opposition has been waging a campaign against
Papandreou's party since a $300 million banking and arms scandals
broke in October. The opposition parties charged government
officials were involved in illegal deals allegedly set up by banker
George Koskotas, who is accused of influence peddling, embezzlement
and fraud.
   The deals allegedly involved _ directly or indirectly _ the prime
minister and members of his party, including Papandreou's son,
George, who is minister of education.
   Seven ministers have left the 59-member Cabinet and Koskotas, the
former chairman of the Bank of Crete, fled Greece Nov. 6 and has
been arrested in the United States.
   Newspapers that supported Papandreou have criticized him for
dragging his feet in ordering an investigation into the scandal.
   Recent opinion polls have indicated that Papandreou and his party
would not be able to win a parliamentary majorty if elections were
held soon.
</TEXT>
