<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HotelFire 2ndLd-Writethru a0467 12-19 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hotel Fire, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0467,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Dead, One Critically Injured in Residential Hotel Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with victim now in serious
condition; Picks up 6th graf, `The hospital ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frequent fire alarms may have left some
residents off guard when fire swept through a downtown residential
hotel, killing one person and seriously injuring another, a survivor
said.
   ``We're so used to it,'' said Helena M.B. TeleRado, a hairdresser
and 10-year resident of the Morningside Hotel. ``The fire alarms are
always going on, and they turn it off.''
   Fire Chief Luther Taylor said Sunday's fire was apparently
started by a discarded match in a third-floor apartment.
   Robert Ziker, the hotel's owner, identified the dead man as
Julius Wood, 49, a resident whose body was found in a fourth-floor
apartment.
   Police identified the seriously injured man as Philip Scott, 39.
He was being treated for burns at South Bend Memorial Hospital. He
had been in critical condition, but doctors upgraded him today to
serious.
   The hospital also admitted a resident for smoke inhalation and
another for a broken ankle. Both were in stable condition. St.
Joseph Medical Center admitted a woman in serious condition from
smoke inhalation. Three residents and two fire fighters were treated
for minor injuries and released.
   Two residents who were unaccounted for Sunday night contacted
police early today. They told police they were not at the hotel when
the fire broke out.
   The 105-room, four-story hotel, built in 1924, provided cheap
housing for transients and some long-term residents, many of whom
depend on Social Security or other limited income, authorities said.
   Ms. TeleRado said she paid no heed to an alarm that rang for five
minutes about 9:40 a.m. Sunday, then went silent, or initially to a
maintenance man who pounded on hallway walls and yelled fire.
   ``Certainly there remains a possibility the information was not
passed as quickly as it might have been,'' said Mayor Joseph Kernan.
   He added that a fire alarm was ringing at midafternoon when he
toured the third floor after firefighters controlled the blaze.
   The blaze spread quickly through the L-shaped brick building,
which also housed a music store and karate school. The building was
largely gutted and a wall collapsed. Taylor had no estimate of the
damages.
   Once she realized the danger, Ms. TeleRado said, ``I didn't even
have time to grab my boots, and my boots were right there by the
door.''
   Many residents fled shoeless and in nightclothes and lost their
few possessions, said the Rev. Steven Newton, director of a newly
opened homeless center who took in 56 Morningside residents.
   ``They were in the last kind of housing you can get before the
streets,'' said Newton. ``We're not talking about condominiums being
burned out.''
   Word of the fire brought an outpouring of food, clothing, gifts
and money to the homeless center. Showing a check made out to the
center for $1,000, center volunteer David T. Link said, ``Somebody
just walked in off the street with that.''
</TEXT>
