<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Army 1stLd-Writethru a0519 12-19 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Army, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0519,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disciplinary Action For Alleged Training Abuses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, ``Such charges...'' with 1 graf to CORRECT that
men serve three years, women two; PICKS up 4th pvs, ``Maariv
detailed...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army has taken disciplinary action against
officers in northern Israel for abuses during basic training such as
denying water and medical treatment to recruits, an army spokesman
said today.
   The Hebrew-language daily Maariv said the action followed
complaints filed recently by parents of recruits to the prestigious
Golani Brigade.
   Such charges often cause a scandal in Israel, where all men are
required to serve three years in the army and all women serve two
years. Most men also serve at least 42 days of reserve duty each
year until age 55.
   Maariv detailed five of the complaints in a front-page report.
Recruits also were allowed only two or three hours sleep instead of
the regulation six hours in at least two instances and were once
denied water for an entire day, the newspaper said.
   The report said some soldiers were also denied visits to the
doctor and were left limping from leg injuries. Others have required
psychological treatment following the abuses, the newspaper said.
   Maariv said a sergeant and a platoon commander were removed from
their posts and a company commander was to be tried by an army
tribunal. The paper said unspecified action also was taken against a
base commander.
   The army spokesman would not give details of the actions taken
against the four, or of the alleged abuses.
   As a result of the abuses most recruits dropped out of the unit,
where service is mostly on a voluntary basis and only 25 percent
complete basic training, Maariv said.
   An army spokesman said Gen. Yossi Peled, the head of northern
command personally investigated the matter and took disciplinary
action against those involved.
   ``The Northern Command looks very gravely upon such phenomena.
Steps have been taken to ensure such phenomena don't recur,'' the
spokesman said.
   Maariv said Peled had also appointed a team to further
investigate the case.
</TEXT>
