<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ToughVictim     12-19 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tough Victim,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Scares Away Assailant With Punch-And-Kick Combination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 51-year-old fashion model says
she scared away an armed assailant with a rib punch and a kick to
the shins because she didn't want to die.
   Carolyn Brimer said she left the pistol-packing man stunned
Saturday after he assaulted her in a shopping mall parking lot.
   ``I didn't want to be lying in a ditch, bleeding to death,'' Mrs.
Brimer said. ``I didn't want to be dead in a gutter.''
   Mrs. Brimer, 5-foot-5 and 115 pounds, was on her way to her job
as a department store model when a man appeared as she was getting
her purse from her car.
   The man jabbed a pistol into her rib cage and told her to get
into her car, Mrs. Brimer said.
   ``I knew if I got in that car, that was it,'' she said.
   She said she shouted ``No!'' and gave the man the one-two,
punch-kick combination. The man looked stunned, then slowly walked
away with his head cocked to one side, still looking at her.
   Mrs. Brimer jumped into her car and locked the doors. Larry
Epperson, an off-duty policeman working as a mall security guard,
then walked by and offered help.
   Epperson took Mrs. Brimer inside the store and then chased a man
on foot and apprehended him. No weapon was found.
   Police charged Billy Terry, 23, of Atkins, with criminal attempt
to commit kidnapping, aggravated assault and fleeing the scene of a
crime.
   ``I'm just thankful I have my life _ that God had his hand in
it,'' Mrs. Brimer said. ``I hope other women will stand up and
fight. Someone has got to put a stop to this.''
</TEXT>
