<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica     12-19 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angry Black Music Fans Attack Motorists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One woman was killed and 31
people were injured when black music fans, angered by lengthy delays
at a rock concert, attacked motorists driving on a nearby road,
police and witnesses said today.
   The crowd at the Magalies Resort, about 60 miles west of
Pretoria, hurled rocks, bricks and other objects at passing cars
Sunday afternoon after waiting two hours for the concert to begin,
the witnesses said.
   Twenty-two whites were among those injured as they drove through
a 200-yard stretch of road where the mob was attacking vehicles,
police and witnesses said. A young black woman was killed when she
was hit by a car, police said.
   One of the performers who arrived late, popular black singer
Yvonne Chaka Chaka, narrowly escaped injury when the mob attacked
her van which had her name written on the side, witnesses said.
   About 4,000 people attended the concert, and nine were arrested
on charges including attempted murder, police said.
   In a separate development, a white man charged in a shooting
spree that targeted blacks and left eight people dead and 15 injured
pleaded innocent today to murder charges.
   Barend Strydom, 23, a former policemen who belongs to an neo-Nazi
group, was arrested Nov. 15 after he went on a shooting rampage in
downtown Pretoria. All the victims were black except for one man of
Indian descent.
   Three pyschiatric reports presented to the court today declared
Strydom fit to stand trial.
   Strydom is a member of the Afrikaner Resistance Movement, which
opposes all concessions to blacks and views President P.W. Botha's
gradual race reforms as capitulation to the nation's 26 million
black majority.
   The case was recessed until February.
   Also today, Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu attacked the
government for placing restrictions on the funeral of a black woman
activist.
   Irene Mkwayi, 64, who died last week of natural causes, was the
co-president of the Release (Nelson) Mandela Campaign and wife of
Wilton Mkwayi, a member of the African National Congress guerrilla
movement who has been imprisoned since 1964.
   A large police contingent was present at the church service and
the Avalon Cemetery, where Mrs. Mkwayi was buried. Police restricted
the funeral to 200 people, allowed only ministers to speak, limited
the service to two hours and specified a route for the funeral
procession.
   ``I want to tell the government that they may have tear gas, dogs
and detention without trial, but we know we are going to be free.
This is our land,'' Tutu said.
</TEXT>
