<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1146EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Kemp-Profile     12-19 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kemp-Profile,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kemp Has Worked to Keep Urban Problems, Minorities on GOP Agenda</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack Kemp, the California football player
turned New York congressman, may bring strong new visibility to the
Department of Housing and Urban Development and to the problems
plaguing the nation's cities.
   Kemp talked about ``progressive conservatism'' and sought to
expand his party's appeal among blacks and other minorities as a
candidate for the Republican presidential nomination in 1988.
   As a congressman, he was an advocate of the supply-side economics
and tax cuts that President Reagan embraced. He pushed for tax
incentives to promote development in blighted urban neighborhoods,
and for a program enabling public housing tenants to buy their homes.
   His presidential candidacy proved a flop _ he didn't win a
primary and never scored better than 13 percent of the vote. But
Kemp remained a leading figure among the Republican Party's most
conservative wing at the end of the Reagan era.
   ``I know we didn't win, but if you look at the Republican
platform today ... there's no one who can say we're not winning in
the Republican Party,'' Kemp told supporters in New Orleans during
the Republican National Convention.
   Kemp, 53, was named today by President-elect Bush to join his
Cabinet as HUD secretary.
   He follows Samuel Pierce, a black who survived in the job
throughout all eight years of the Reagan administration _ and who
did so by keeping the lowest of profiles. Even his boss, President
Reagan, once failed to recognize his own Cabinet member and mistook
Pierce for a mayor.
   Although Kemp's strongly conservative ideology is not shared by
most of the mayors of the nation's big cities, his appointment
immediately met bipartisan support.
   Urban advocates believe Kemp's forcefulness and vivid political
profile will bring new attention to the miseries of inner cities _
drugs, poverty, violence and despair _ even if he does not become an
advocate for the increased federal aid they seek.
   ``While there's no question a lot of mayors were in the running,
we do have an elected official who will bring a visibility to issues
that hasn't been there before,'' said Tom Cochran, executive
director of the U.S. Conference of Mayors. ``HUD's going to be on
the front burner again.''
   The concern of urban advocates, however, is that Kemp's plans for
urban ``enterprise zones,'' based on tax incentives, and for tenant
ownership, would supplement and not replace what remains of the
federal urban aid programs that were cut or killed in the Reagan
years.
   Kemp dropped out of the presidential race in the aftermath of his
final round of poor showings in the big Super Tuesday primaries in
mid-March, the last gasp of a candidacy that never met the
expectations many Republican leaders had set for it.
   He has been a member of Congress since winning election in 1970
from the upstate New York district that includes Buffalo, a blue
collar-region. Kemp decided not to seek re-election, though he could
have after dropping out of the presidential race.
   He was born and educated in California, growing up in Los Angeles
and attending nearby Occidental College, where he played football
and led the nation's small colleges in passing statistics. His
father ran a small trucking firm, and his mother was a social worker.
   Kemp got his start in pro football with the Detroit Lions of the
National Football League in 1957, but he bolted to the new American
Football League and the San Diego Chargers. He was later traded to
the Buffalo Bills, where he built a reputation as a perfectionist
who didn't mind playing hurt and led the team to two league
championships and four division titles.
   He was the league's most valuable player in 1965, and that same
year founded the AFL players association.
   He made his first mark in national politics by helping sell
President Reagan on supply-side economics, the belief that cutting
taxes would ultimately produce more tax revenues. He had worked with
Reagan in California as a member of the govenor's staff.
   His call for cutting taxes 10 percent a year for three years was
embraced by Reagan and adopted in a modified form by Congress. At
the same time, it has been credited both with the longstanding
economic recovery and the nation's federal deficit that mushroomed
in the Reagan years.
   ``Kemp is the guy who persuaded Reagan that supply-side economics
was the way to move, and one can argue these horrendous deficits are
a direct result of Kemp's being wrong,'' John Deardourff, a
Republican consultant, once said.
   Kemp has always based his political appeal on economic growth,
and he was often criticized for a mind-numbing devotion to obscure
economists' language and laments for the abandoned gold standard.
   He once described himself as ``less a candidate than a teacher.''
   He frequently surrounded himself at public appearances with black
or Hispanic Republicans, some of them former pro football colleagues.
   While speaking conservative buzz words, he would add his own
concerns about inner cities, minorities, and civil rights.
   ``We've got to have a party that is attractive to minority
Americans,'' Kemp said. ``I'm going to predict ... that by 1992
one-quarter of our party, if we do our job right, will be black,
Hispanic and Asian-American Republicans.''
</TEXT>
