<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Politics 2ndLd-Writethru a0506 12-19 0777</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0506,0798</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Agreement Between Likud and Labor Reported</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with reports agreement has been
reached. Pick up 10th pvs, ``Within Labor...'' Edits to remove
outdated material.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of Israel's two main political blocs,
Likud and Labor, agreed today to form a coalition government, media
reports said.
   State-run Israel radio and Israel television both reported that
the two parties reached agreement when Likud's Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir agreed to demands by the center-left Labor Party that
Labor be given leadership of the powerful parliament finance
committee.
   Avi Pazner, a top aide to Shamir, said agreement had been reached
on major issues but that the prime minister was still trying to get
smaller religious and nationalist parties to join a broad coalition.
   ``We cannot drink `L'chaim' yet,'' he said, referring to the
traditional Hebrew toast meaning ``to life.''
   Israel army radio said the agreement _ seven weeks after
parliamentary elections _ was reached in a meeting between
negotiators Dan Meridor of the right-wing Likud and Moshe Shahal of
Labor.
   It said Labor and Likud also settled a dispute over how many
Jewish settlements would be built in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip, agreeing on a figure of five to eight new settlements in the
next year.
   Labor had been trying to hold down settlements because they could
be an obstacle to the party's plan to trade land for peace with the
Palestinians. Likud had promised as many as 40 settlements to a
nationalist party it was trying to lure into a coalition.
   The army radio report said any settlements after the first year
would have to be approved by the Finance Ministry, which would be
headed by Labor leader Shimon Peres, now the foreign minister.
   Peres agreed to the lesser post of finance minister in the new
government on the condition his party could also chair the
parliament finance committee, giving Labor virtual control over the
country's spending.
   The TV report said that the agreement gave Shamir the right to
approve which Labor member would head the committee.
   Roni Milo, deputy prime minister and an aide to Shamir, said
meetings would be held tonight with religious parties.
   Earlier today, both Shamir and Peres said a new government would
be formed by tonight, either with or without Labor.
   Likud has been trying to form a broad-based coalition with Labor
to avoid having to make concessions on religious issues to the
Orthodox parties. At the same time, it has been negotiating with
likely allies in a narrow government with the smaller parties.
   Within Labor, meanwhile, a group of dovish members called on
party leaders not to join a coalition government if that government
rules out talks with the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   But most of the members of Labor's ``Peace Forum'' said at a
meeting Sunday that the PLO would have to prove its verbal
renunciation of terror with action before the organization becomes
an acceptable partner for peace talks.
   Israeli law now bans contacts with the PLO, which the country
views as a terrorist group. Last week the United States reversed a
ban on contacts with the PLO after the organization's chief Yasser
Arafat made statements recognizing Israel and renouncing terrorism.
   This weekend, a chief PLO official said the PLO's renunciation of
terror did not include atttacks on Israeli military targets.
   Coalition negotiations have been under way since Nov. 1 elections
gave neither Likud nor Labor a clear mandate. Likud won 40 seats in
the 120-member parliament and Labor 39, with the rest split among
small parties.
   The latest impasse arose over Likud's reported promise to the
nationalistic Tehiya party to build 40 new settlements in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip during the government's four-year
tenure.
   Labor said it would agreed to build five to seven Jewish
settlements, Labor minister Chaim Bar-Lev told Israel radio.
   Labor, which has been pushing for an international conference on
a Middle East peace, has resisted building more settlements in
occupied land that might be given up in a peace agreement. U.S.
officials have called the settlements an obstacle to peace.
   Negotiators for Labor and Likud have reportedly agreed Shamir
would lead the proposed government for its full tenure and would not
rotate his position with Peres, as he did in the so-called unity
government that both parties have led since 1984.
   Peres would serve as finance minister while Rabin would retain
the defense ministry. Likud member Moshe Arens, a former defense
minister, would serve as foreign minister.
   In the proposed joint government, the two parties would have an
equal number of ministers in the decision-making Inner Cabinet.
</TEXT>
