<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shevardnadze-Wife     12-19 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shevardnadze-Wife,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lavish Gift For Wife of Soviet Foreign Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Japan-Soviet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lavish gift-giving is a Japanese custom that Nanuli
Shevardnadze, wife of the visiting Soviet foreign minister, is now
familiar with.
   She visited a pearl shop Monday while her husband, Eduard
Shevardnadze, opened the first Japan-Soviet foreign ministerial
talks in nearly three years. And she received a pearl necklace worth
about $24,000, Kyodo News Service reported.
   Mrs. Shevardnadze started her first full day in Tokyo with a
visit to the posh Tasaki Pearl Gallery in Tokyo's Akasaka,
accompanied by her hostess, Chiyo Uno, wife of Foreign Minister
Sousuke Uno.
   Shigeo Maruyama, an employee of the shop owned by the Tasaki
Shinju Co., said Mrs. Shevardnadze saw a demonstration of how pearls
are extracted from shells.
   At the end of her visit, Shunsaku Tasaki, president of the
company, presented Mrs. Shevardnadze with the necklace, Maruyama
said.
   Although the employee refused to confirm the exact price of the
necklace, he said the figure reported by Kyodo was ``probably
right.''
</TEXT>
