<HEAD>Selectmen Order Removal Of Controversial Fire-Station Cross</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORANGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Under threats of a lawsuit by a minister,
selectmen removed a cross that had sat atop the fire station every
Christmas since 1979 and replaced it with a star.
   Edward Berlin, a lawyer for Rev. Randall Gibson, and another
attorney for the Civil Liberties Union of Massachusetts had given
the town a deadline of 5 p.m. Sunday to remove the cross or be taken
to court.
   ``It was never put up there to offend anyone. ... It was a cross
to commemorate Christmas,'' said Charles Baker, head of the town
board of selectmen.
   Baker said the cross was replaced with a star because a star has
no specific religious significance.
   Gibson, a Unitarian Universalist minister, said he was not
opposed to the Christian religious symbol of the cross but called it
an affront to non-Christians.
   About 150 townspeople had signed a petition asking that the cross
stay.
