<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BerdellaPlea     12-19 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Berdella Plea,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sex Killer Pleads Guilty in Five Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRAIG HORST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man pleaded guilty today to the sexual
torture and murder of five men and was sentenced to life in prison.
   Robert Berdella, already sentenced to life plus seven years for
sexually torturing, beating and injecting a man in a separate case,
described the killings during a 90-minute court hearing.
   Berdella, 39, pleaded guilty to first-degree murder in the death
of Robert Sheldon, 23, of Arleta, Calif., testifying that he put a
plastic trash bag over his head and tied it with a rope until
Sheldon suffocated.
   Berdella testified that Todd Stoops, then 24, died of a loss of
blood.
   He said Jerry Howell, Walter Ferris and Mark Wallace died because
they could not breathe after he injected them with drugs and gagged
them while they were tied to a bed in his midtown Kansas City home.
   Berdella was sentenced to life in prison without the chance of
parole on the first charge and life in prison for the other four
counts of second-degree murder.
   Berdella, an art collector and operator of a shop that sold art
objects and antiques, became a household name in Kansas City after
his arrest in April after a man wearing only a dog collar ran
screaming from his midtown house.
   The man told authorities he had been sexually tortured, beaten
and injected with drugs by Berdella.
   ``I kept him bound to a bed with ropes tying his hands and
feet,'' Berdella said when he pleaded guilty.
   The arrest, followed by days of digging in Berdella's yard and
searching his rambling house, resulted in the discovery of two
skulls on Berdella's property and hundreds of photographs depicting
nude and sometimes unconscious men.
   Sheldon's skull was found buried on Berdella's property. No
mention was made of where the rest of his remains or the bodies of
the others were.
   ``I tied his hands and feet on the bed,'' Berdella testified
about the death of Howell, who was 19 when he disappeared in 1984.
``I injected drugs into his body and gagged him. Apparently the
combination of drugs and the gag made it impossible for him to
breathe.''
   Ferris was 25 when he was last seen in 1985.
   Relatives of some victims attended the hearing after private
meetings with Jackson County Prosecutor Albert Riederer.
</TEXT>
