<2ND_LINE>PM-Dartmouth Review,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dartmouth Review Editors Seeking Shorter Suspensions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVERHILL, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer warned today that upholding
Dartmouth College's suspension of two former student editors of a
conservative newspaper would stifle freedom of expression on
campuses nationwide.
   But a lawyer for the Ivy League college said the suspensions of
the two white students for harassing a black professor ``is a simple
case of student misconduct. ... This is not a case which involves
their right to publish.''
   The claims came in opening arguments on a bid by John Sutter, 22,
and Christopher Baldwin, 21, for a court order reinstating the two.
   Grafton County Superior Court Judge Bruce Mohl will decide
whether they should be allowed to return to classes next month
rather than in September, when their 18-month suspensions expire.
   The hearing also will give a first reading of how the court will
treat a lawsuit filed by the two and another Dartmouth Review
staffer claiming the college discriminates against conservatives.
   Jack Middleton, Dartmouth's lawyer, argued that ``freedom of
expression exists on the Dartmouth campus for all members of the
community, not just the Dartmouth Review,'' a student-run,
off-campus weekly.
   But Harvey Myerson, lawyer for the ousted students, called the
case ``a signal unmistakable to the student body and those connected
with it and the student bodies across the country that `you will do
as we wish or you will not do it at all.'''
   Sutter, of St. Louis, and Baldwin, of Hinsdale, Ill., were
suspended in March by a campuswide disciplinary panel for harassing
William Cole. A third student got a shorter suspension and fourth
probation for a classroom clash in February with Cole, one of whose
music courses was panned by the Review as ``one of Dartmouth's most
academically deficient.''
</TEXT>
