<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AIDSReport     12-19 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Report,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Federal AIDS Awareness Program Got Off to Slow Start</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AIDS education program conducted by the
federal Centers for Disease Control has been marred by delays in
mass mailings and by limited broadcasts of public service ads, a
congressional report said Monday.
   The report from the General Accounting Office, the investigative
arm of Congress, also said callers may find it difficult to get
through to an AIDS telephone hotline.
   The GAO said that even though the CDC's AIDS education budget
increased from about $17 million in fiscal 1985 to nearly $210
million in 1988, ``its efforts to focus national attention on AIDS
prevention were impaired by the slow implementation of key
activities aimed at the general public.''
   Rep. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., who requested the GAO
investigation, said she would forward a copy of the report to
President-elect Bush for use as ``a guide on how not to implement
health education programs.''
   GAO found several problems associated with ``AIDS Awareness and
Prevention Month'' in October 1987. The center in May 1987 chose
that month for its big push but was unable to get clearance from the
White House Domestic Policy Council for the centerpiece of the
campaign _ a national AIDS information mailing to all households.
   Plans for the mailing, which had been explicitly sought but not
required by Congress, were dropped in July 1987, the GAO report
said. The following year, Congress made the mailing mandatory, and
the pamphlet ``Understanding AIDS'' was mailed last June.
   CDC produced 38 public service announcements on AIDS and
distributed them to the major television networks on Sept. 30, 1987,
the report said, but there was only one airing by a network during
the following ``AIDS Awareness' month. The three networks did air
CDC public service announcements six times in November 1987.
   When ads did air, they were not likely to be seen by many people.
Between December 1987 and February 1988, GAO reported, nearly 90
percent of all network-aired AIDS public service announcements were
shown during non-primetime viewing hours. Nearly 60 percent were
shown between 11 p.m. and 7 a.m., GAO said.
   The report also cited problems, largely corrected by last summer,
of getting through to an AIDS hotline. CDC expanded the hotline from
17 lines to 68 lines in October 1987 as part of its ``awareness
month'' activities, but the monthly busy signal percentage was far
higher than the 3 percent maximum specified in its contract.
   Between October and December 1987, GAO said, the average busy
signal rates on operator-assisted lines ranged from 38 percent to 65
percent. By last summer, however, the rate was down to 7 percent.
Busy signals are still a problem immediately after public service
announcements are aired and CDC is working to correct the situation,
GAO said.
   The watchdog agency said it also found that the AIDS Information
Clearinghouse, a CDC contractor, was taking twice as long as it
should have to send out copies of a pamphlet called ``What You
Should Know About AIDS'' when investigators sought them last January
and Feburary. But another order in March arrived within the six-day
period required by contract.
   Boxer criticized the Reagan administration for failing to provide
leadership in the AIDS crisis, particularly in educating Americans,
and also said she was disturbed by ``this poor response by the media
to provide frequent AIDS education messages.''
   Boxer chairs the AIDS Task Force of the House Budget Committee.
Last year she urged the TV networks to reconsider their refusal to
air the CDC's education messages, which discussed condoms as a means
of preventing the spread of AIDS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
