<HEAD>Arrest Warrants Issued For Officers Suspected in Prostitution Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have issued arrest warrants
for two police officers supected of involvement in a prostitution
ring that sold Thai women to Japanese employers, police said Monday.
   More than 10 other Bangkok-based groups, including airlines
officials and businessmen, were involved in the ring linked to
organized crime in Singapore and Malaysia, said a senior police
official.
   Police issued warrants last month for Capt. Suplin Sukkasee and
Lt. Chamras Kamma, who have agreed to report to authorities for
questioning by Tuesday, said the police official, who requested
anonymity.
   He said the officers were suspected of luring two women to Japan
with the promise of well-paid jobs. The two, who were forced to work
as prostitutes, sought refuge in the Thai Embassy in October, the
official said.
   Thai women aged 20 to 25 were sold to Japanese employers for at
least $16,000 and were expected to earn twice that amount, the
official said.
