<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Smith-Execution     12-19 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Smith-Execution,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missouri Officals Halt Plans For First Execution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Missouri prison officials today halted
plans to execute an inmate Tuesday in anticipation that a federal
court would block the execution now that he has ordered his appeals
continued.
   An attorney also filed new legal motions with the 8th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in St. Louis seeking to block the
execution, which would have been Missouri's first since 1965.
   C. John Pleban requested a stay of execution for Gerald Smith,
saying Smith, who previously had abandoned his appeals, wants to
continue his legal challenges.
   Included with the request for a stay was a letter Smith wrote to
the federal appeals court.
   ``I had decided to forego any further review of my cases because
I had lost faith in a judicial system that had failed me for eight
years,'' Smith wrote.
   ``However, due to recent developments on my case, this travesty
can no longer be ignored. And thus it would be an act of suicide for
me to follow through with my execution without having these matters
reviewed,'' Smith wrote.
   The recent developments were apparently a reference to a recent
newspaper article that raised doubts about Smith's guilt.
   Smith faces two separate death warrants _ one for the 1980
bludgeoning death of Karen Roberts and another for the 1985 murder
of fellow inmate Robert Baker.
 
</TEXT>
