<DOCNO> AP881219-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1405EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Escapee-Christmas Bjt   12-19 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Escapee-Christmas, Bjt,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>For Escaped East German Border Guard, No Going Home For Christmas</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assocated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Christmas approaches, Jens Bernhardt starts
thinking of home on the other side of the dangerous Berlin Wall.
   But the former East German border guard knows there's no going
back after his dramatic July 1987 escape to the West.
   ``Everything, everyone in my family is back there. It was tough
last Christmas. This year it's also going to be hard _ really
hard,'' Bernhardt says.
   While hundreds of East Germans flee to West Germany and West
Berlin over border barriers each year, only a small number return to
their communist homeland, West German officials say.
   For those fearing possible punishment if they return, there are
often pangs of homesickness, especially during the Christmas season.
   Bernhardt, who says he would be prosecuted as a deserter if he
dared to return home, described what it's like to be an East German
escapee unable to be with his family for Christmas.
   ``Last year I decided to do volunteer work during Christmas at
Checkpoint Charlie'' to keep occupied, Bernhardt said in an
interview in West Berlin.
   ``Just sitting around alone _ '' he said, shaking his head
without finishing the sentence as he reflected on another Christmas
away from home.
   Checkpoint Charlie, a crossing between East Berlin and West
Berlin, is tightly controlled by communist troops.
   Bernhardt works full-time on the West Berlin side of the
checkpoint, giving guided tours at a museum devoted to escapees from
East Germany and lecturing student groups on conditions in his
homeland.
   While Bernhardt admits it is hard making contacts in the West as
an outsider, he says he's happy he took the chance.
   ``Even now after more than a year I wake up some mornings and
break out laughing just at the thought of being here,'' Bernhardt
says.
   Bernhardt was a 19-year-old East German border guard when he
climbed down from a guard tower and scrambled over a steel-mesh
fence separating West Berlin's Spandau district from East German
territory near Potsdam.
   Bernhardt said he decided to flee after he was assigned duty as a
border guard and he was faced with shoot-to-kill orders along the
East German-constructed barriers.
   ``There are so many who try to flee, and every DDR (German
Democratic Republic) soldier is afraid they may someday have to
shoot someone escaping. I couldn't come to terms with that,''
Bernhardt said.
   At least 77 people have been killed trying to escape over
communist-built barriers blocking off West Berlin, according to the
Working Group August 13. The human rights organization took its name
from the day East Germany began building the Berlin Wall on Aug. 13,
1961.
   Bernhardt gave a gripping account of his escape to the West.
   ``There were always two guards, but your partner and guard tower
were changed regularly so you didn't get to know each other well
enough to build up trust,'' Bernhardt recalled.
   ``So after planning for two weeks _ I knew I had to do it _ I
waited until my partner fell asleep at 3 a.m.,'' he said.
   After hiding his colleague's ammunition, Bernhardt said he
climbed down from the tower. His knees weak with fright, Bernhardt
crossed the strip of land separating the tower from the 10 foot-high
steel-mesh fence blocking his way to West Berlin.
   ``I was so afraid I would be spotted and shot at from another
tower. My knees were like rubber and I couldn't run. I staggered
like a drunk to that fence and pulled myself over it with metal
hooks I stuck in the holes of the panels,'' Bernhardt said.
   Now, 17 months after his escape, Bernhardt says he's sorry he
worried his parents by fleeing.
   ``I know I caused them anguish, but now they know I'm safe and
I'm sure they're happy for me,'' he said, asking that the names of
his parents and two younger brothers not be used. He said his home
was in the Karl Marx-Stadt area of East Germany, about 25 miles
north of the Czechoslovak border.
   Asked what he would like most for Christmas if he had a choice,
Bernhardt said: ``That no DDR soldier ever again has to shoot
someone going over the border. That the day comes when we can pass
freely through that Wall.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881219-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1412EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Vietnam-Troops Bjt   12-19 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-Troops, Bjt,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Part of Vietnamese Occupation Force Leaves Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SA MAT, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Infantry, armor and artillery units
returned home Monday in a partial Vietnamese withdrawal from
occupied Cambodia, where insurgents are fighting a jungle war
against the Hanoi-supported government.
   Vietnam said the soldiers were leaving western Cambodia on four
land routes and by boat down the Mekong River, and claimed only
50,000 troops would remain to support the client government
established after its December 1978 invasion.
   The Khmer Rouge rulers whose murderous regime Vietnam overthrew a
decade ago have the strongest force in the three-party guerrilla
coalition fighting the occupation army.
   Villagers and children waving Vietnamese and Cambodian flags
lined the red dirt road on which soldiers of the 5th and 309th
Divisions approached and crossed the frontier Monday at Sa Mat.
   Included in columns were Soviet-made trucks towing U.S.
howitzers, and armored personnel carriers captured at the end of the
Vietnam War in 1975. At least one vehicle still carried the horse
emblem of the U.S. 11th armored cavalry.
   Vietnam and the client government it supports in Phnom Penh say
18,000 soldiers will have left Cambodia in a week-long withdrawal
scheduled to end Wednesday.
   Western analysts sometimes said earlier partial withdrawals,
which began in 1982, were only ``troop rotations.'' Americans and
others acknowledge, however, that Hanoi has reduced its strength in
Cambodia substantially from a high of 200,000 soldiers.
   While vehicles moved along the dusty roads, the official
Cambodian news agency SPK said a fleet of nearly 200 vessels
carrying Vietnamese soldiers sailed past Phnom Penh on their way
home.
   It said about 10,000 people, including Cambodian Communist Party
officials and military officers, lined the banks in the early
morning to bid farewell to the soldiers.
   Division commander Col. Nguyen Minh Chau came ashore to shake
hands and the fleet then sailed southward on the 70-mile journey to
the border, the agency said.
   At Sa Mat, an officer commanding three vehicles, told reporters
his unit had seen little action in two years against Khmer Rouge
guerrillas. ``They may attack some of our small units but when they
hear armor coming they disappear,'' Nguyen Van Vinh said.
   Other soldiers also said they had met few guerrillas during a
prolonged lull, which has been confirmed by Western analysts and
interpreted either as the end of the guerrillas or a ``calm before
the storm.''
   Some say the Khmer Rouge, whose strength usually is given as
30,000-40,000, are concentrating on organization, propaganda and
stockpiling weapons as the Vietnamese proceed with a promised
pullout of all forces by 1990.
   Earlier Monday, elements of the two divisions joined in a
farewell ceremony at Kompong Cham, a provincial capital on the
Mekong about 45 miles from the border. A rock band played, thousands
of children lined the roads and commanders laid wreaths at a
monument to the hundreds of thousands of people killed during the
Khmer Rouge's reign of terror in 1975-79.
   Children held up placards reading ``We will think of you always''
as the Vietnamese column rolled through the war-scarred town toward
steel ferries that took them across the river.
   Kompong Cham, once a thriving resort and center of the rubber
trade, was largely destroyed in 1973 when the Khmer Rouge nearly
seized it from the U.S.-backed government of President Lon Nol. It
became a ghost town during Khmer Rouge rule.
   At this border post, the Vietnamese soldiers completed a five-day
trek across Cambodia from bases in Battambang, a province on the
Cambodian border with Thailand.
   Lt. Gen. Nguyen Van Thai, a Vietnamese army spokesman, said about
6,000 soldiers and 300 vehicles were involved.
   About 150 foreign journalists were in Cambodia for the withdrawal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881219-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1415EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-KempProfile     12-19 0824</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kemp Profile,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kemp's New Job Gives Him Visibility, Chance to Try Urban Ideas</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Jack Kemp, named to head George Bush's
Department of Housing and Urban Development, will now have a forum
to keep his own political profile in the public eye.
   Kemp, who fought unsuccessfully for the Republican presidential
nomination, said after Bush introduced him as the HUD choice Monday,
``I haven't ruled out seeking office some day, nor have I ruled it
in.''
   For now, though, Kemp will have a chance to test some long-held
theories for reviving inner cities and will also bring new
visibility to the problems of housing and poverty that plague the
nation's cities.
   A nine-term Republican congressman from a district that includes
part of Buffalo, N.Y., Kemp is still just 53, and the former pro
football quarterback presents a youthful, energetic appearance.
   Bush said he had extracted no promises that his former rival
would not pursue his own political agenda, but ``it doesn't concern
me at all.''
   ``Jack has shifted gears here to be part of our team,'' the
president-elect said.
   Kemp himself said he would keep silent on issues outside his new
assignment. ``I'm not going to speak on foreign policy. ... I'm
going to be a good team player,'' he said.
   As HUD secretary, Kemp will succeed Samuel Pierce, who survived
all eight years of the Reagan administration while keeping the
lowest of profiles. Even President Reagan once mistook Pierce for a
mayor, a mistake Bush won't make about a widely known politician who
is especially popular among conservatives.
   He is best known for his advocacy of ``supply-side econonics,''
including the tax-cutting bill bearing his name that was the heart
of Reaganomics. But his legislative interests were broad.
   He and liberal Bronx Democratic Rep. Robert Garcia formed an
unlikely alliance to push for urban ``enterprise zones,'' a program
of tax breaks to promote development of blighted urban areas. As a
congressman, Kemp couldn't get the bill passed but could try again
in his new position.
   Kemp also introduced legislation to enable residents of federal
low-income housing to buy their homes at below-market prices.
   Although his strongly conservative ideology is not shared by most
of the mayors of the nation's big cities, his appointment was
generally praised.
   ``While there's no question a lot of mayors were in the running,
we do have an elected official who will bring a visibility to issues
that hasn't been there before,'' said Tom Cochran, executive
director of the U.S. Conference of Mayors. ``HUD's going to be on
the front burner again.''
   Jack French Kemp was born in California, grew up in Los Angeles
and attended nearby Occidental College, where he played football and
led the nation's small colleges in passing.
   His father ran a small trucking firm, and his mother was a social
worker.
   Kemp got his start in pro football with the Detroit Lions of the
National Football League in 1957, but he bolted to the new American
Football League and the San Diego Chargers. He was later traded to
the Buffalo Bills for $100, where he built a reputation as a
perfectionist who would play hurt. He led the team to two league
championships and four division titles.
   He was the league's most valuable player in 1965, and that same
year founded the AFL players association.
   Kemp made his first mark in national politics by helping sell
Reagan on supply-side economics, the belief that cutting taxes would
ultimately produce more tax revenues. He had worked with Reagan in
California as a member of the govenor's staff.
   His call for cutting taxes 10 percent a year for three years was
embraced by Reagan and adopted in a modified form by Congress. It
has been credited with bringing about economic recovery but also has
been blamed for pushing the federal budget deficit to record levels
in the Reagan years.
   Kemp dropped out of the presidential race in mid-March, after
poor showings in the big Super Tuesday primaries. He had decided
earlier not to seek re-election to his congressional seat in order
to pursue the presidency.
   In recent months, Kemp appeared to be angling for an
administration job that would keep him in the political arena and
public eye.
   At the Republican Convention in August, he let it be known he
would like to be selected as Bush's vice presidential nominee. He
wasn't.
   Kemp also suggested back then that he'd like to be secretary of
state, or defense, or treasury, but said he didn't think he'd be
offered any of those jobs. He was right.
   In September, the Heritage Foundation, a conservative Washington
research organization, announced Kemp would become one of its
fellows, lecturing and writing about economics and foreign policy.
But Kemp appararently was not content with the prospect of an
ivory-tower future. He said Monday, ``This is far more attractive,
with all due respect.''
</TEXT>
