<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDS-Court     12-19 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Court,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Changes Mind, Will Allow AIDS Defendants In Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of three judges who said they would
bar AIDS-infected defendants from their courtroom has changed his
mind, saying he is putting his professional concerns ahead of his
personal beliefs.
   ``If they just want to be there for a fair trial, they got it,''
Jack Montgomery, a Jefferson County district judge, said of
defendants who test positive for the AIDS virus.
   Montgomery and two other Jefferson County district judges, O.L.
``Pete'' Johnson and Mike McCormick, announced last week that they
had barred AIDS-infected defendants from their courtrooms to enter
pleas or to be sentenced.
   Instead, the judges said they would conduct the procedures by
telephone _ a practice each judge carried out once.
   Montgomery said he did not want himself or the people in his
courtroom exposed to defendants harboring the acquired immune
deficiency syndrome virus. Johnson and McCormick said their bailiffs
did not want to handle AIDS-infected defendants.
   The judges' policy sparked complaints from lawyers and civil
libertarians that the defendants' constitutional rights were being
violated. Others were concerned about the image the judges' action
gave Birmingham.
   ``We've been fighting that (bigoted) image for a long time _ we
don't need to fight it again with our judges,'' said Charles
Collins, a board member of Birmingham AIDS Outreach.
   Montgomery said he changed his mind after talking with several
people, including his wife.
   ``My wife called me a big, stupid jerk,'' Montgomery told the
Birmingham Post-Herald in a story published Monday.
   ``I'm putting my professional thoughts above my personal
thoughts'' by allowing AIDS-positive defendants into the courtroom,
he said.
   But Montgomery said that under certain circumstances, such as if
an AIDS-infected defendant is known to be violent, he may hold a
hearing at the jail intead of in court.
   Johnson and McCormick also altered their views somewhat, saying
they will look at each case individually.
   ``If there's evidence that the defendant has a history of
violence, they'll be treated differently than one who doesn't,''
Johnson said. ``But someone won't be necessarily banned from the
courtroom just because he has AIDS.''
   The judges had asked the Birmingham Bar Association and the
American Bar Association for guidelines for dealing with
AIDS-infected defendants. Neither organization had any available.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
