<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ProjectVandals     12-19 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Project Vandals,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housing Authority Fights Losing Battle With Vandals, Thieves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Gordon and his crew spent four days
renovating a housing project apartment only to have each day's work
undone by thieves who took everything from wiring to the toilet.
Then the maintenance crew gave up.
   The apartment is one of more than 1,100 vacant apartments in the
city's 10 public housing projects. More than 600 people remain on a
waiting list for subsidized housing as New Orleans Housing Authority
officials battle what they say is a wave of drug-related thefts.
   The problem erupted early this year when cocaine began to
flourish in New Orleans at the same time the price of aluminum began
to rise at recycling centers, according to housing authority
officials.
   Aluminum has become a major source of income for drug users,
according to Gordon, a maintenance supervisor for the St. Thomas
project. Window sashes, mail boxes, mail slots, faucet handles _
anything made of aluminum _ brings between 40 cents and 80 cents a
pound.
   Housing authority workers say apathetic tenants and unresponsive
police share part of the blame for the ransacking of vacant units.
   ``There's no involvement by our residents here,'' said Nathaniel
Johnson, manager of the St. Bernard housing project. ``For somebody
to go on a second floor and tote a refrigerator out and put it on a
truck, someone should become somewhat suspicious. But apparently
they don't.''
   When the thefts are reported to police, Johnson said, ``All we
get is an item number and `Good luck getting your item back.'''
   New Orleans police Lt. Yvonne Bechet said there is a three-man
unit assigned to the housing authority, and police respond whenever
they are called. But she said calls to police from the authority are
infrequent.
   She also said residents may be afraid to call police because they
fear retaliation.
   ``They live in a very dense area, very close to those parties
that are committing those acts,'' she said.
   Don England, authority deputy executive officer for management,
said public housing vacancy rates have been reduced from more than
13 percent in July to just under 10 percent in early December. But
vandals make the work slower and more expensive.
   Meanwhile, the homeless, the unemployed and the poor are forced
to wait for public housing.
   In St. Thomas, for example, there are 170 vacant apartments and a
waiting list of 60 renters. In all, New Orleans public housing
developments have 1,124 vacancies and a waiting list of 634
applicants, based on December figures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
