<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BrantonFuneral     12-19 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Branton Funeral,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noted Civil Rights Lawyer Eulogized</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wiley A. Branton was eulogized Monday as a
crack civil rights lawyer of the 1950s and 1960s whose ``life was
dedicated to protecting and defending the constitutional rights of
black people.''
   A funeral service for Branton, who died here Thursday of a heart
attack at age 65, was held in Washington Cathedral.
   The more than 1,100 mourners, led by Branton's widow Lucille,
included Supreme Court Justice Thurgood Marshall, White House
national security adviser Colin Powell, Washington Mayor Marion
Barry and Lynda Robb, wife of Sen.-elect Charles Robb, D-Va., and
daughter of President Johnson.
   Branton will be buried on Wednesday in Bellwood Cemetery at his
hometown of Pine Bluff, Ark.
   Reviewing the legal career of his old friend, Washington lawyer
Vernon E. Jordan Jr., former president of the National Urban League,
said Branton's work as director of the Voter Education Project in
Atlanta resulted in the registration of more than 600,000 black
voters in the South in the 1960s.
   That cooperative effort helped create the momentum for passage of
the 1965 Voting Rights Act during the Johnson administration and
``made possible the election of blacks and a new breed of whites to
public office,'' Jordan said.
   ``Wiley Branton has argued his last case, he has written his last
brief, he has presented all the evidence and he has made his closing
argument,'' Jordan said. ``... We the jury find today that Wiley
Branton fought the good fight, finished his case and kept the
faith.''
   Marshall, who worked with Branton as civil rights lawyers in
Little Rock, Ark., during the 1957 struggle to achieve racial
desegregation of Central High School, said after the service that
Branton ``was truly a great American, a terrific lawyer and a
tactician who knew what to do for his people, and how to do it.''
   After serving as attorney for Freedom Riders, the young civil
rights activists who toured the South in the 1960s, Branton was
appointed executive secretary of the federal Council on Equal
Opportunity by President Johnson and was special assistant to
Attorneys General Nicholas Katzenbach and Ramsey Clark.
   He also was executive director of the United Planning
Organization, the anti-poverty agency for the District of Columbia,
and was dean of the Howard University Law School from 1978 until
1983. At his death, he was a partner in the Washington office of the
Chicago-based law firm of Sidley and Austin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
