<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Condors     12-19 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Condors,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amid The Flap Of Wings, Freedom and First Flight For Andean Condors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An excited young Andean condor flapped her
wings and took off on her first flight as biologists freed three of
the birds into the wild to pave the way for the eventual release of
endangered California condors.
   The three birds were the first of up to 17 Andean condors,
donated by various zoos where they were born, that will be freed by
late 1989 so scientists can test the techniques they hope to use
when they release California condors, which are North America's
largest birds with 9{-foot wingspans.
   Only 28 endangered California condors remain alive, all in zoos
in Los Angeles and San Diego. Officials are trying to get the
carrion-eating vultures to breed in captivity in hopes of starting
to reintroduce them into the wild in five to 10 years.
   The release of the first three Andean birds started last Friday
night in a wet and snowy Hopper Mountain National Wildlife Refuge,
about 50 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles. The three birds,
living in a net-covered enclosure set into rocks, were placed in a
roost box while scientists removed the netting, U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service biologist Teresa Nichols said Monday by phone from
Ventura.
   On Saturday morning, ``we opened the door, and the birds walked
out single file,'' Nichols said. At first, they stopped where the
net had been, then ``did their morning behavior _ stretching their
wings and trying to find sun to warm up,'' she added.
   Then, 8{-month-old condor Y1, born at San Diego Wild Animal Park
and the oldest of the trio, ``seemed to get very excited,'' Nichols
said.
   ``She started flapping her wings, jumping up and down and turning
in circles, extending her wings and flapping. ... She turned her
head into the breeze, jumped into the air and took her first flight.
She spiraled down, trying to soar awkwardly. She landed on some
rocks on a side hill beneath the release site.''
   The bird ``spent the rest of the day making short flights between
various rocks,'' while 6{-month-old condor Y3, born at Patuxent
Wildlife Research Center in Maryland, ``made some very short flights
among the rocks,'' Nichols said.
   Meanwhile, 6}-month-old condor Y2, born at the Buffalo (N.Y.)
Zoo, roosted on rocks without making a first flight.
   ``They're doing as we expected them to be doing,'' Nichols said.
``We're very pleased with how things are going.''
   Four more condors, kept in an enclosure in the nearby Sespe
Condor Sanctuary, will be released in late January or February, she
added.
   Efforts to save California condors have cost more than $20
million to date. The Andean condor release experiment will cost
about $440,000, officials have said.
   Some 1,000 to 2,000 Andean condors remain in the wilds of South
America. Thousands of California condors once flew free but their
numbers dwindled to the point that four of the last five breeding
pairs vanished in 1984-85. The Fish and Wildlife Service made a
controversial decision to round up the last six wild birds in 1986
to prevent their demise.
   Their path toward extinction has been blamed on development of
condor habitat and lead poisoning from eating carcasses of animals
shot by hunters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
