<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Undercover Grandmother,0148</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Forms Anti-Drug Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who went undercover to help break up a
drug operation in Polk County has organized Grandparents for Drug
Free America.
   Pat Morrison, 44, of Salem said she decided to put together the
non-profit group for both educational and political purposes.
   Morrison has been the focus of media attention since she
participated in a six-week undercover investigation that led to the
arrests of six people Oct. 20-21.
   She said she became involved so police could break up the
methamphetamine lab that was supplying drugs to her daughters.
   One goal of the organization is to gain legislation for federal
controls on the distribution of chemicals used in the manufacture of
methamphetamine, she said.
   The educational side of Grandparents for Drug Free America would
encourage community involvement in reporting drug crime, Morrison
said.
