<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugSurvey     12-19 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Survey,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey: 1 In 5 High School Students Smoked Pot, 1 In 2 Drank Last
Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One in five high school students smoked marijuana
in the last year, and half took a drink, according to a 24-state
survey by an Atlanta-based anti-drug group.
   The survey also reported findings ``shattering one widely held
notion about adolescent drug use'' _ that kids use drugs at school.
Less than 2 percent of the students surveyed reported using alcohol
or drugs on school premises.
   ``Students use drugs in their homes, in the homes of friends and
in cars, primarily at night and on weekends,'' said Dr. Ronald D.
Adams, the author of the report. ``We don't have a `school drug
problem.' We have a community drug problem.''
   The Parents' Resource Institute for Drug Education questioned
students in grades 6-12 in 24 states during the 1987-88 school year.
   More than 203,000 students filled in the group's questionnaire,
which was distributed at 302 schools, said PRIDE spokesman Doug
Hall. Although the survey is not a scientific sampling, the group
believes the results are ``very significant'' because of the large
number of students surveyed, from every region in the country, Hall
said.
   Students did not sign their names to the questionnaries, which
were machine-tabulated by the group to protect confidentiality, Hall
said.
   Among high school students, defined as grades 9-12, 20 percent of
those surveyed had used marijuana at least once in the previous
year. Fifty-eight percent had drunk beer, 56 percent had drunk wine
coolers and 46 percent had drunk liquor. Among seniors, 64 percent
said they had drunk beer in the previous year.
   Of the high school high students who drank, 30 percent said they
usually got drunk when they did.
   Four percent of the senior high students had tried cocaine.
Thirty-five percent had smoked cigarettes.
   Among junior high students, 31 percent had tried beer ; 30
percent, wine coolers; 18 percent, liquore; 16 percent, marijuana; 1
percent, cocaine; and 22 percent, cigarettes.
   More than half _ 51 percent _ of all students surveyed said they
found beer and wine coolers were at least ``fairly easy'' to obtain.
Twenty-six percent said the same for marijuana, and 12 percent said
so for cocaine.
   The questionnaires found some apparent ignorance about the
effects of wine coolers. Sixty-five percent of the students surveyed
said they were uncertain about any detrimental effects from wine
coolers, compared with 56 percent for beer _ although wine coolers,
which contain 4 percent to 6 percent alcohol, are more potent than
beer, which has an alcoholic content of 3 percent to 4 percent.
   The students were most likely to drink or to smoke marijuana at
home, at a friend's house or in a car. The largest percentages said
they had had beer, wine coolers or marijuana at a friend's house,
and liquor at home.
   The survey was conducted among schools in Alaska, Alabama,
Arkansas, California, Connecticut, Florida, Georgia, Idaho,
Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky, Missouri, Mississippi, New Mexico, New
York, Oklahoma, Pennsylvania, South Carolina, Tennessee, Texas,
Virginia, Washington, Wisconsin and West Virginia.
</TEXT>
