<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Arafat     12-19 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arafat,0691</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Allowed to Call Envoy Ambassador, but Recognition Withheld</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto VIE14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Austria said Monday it will allow the PLO
to call its representative in Vienna an ambassador, but will not
regard him as such and does not recognize the recently proclaimed
Palestinian state.
   Chancellor Franz Vranitzky told reporters, however, that his
government's position ``comes close to recognition.''
   Yasser Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization,
said after separate meetings with Vranitzky and Foreign Minister
Alois Mock that he had chosen Daud Barakat as ambassador to head the
PLO mission.
   Vrantizky and Mock said Barakat would be ambassador in title only
and Austria's ambassador to Tunisia would double as ``political
representative'' to PLO headquarters in Tunis.
   They said Austria does not recognize governments without
territory, but pledged political and humanitarian support for the
PLO.
   ``We will include Mr. Barakat in the list of ambassadors, but he
is not accredited,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Walter Greinert said.
   Because Austria has not extended formal recognition of the
Palestinian state proclaimed Nov. 15 in Algiers, Barakat cannot
present credentials to President Kurt Waldheim, Greinert said.
   Waldheim received Arafat at his office in the former Hofburg
imperial palace opposite the chancellery.
   Arafat emerged an hour later flashing a V sign with his fingers,
but did not make a statement, and was driven off in a police
motorcade. The PLO chief has scheduled a news conference for Tuesday
before leaving for Yugoslavia.
   Waldheim hailed the resumption of the U.S.-Palestinian dialogue
in Tunis last week and expressed his hope that an international
conference on the Middle East would be held in the near future under
the U.N. aegis, the Austria Press Agency said.
   Austria's Jews and two other pro-Israeli groups wrote joint
letters to Vranitzky and Mock expressing displeasure about the
reception given Arafat on his one-day visit.
   Mock told reporters the proclaimation of an independent state by
the Palestine National Council, which acts as the PLO legislature,
and ``Arafat's significant speech in Geneva'' to the U.N. General
Assembly last ahad had revived prospects for peace in the Middle
East.
   ``We appeal to Israel to react positively to the PLO's move,
which was positively assessed virtually by the entire international
community, and to give peace a chance in the Middle East,'' Mock
said.
   He praised the PLO's ``full commitment'' to U.N. Security Council
Resolutions 242 and 338 as a basis for solution of the Middle East
conflict, the renunciation of terrorism and its commitment to the
right of all countries in the region to exist within secure borders.
   The foreign minister criticized Israel for what he termed
violations of international covenants and ``fundamental freedoms and
rights'' in the occupied territories. Palestinians in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip began a rebellion against Israeli rule more than a
year ago.
   ``In the last 1{ years the fourth Geneva agreement on the
treatment of the civilian population by a military occupation power
has repeatedly been violated by Israel,'' Mock declared.
   Earlier Monday, Vranitzky promised to support Arafat's campaign
for an international conference. The chancellor criticized Israel's
``misconduct'' toward civilians in the occupied lands and promised
medical and agricultural aid through the United Nations.
   Letters from the Austrian Jewish community, Austrian-Israeli
Society and B'nai B'rith said ``Austria puts itself in the service
of PLO propaganda'' by receiving Arafat.
   ``The PLO is conducting a hoodwinking tactic by talking peace and
at the same time continuing to aim toward destruction of the state
of Israel,'' they said.
   At the airport, Arafat said of the Israelis: ``Sooner or later
they will discover that peace is more important for them than
anything else.''
   Israel considers the PLO a terrorist group and refuses to deal
with it. The United States began direct contacts with the PLO last
week.
   Arafat said ``Yes, yes'' when asked whether he would visit other
European capitals, but would not say where he would go. The official
Yugoslav news agency Tanjug said he was expected in Belgrade on
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
