<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DefenseStudy     12-19 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Study,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says Two-Year Budgets Would Help Insulate Pentagon From
Politics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pentagon budgets should be approved for at
least two years at a time as part of the effort to insulate defense
spending from political pressures, a private study said Monday.
   The Defense Department also should streamline its complicated
procedures for buying weapons, but shouldn't do that by creating an
entirely new bureaucracy outside the four services, the study
concluded.
   The review, directed by a pair of former defense secretaries, was
prepared by the Foreign Policy Institute and the Center for
Strategic and International Studies, two Washington-based,
nonpartisan groups that study policy issues.
   Co-chairs of the study were Harold Brown and James Schlesinger,
who each were secretary of defense in the 1970s.
   The report's recommendations echoed reforms proposed by other
studies in the past decade, all of which have called for more
stability in the defense budget as way of making more efficient use
of taxpayers' money.
   Defense spending has long been one of the most popular areas for
legislators' attention, the study noted.
   ``Political agendas and `pork barrel' politics create serious
problems for the effective management of defense resources; yet
there has been little change in this area to date,'' it said.
   The study called for two-year budget cycles to replace the
current system of annual appropriations. ``Such a move would add
greatly to stability in defense programs and make possible more
sound and realistic budget planning,'' it said.
   The report also called for unspecified changes in the way the
Defense Department buys weapons.
   Creation of Pentagon offices designed to streamline weapons
purchasing hasn't done the job, the study said. ``Although the new
positions have been created, they have been superimposed upon the
old acquisition system without altering the real distribution of
power.''
   The two-year military budget cycle has been endorsed previously
by Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee.
   Nunn said Monday that his committee will look carefully at the
nomination of former Sen. John Tower as secretary of defense in the
Bush administration.
   Tower was Nunn's predecessor as Armed Services chairman but that
doesn't entitle him to any special consideration, Nunn said.
   ``The committee will have a higher set of standards ... for the
entire team,'' from Tower down through the Pentagon's top set of
managers, Nunn told reporters.
   Asked if Tower will receive kid-glove treatment at his
confirmation hearing, Nunn said, ``We are not going to play the
old-boy game this go-around.''
   Nunn said he and Sen. John Warner of Virginia, the panel's
ranking Republican, will insist on seeing the full FBI report on
Tower. The agency conducted an extensive background investigation
following allegations of womanizing and drinking, and reports about
Tower's coziness with the defense industry.
   Nunn said he did not want to repeat the mistakes of Tower's early
tenure as chairman, when former top Pentagon official Melvyn Paisley
was confirmed. Paisley now figures prominently in the government's
defense procurement fraud case.
   Nunn also said he plans to introduce legislation early next year
providing for a broad new program of voluntary national service for
young Americans beginning at age 18.
   The incoming Senate majority leader, George Mitchell of Maine,
``wants to make that one of the top priorities for the Democratic
majority,'' Nunn said, adding he expects substantial Republican
support as well.
   Nunn said he hoped the idea, which would include both military
and civilian service and encompass expanded VISTA and Peace Corps
programs, could be enacted into law within two years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
