<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CounselorScholarships     12-19 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Counselor Scholarships,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Counselor Donates Half His Income To Set Up Scholarship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRETEL WIKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Middle school counselor Jay Levine has invested a
lot of time setting students on a course for life. Now he's doing
the same thing with his money.
   Levine, a counselor for seventh- and eighth-grade students at
Jackson Middle School for 3{ years, started his own scholarship fund
two years ago by donating $20,000 _ about half his annual income _
to the United Negro College Fund. He's pledged to give at least
$20,000 in each of the next four years until the fund reaches
$100,000.
   ``The biggest thing is I see too many students who don't have any
future goals to plan for,'' Levine said Monday. ``You have to have
some expectations to have something happen.''
   Levine, who earned his master's degree in 1971 in counseling from
Wayne State University, said he expects to award the first
scholarship in 1992, using the interest accrued from the investment.
   The United Negro College Fund will administer the trust. Students
who attended Jackson Middle School or Detroit's Southeastern or
Kettering high schools, where Levine formerly taught English, will
get priority in the application process.
   Mary E. Sims, the United Negro College Fund's Michigan area
development director, is helping Levine organize the program.
   ``The important thing he stressed ... is it's just too late when
they become seniors,'' she said. ``Many students need the incentive
way before their senior year. His whole purpose is to say, `Look,
here's some money that might be available if you hit the books.'''
   Sims said the unusual aspect of Levine's gift is that it is from
a high school counselor.
   ``We do have individuals who have established scholarships,'' she
said. ``Most are more affluent.''
</TEXT>
