<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Jordan     12-19 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jordan,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Reshuffles Cabinet, King Appoints New Advisers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Ziad Rifai reshuffled his
Cabinet on Monday and King Hussein named a new national security
adviser, the official Jordan News Agency reported.
   Government sources who requested anonymity said the changes did
not signal any major shift in Jordan's economic or foreign policy.
   Former army commander in chief, Field Marshal Zeid bin Shaker,
was named chief military affairs adviser to Hussein, according to
the news agency Petra. Shaker also is to head the kingdom's public
security, intelligence and army departments, according to a source
in the prime minister's office.
   The post of commander-in-chief will be phased out, official
Jordanian television reported. It said the armed forces' general
chief of staff, Fathi Abu Taleb, will fulfill the responsibilities
of commander-in-chief.
   Adnan Abu Odeh, a minister at the royal court, was appointed
political adviser to the Jordanian monarch, the news agency reported.
   Amer Khamash, a member of Parliament, was appointed a special
adviser to the king, but the agency did not define his duties.
   The prime minister replaced three ministers in the 26-member
Cabinet, according to a high-ranking source in his office. The new
government is the fifth since Rifai took office in April 1985.
   Former Royal Court Chief Marwan Kassem was appointed Jordan's
foreign minister, replacing Taher Masri.
   Zuheir Malhas, who was health minister until 1985, took the post
again, succeeding Zaid Hamzeh.
   Yanal Hikmat, a former protocol chief at the royal palace, became
minister of tourism, replacing Zuheir Ajlouni, who became state
minister for prime ministry affairs. State ministers are advisers to
the prime minister.
   The former supply minister, Abdul Salam Kanaan, also was named a
state minister for prime ministry affairs. The new head of the
Supply Ministry is Fayez Tarawneh.
   Yousef Hamdan, a previous minister of municipal, environmental
and rural affairs switched jobs with the minister of agriculture,
Marwan Hmoud.
   The state minister for parliamentary affairs, Sami Joudeh,
dropped out of the government.
   The new ministers and royal court appointees were sworn in with
Hussein present at army headquarters on the outskirts of Amman, the
agency said.
</TEXT>
