<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Scandal     12-19 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Italy-Scandal,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Key Figure in Railroad Scandal Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A key figure in a corruption scandal that has rocked
Italy's state-run railway has been arrested after returning from
abroad, police said Monday.
   Elio Graziano, who supplied the railway with disposable sheets,
was arrested Sunday when he stepped off a plane from Brazil, police
said.
   An investigation began after a rival company said that only
Graziano's company was informed the government was taking bids on
the $120 million contract.
   Graziano, who is accused of fraud and corruption, is one of 11
people charged in the case, which led to the resignation last month
of the president of the railway, Ludovico Ligato. The government has
named Mario Schimberni, former chairman of the Montedison chemical
conglomerate, as special railroad commissioner.
   Graziano, 56, left Italy before the arrest warrant was issued
Nov. 17. He told Italian journalists in an interview from New York a
few weeks ago that his business transactions with the railway were
always above-board.
