<HEAD>Concert For Burmese Students Canceled After Police Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alleged police threats forced a Thai
student group to cancel a fund-raising concert for Burmese students
who fled a military crackdown, an organizer said Monday.
   The seven-band concert planned for Tuesday was to buy food and
medicine for students who fled the Sept. 18 coup in Burma, said
Watchara Petthong, the leader of Sajjatham, a university-based
political party.
   Petthong said a senior police official on Friday warded that Thai
and Burmese students would be arrested if the concert was staged.
   Authorities in Burma have killed more than 500 people since the
coup, which ended months of pro-democracy demonstrations.
   Gen. Chavalit Yongchaiyudh, Thailand's chief of army, last week
told its leader, Gen. Saw Maung, that he would try to persuade the
students to return home. Yongchaiyudh was the first foreign official
to visit Burma since the coup.
