<2ND_LINE>AM-Election Probe,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Deputy Prison Commissioner Charged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former prison official has been
indicted on charges he sought political contributions from
underlings during Alabama's rough-and-tumble 1986 gubernatorial
election.
   Charles Bryan, 60, former deputy prison commissioner, was the
last of four people indicted following a two-year investigation.
   Montgomery County District Attorney Jimmy Evans said all the
indictments related to the campaigns of former Lt. Gov. Bill Baxley
and ex-Attorney General Charlie Graddick, whose battle for the
Democratic nomination for governor went from the voting booth to the
courtroom.
   Bryan, who turned himself in Saturday at the Montgomery County
Jail, is charged with illegally influencing the vote or political
action of people.
   He was released in less than an hour on $5,000 bond, jail
officials said.
   Indicted on the same charges last week were Birmingham private
investigator Andy Yeomans, Mobile private investigator Don Bekurs
and state prison Warden Jim Morrison of Elmore County. Each turned
himself in Thursday and was released on $5,000 bond.
   Yeomans and Bekurs were campaign aides to Graddick, and Bekurs
also worked in Graddick's state office. The indictments accused them
of using state-owned electronic equipment to eavesdrop at state
Democratic Party headquarters in Birmingham.
   Morrison and Bryan were accused of ordering subordinates to
solicit contributions or make donations to the Baxley campaign.
During the 1986 campaign, Morrison was director of external
corrections for the state prison system and Bryan was his boss, Hale
said.
   Bryan resigned the Department of Corrections in early 1987.
   Baxley, now a Birmingham attorney, and Graddick, a Montgomery
investment banker, were out of their offices Monday, their
secretaries said, and they could not be reached for comment.
   Graddick led the 1986 Democratic runoff by 8,756 votes over
Baxley. But a state Democratic Party subcommittee and the federal
courts ruled Graddick's lead came from illegal Republican crossover
votes and they gave Baxley the party's nomination.
   The resulting voter backlash helped Guy Hunt become Alabama's
first Republican governor in 112 years.
</TEXT>
