<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya-Party,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Cabinet Minister, 2 Others Expelled From Ruling Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling party Monday expelled a former
Cabinet minister from its ranks 10 days after he resigned in a
quarrel over party election results.
   Kenneth Matiba, former transport and communications minister, was
ousted from the Kenya African National Union party along with Kimani
wa Nyoike, a jailed former legislator, and Joseph Kimotho Mugambi,
the vice-president of a party branch.
   Matiba resigned his Cabinet post Dec. 9 after challenging the
results of party elections in his central Kenya constituency.
   Peter Oloo Aringo, party chairman and minister for education,
said the party's governing council expelled Matiba and Mugambi
because of ``their unpatriotic and anti-nationalistic behavior'' in
questioning the party elections.
   Mugambi was party vice-chairman in northern Laikipia district.
   Matiba's expulsion from the party also automatically removes him
from Parliament and a by-election must be held in his constituency.
   President Daniel arap Moi, who also leads the party, told 4,000
party members at a seminar in Nairobi that Matiba had ``insulted the
presidency'' by sending supporters to the State House _ Moi's
official residence _ to protest the election results.
   He should have sent them to party headquarters at the Kenyatta
International Conference Center ``if he had any complaints,'' Moi
said.
   Matiba was first elected to Parliment in 1979 and has held
several positions in Moi's Cabinet in the past five years.
   Moi on Monday replaced Matiba with a political rival, Joseph
Kamotho.
   Nyoike, a former assistant minister in Moi's government, was
sentenced to a 20-month prison term Oct. 21 for failure to reveal to
the authorities an alleged plot by the rebel Kenya Patriotic Front
to overthrow Moi's government.
