<2ND_LINE>AM-Bodies Returned,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bodies of Air Crew Returned By Polisario Guerrillas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bodies of five Americans killed in a
missile attack on their plane by Polisario guerrillas in the Sahara
Desert have been returned to U.S. authorities, the State Department
said Monday.
   The bodies were handed over Friday by the guerrillas to U.S.
officials in Algiers, where the Soviet-armed group has its
headquarters.
   They were then flown to the U.S. Air Force base in Torrejon,
Spain, for a forensic examination and will be returned to their
families as soon as the procedure is completed, said a State
Department official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The five Americans were working for T & G Aviation of Chandler,
Ariz., which was under contract to the U.S. Agency for International
Development on a locust-spraying operation over the Sahara Desert.
   The Polisario Front, which has been fighting Morocco since 1975
for control of the Western Sahara, accepted responsibility for the
downing of the DC-7 aircraft Dec. 10 and the crippling of a
companion plane that landed safely after the attack.
   The Polisario apologized for the attack, which occurred over
remote desert terrain on the border between Morocco and Mauritania,
saying it mistook the planes for Moroccan military reconnaissance
aircraft.
   The United States said evidence gathered so far by an FBI
investigating team had not turned up any reason to doubt the
Polisario explanation.
   But the State Department official said the team has not been able
to get to the crash site because of concern for safety in the combat
zone. The team has interviewed the five survivors of the other plane
and examined the damage, he said.
</TEXT>
