<HEAD>Rate Plan Approved For Diablo Canyon Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ratepayers may have to absorb up to $4.5
billion of the $5.5 billion cost of building the Diablo Canyon
nuclear power plant under a plan that was approved Monday by the
state Public Utilties Commission and immediately attacked by
consumer groups.
   The 28-year plan agreed to by Pacific Gas & Electric Co., the
commission staff and Attorney General John Van de Kamp will base
electric rates on how well the plant performs, starting with a 5
percent increase in January.
   But opponents immediately announced they would challenge the plan
in the state Supreme Court.
   Sylvia Siegel, executive director of the consumer group Toward
Utility Rate Normalization, said ratepayers had been victimized by a
``sellout by the PUC'' and accused the commission of ``abdicating
its responsibility to set just and reasonable rates.''
   Diablo Canyon began commercial operation in 1985, 13 years behind
schedule and at 17 times its originally planned cost. Design errors,
the discovery of the magnitude of the earthquake fault, federal
licening problems and legal challenges all contributed to the delay.
   In its initial assessment, the state commission's consumer staff
recommended allowing only $1.1 billion of Diablo Canyon to be
imposed on ratepayers.
   In the settlement approved Monday, the commission decided for the
first time in state history to base rates for a major power plant on
the level of its performance _ the more electricity it produces, the
more customers will pay.
   The commission staff estimates that under terms of the
settlement, customers will pay $3.5 billion and PG&E stockholders $2
billion. That would represent the largest amount a state regulatory
commission has required stockholders to pay for the construction
costs of an operating nuclear plant in the United States.
   Those figures are based, however, on the average lifetime
performance of similar nuclear plants nationwide, operating at 58
percent of capacity. The utility predicts that Diablo Canyon will
operate at 65 to 70 percent of capacity, which would add about $1
billion to the customers' share.
   Under the settlement, electric rates are scheduled to rise about
5 percent Jan. 1 and another 1.6 percent in each of the next three
years, with additional amounts in those years for inflation in the
cost of fuel. Those percentages would be higher in the years after
1989 if the plant operates as well as the utility is forecasting.
   PUC member Donald Vial called the plan ``reasonable, consistent
with the law and in the public interest.'' He said the utility would
have an incentive to operate the plant safely because the U.S.
Nuclear Regulatory Commission would order a shutdown of an unsafe
plant.
   But the plan is opposed by a number of consumer and environmental
groups, who argued that mistakes and mismanagement by the utility _
in particular, the failure to detect the magnitude of an earthquake
fault near the San Luis Obispo site _ would justify saddling company
stockholders, rather than ratepayers, with most of the construction
cost.
   Mothers for Peace, the San Luis Obispo group that has led the
opposition to Diablo Canyon, said the plan connecting electric rates
to performance would create ``a dangerous conflict between plant
safety and company profits.''
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
