<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--WatermelonVote     12-19 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Watermelon Vote,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Watermelon Growers To Vote on Promotion Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commercial watermelon growers and handlers will
be able to vote Feb. 6-21 on whether to support a proposed research,
advertising and sales promotion program, the Agriculture Department
said Monday.
   J. Patrick Boyle, administrator of the department's Agricultural
Marketing Service, said the program would operate at no cost to the
federal government and would be financed by an assessment of up to 2
cents per 100 pounds of melons.
   The fee would be paid by farmers who grow five acres or more of
watermelons and by ``first handlers,'' or dealers who buy directly
from farmers.
   A 29-member board representing producers, handlers and the
general public would administer the program, Boyle said.
   Two-thirds of those voting in the referendum are required for
approval of the program. Ballots, copies of the proposal and other
details are available from country extension agents where
watermelons are grown, he said.
</TEXT>
