<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bush-Christmas     12-19 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Christmas,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, in Christmas Greeting, Says There Is Peace on Earth</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush said Monday he sees an
``enormous opportunity'' to forge a new relationship with the Soviet
Union and further the cause of peace.
   In a Christmas greeting to inaugural workers, Bush said he hopes
to strengthen that peace and add to the stock of good will among men.
   Bush and his wife Barbara attended the Christmas party in a stark
government warehouse adjacent to a converted machine-gun factory
where inaugural preparations are under way.
   The vice president donated a bright, red bat and Mrs. Bush a
stuffed bear to the workers' ``Toys for Tots'' drive.
   Bush said he and President Reagan had a ``fascinating'' meeting
with Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev in New York two weeks ago,
and he called the current period a ``promising time in American
history.''
   ``I am not euphorically optimistic about that (U.S.-Soviet)
relationship, but I see enormous opportunity,'' said Bush. ``What
more important assignment does a president have than to work for
world peace?''
   ``We're in a changing world. We see change inside the Soviet
Union. We've seen historic change in Pakistan recently. We hope to
be seeing more change, inextricable change toward democracy in this
hemisphere,'' he said.
   He told more than 500 workers he will be a president who will
``keep our forces strong and keep our defenses up.''
   ``But as we approach Christmas, I think it is important to note
that there is peace on earth, certainly between the major powers ...
and I'd like to add to that ingredient of good will towards men by
working hard to strengthen the peace so that our kids, your kis can
grow up in a world with much more promise of peace,'' he said.
   He predicted ``a rough battle when I get in there in terms of
getting this deficit under control. But when I campaigned and said I
want this to be a kinder and a gentler nation, I believe it very,
very much. And I'm going to work, with the help of all of you to
make that promise come through.''
   Bush joked, ``We are very generous in this line of work. You have
48 hours off for Christmas.''
   ``Only 24!'' a woman shouted.
   ``Make that 24 for some departments,'' said Bush. ``That makes us
double grateful to all of you (who) are willing to make that
sacrifice to make this inauguration the best one yet.''
</TEXT>
