<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RenewedHouses     12-19 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Renewed Houses,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Low-Income Families Move Into Renewed Houses In Time For Christmas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two historic row houses once targeted for
demolition were turned over to low-income families Monday after a
$1.5 million renovation that officials said is helping to revitalize
a depressed section of north Philadelphia.
   ``It's like a Christmas present to me, because I was in a
must-move situation,'' said Tamara Fletcher, 26, who had been living
with her two sons in a home that recently was condemned. ``This
couldn't have come at a better time.''
   Eleven other families, some living in shelters for the homeless,
also will be moving into the brightly lit, blue-carpeted apartments,
which were refurbished through a public and private partnership
organized by National Temple Non-Profit Corp., a north Philadelphia
community group.
   ``North Philadelphia is on its way back,'' Mayor W. Wilson Goode
said during ribbon-cutting ceremonies Monday morning.
   The city provided no-interest loans and tax breaks, and funding
came from the Cigna Corp., Ford Foundation, National Trust for
Historic Preservation, William Penn Foundation and Mellon Bank
(East).
   The two houses that once belonged to wealthy 19th-century
Philadelphians were renamed the Waller House after doors were carved
through the common wall during renovation.
   The residents, all of whom earn less than 50 percent of the
Philadelphia-area median income, which totals $17,400 for a family
of four, will pay a maximum of 30 percent of their income for rent
and utilities.
   They had to apply through National Temple and must abide by rules
to keep up the apartments or face eviction, said Judy Burrell,
property manager.
   ``I am so excited,'' Ms. Fletcher said. ``If I have to stay up
day and night, I'm going to try to get things together, so I can set
my Christmas tree up.''
   Just a few years ago, the house into which she and her sons moved
Monday had been inhabitable.
   ``The front steps of the building had been stolen,'' said Henry
Magaziner, an architect who helped plan the renovation. ``The doors
were bashed in, the windows were busted, rain had been pouring into
the building, the roof was leaking.''
   A former owner, social worker Deborah Roye Morris, said she saved
the building from a wrecking ball in 1982. She drove by one day as a
hole was punched in one wall and was able to stop the demolition,
she said.
   City Housing Director Edward A. Schwartz said he has noticed
others taking action because of the renovation work.
   A number of people whose houses had been condemned in north
Philadelphia recently asked for a reprieve, offering to reinvest in
the community, Schwartz said.
   ``That's a sign that people are sitting up and taking notice,''
he said.
   The trend is also visible in some large mortgages that banks have
approved during the past six months, he said.
   Anti-drug efforts, job training, improved schools and commercial
development also figure into the picture, he said.
   ``So that gradually the elements that make a viable urban
comunity are put into place and people have confidence that they can
stay and move here and improve their quality of life.''
</TEXT>
