<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bush-Debt     12-19 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Debt,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Sees Security Problem in Third World Debt</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush said Monday that U.S.
national security officials should take part in a review of Third
World debt because of ``enormous problems'' in the Western
Hemisphere.
   The World Bank estimates Third World debt as $1.32 trillion,
including $442 billion in Latin America and the Caribbean.
   Bush said there is concern that private banks have not been
lending as much as they might.
   ``And so I do think that should be subject to a major review
which will include not just the Treasury but our national security
people because we've got enormous problems, particularly in our own
hemisphere, on Third World debt,'' he said.
   He did not point to any of the debtor countries, some of which
have long histories of military coups.
   Bush spoke of possible problems in forgiveness of debt.
   European creditor governments have forgiven some debt, especially
in the poorest countries of Africa. Debts owed to the U.S.
government could only be forgiven if Congress voted to do it, which
is considered unliklely.
   Some forgiveness of debt by private banks has also been widely
proposed.
   ``I think you have to be very careful of forgiveness of debt if
you want future loans,'' Bush said. ``So I think we've got to find a
more versatile answer than simply compelling private institutions to
write off the debt.''
   U.S. banks would be certain to question the legality of any
attempt to force them into debt forgiveness.
   Bush said forgiveness would dry up the $20 billion in additional
bank lending urged in 1985 by James A. Baker III, who was then
treasury secretary. Baker will be secretary of state under Bush.
   Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., who has urged some forgiveness,
quickly said the rest of the world has known for years that Baker's
ideas were unworkable.
   ``I am happy that the president-elect recognizes that we need a
new approach,'' he said in a statement. ``If he is serious about
encouraging and supporting economic reform in the developing world,
he will have to consider interest or debt reduction in many cases _
as I have argued for six years.''
   Fifteen Third World countries with the biggest debts have begun
reducing them again, the International Monetary Fund reports.
   These countries, singled out by Baker in 1985, increased their
debt last year by $2 billion after reductions in 1985 and 1986. But
in the first six months of this year there was a $9 billion
reduction.
   The fund's Bureau of Statistics did not give a total for the debt
of the 15 countries in its study, made available Monday in the
official ``IMF Survey'' dated Dec. 12. The World Bank, sister
organization of the fund, released figures on Sunday that added up
to $519.3 billion for the 15.
</TEXT>
