<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Summit,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gulf Council Praises U.S., Iran, Iraq at First Peacetime Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Fahd of Saudi Arabia praised U.S.
negotiations with the PLO and the Iran-Iraq truce as he led his five
Gulf Cooperation Council allies into the oil giants' first peacetime
summit Monday.
   Leaders resplendent in gold-rimmed cloaks and white turbans heard
an opening speech by the Emir of Bahrain, Sheik Isa bin Salman al
Khalifa, before retiring behind closed doors to focus on
accelerating Iran-Iraq peace talks and supporting the quest for a
Palestinian homeland.
   ``The summit coincides with the emergence of a climate of peace
in the gulf, the end of the war between Iraq and Iran,'' said Isa.
``We hope this will contribute to normal relations and balanced
policies that in turn will return confidence and restore the
war-shattered bridges so that peace may be revived.''
   All Gulf Council states supported Iraq in the eight-year war that
ended in August with a U.N.-negotiated cease-fire.
   The council was formed at the beginning of that war. It binds
Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, and
Qatar in an economic and military pact to strengthen security
because of the Iran-Iraq war and Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's
threats to export Iran's Islamic revolution.
   Isa praised Palestinians waging a year-old uprising against
Israel in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. He also pledged the
council's ``unwavering support'' for the state declared in the
occupied lands by the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   He promised the gulf states would help contain Lebanon's
protracted civil war and ``salvage the Lebanese people.''
   Earlier, Fahd lauded the United States for beginning last week a
dialogue with the PLO ``toward a genuine and just peace for the
Palestinian people,'' the Gulf News Agency reported.
   Washington reversed a 13-year ban on talks with what it called a
terrorist organization after PLO chairman Yasser Arafat renounced
terrorism and recognized Israel's right to exist.
   ``It is perhaps a good omen that the ninth GCC summit is convened
in an atmosphere of blissful breakthroughs, namely the end of the
war between two Moslem neighbors _ Iran and Iraq _ and the
commencement of direct negotiations between them.''
   Officials said the gulf leaders will discuss economic integration
during four-day talks and ways of mustering a united front within
the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to help
stabilize production and prices. Gulf Council states account for 40
percent of the world's proven oil supplies.
   Their charter calls for a gulf common market patterned after the
European Community, but critics say progress in that direction has
been painfully slow.
</TEXT>
