<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1831EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-EggScare     12-19 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egg Scare,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain to Pay Farmers Millions to Kill Hens, Destroy Eggs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced Monday it will help
farmers weather a national scare over food poisoning with payments
of more than $34 million to destroy millions of young hens and
surplus eggs.
   One British newspaper called the crisis ``the storm in an
eggcup.'' It already has cost a deputy health minister her job.
   Government officials have reported 49 outbreaks of salmonella
from eggs affecting 1,000 people, but they say many more cases are
unreported.
   The scare burst into the open Dec. 3 when Edwina Currie, an
outspoken deputy health minister, said most British eggs were
tainted by salmonella bacteria, a form of food poisoning that can be
fatal in rare cases. Egg sales plummeted by up to 60 percent, and
Mrs. Currie was forced to resign Friday.
   The same day, the government launched a $925,000 advertising
campaign to try to make Britons buy eggs again.
   Under Monday's $34.6-million package to bail out producers, the
government over the next four weeks will buy 400 million eggs to
burn _ the equivalent of two weeks' normal consumption, now unwanted
by wary consumers.
   In addition, 4 million hens will be destroyed, mostly by gassing.
That number equals about a tenth of the national laying flock.
   The bailout will allow farmers to trim their flocks and lower
their costs.
   Opposition legislators and media commentators complained that
farmers had no right to a subsidy from the Conservative government
of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   Opposition Labor Party legislator Clare Short said the government
had bowed to farming interests without making it ``conditional on
cleaning up their act.''
   ``The farmers are a big, powerful lobby, so the government
responded to them and shows no concern for members of the public,''
Ms. Short said.
   ``The storm in an eggcup is a good indication of the
Conservatives' instincts,'' commented The Independent, a British
national newspaper. ``They decided to protect producers at the
expense of consumers and taxpayers.''
   Some critics complained that Agriculture Minister John MacGregor,
who announced the payment in the House of Commons, did nothing to
clear up confusion over the extent of the danger.
   MacGregor said that if people boil eggs until they are hard and
avoid foods made with raw eggs ``then the risks are very, very small
indeed.''
   Farming organizations said the money, to be given in a single
payment, was not enough.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881219-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 2006EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FernaldWorkers     12-19 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fernald Workers,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fernald Workers Return From Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees of a federally owned
uranium-processing plant who still want safety improvements ended a
10-week strike and returned to work Monday for reorientation
sessions.
   The plant's operator, Westinghouse Materials Co. of Ohio, said
the safety and refresher orientations will take much of the week.
Westinghouse spokesman Bob Walker said production of uranium, used
in other Energy Department plants nationwide for the government's
production of nuclear weapons, will resume after the sessions.
   ``It's basically a reorientation, safety sessions, safety
training. Before we can restart production, we're going to have to
recertify people on a lot of equipment. So it's going to be several
days before we're going to start producing,'' Walker said.
   Operations at the plant 18 miles northwest of here, formally
known as the Feed Materials Production Center, will return to normal
after holiday vacations end at the beginning of January, Walker said.
   ``I think getting back to work is the beginning of the
solution,'' said David Day, president of the Fernald Atomic Trades
and Labor Council, a 14-union coalition at the plant. ``We had to
get back into the plant to help make things safe and to address some
of the other problems.''
   Westinghouse officials said as many as 400 employees returned to
work Monday. An additional 250 striking employees were laid off two
weeks ago because of declining demands from other Energy Department
operations for the Fernald plant's uranium.
   In order to return to work, the unions agreed to separate pending
safety grievances with Westinghouse from the three-year contract,
which union members approved Saturday by a 3-to-1 ratio. The strike
began Oct. 7, halting production.
   For Monday's reorientation, union workers were bused from the
plant's 1,050-acre site to a suburban Cincinnati movie theater to
see a film. They returned Monday afternoon to the plant for
classroom sessions.
   Union workers are concerned about exposure to radioactive
materials, including uranium and plutonium, a weapons-grade
substance to which plant workers occasionally have been exposed in
handling wastes accepted for temporary storage from other plants.
   The unions plan to continue negotiations on a separate agreement
covering health and environmental issues. The contract approved
Saturday includes a new health insurance program, and no pay
increase. Under the agreement, workers may pursue up to 4,000 safety
and health grievances against Westinghouse, which initially offered
to pay workers $150 each to drop their grievances.
   Officials at the 37-year-old plant are under pressure from the
state and a lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court by plant
neighbors, to clean up thousands of pounds and barrels of toxic and
radioactive wastes stored on site.
   The Energy Department has pledged itself to a cleanup at the
plant that is estimated to cost $1 billion, and has begun some
cleanup work and studies. But political leaders, employees and
neighbors are concerned that a long-term report, issued last week by
the Energy Department, recommends closing Fernald in a few years.
Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, has said he thinks the cleanup will get a
higher priority if the plant remains open.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
