<HEAD>Biggest U.S. Corporate Takeovers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pillsbury Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd item, `Kraft, by...', to CORRECT that it completed,
sted just announced. Also moving on the financial wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the 15 biggest corporate takeover deals in U.S. history.
The list includes the acquired company, the principal acquirer, the
dollar value and the year completed, or the date the deal was
announced if still pending.
   _RJR Nabisco, by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts, $24.5 billion,
announced Nov. 30, 1988.
   _Gulf Oil, by Chevron, $13.4 billion, completed in 1984.
   _Kraft, by Philip Morris, $12.9 billion, completed in 1988.
   _Getty Oil, by Texaco, $10.1 billion, completed in 1984.
   _Standard Oil (45 percent), by British Petroleum (already held 55
percent), $7.9 billion, completed in 1987.
   _Conoco, by DuPont, $7.4 billion, completed in 1981.
   _Federated Department Stores, by Campeau, $6.58 billion,
completed in 1988.
   _Marathon Oil, by USX, $6.5 billion, completed in 1982.
   _RCA, by General Electric, $6.4 billion, completed in 1986.
   _Beatrice, by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts, $6.1 billion, completed in
1986.
   _Superior Oil, by Mobil, $5.7 billion, completed in 1984.
   _Shell Oil, (30.5 percent), by Royal Dutch-Shell (already held
69.5 percent), $5.7 billion, completed in 1985.
   _Pillsbury, by Grand Metropolitan, $5.68 billion, announced Dec.
18, 1988.
   _General Foods, by Philip Morris, $5.6 billion, completed in 1985.
   _Southern Pacific, by Santa Fe, $5.2 billion, completed in 1983.
(Later broken up by the Interstate Commerce Commission.)
