<1ST_LINE>r w AM-S&LRescue     12-19 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-S&L Rescue,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Gives $91 Million to California S&L to Save Two Ohio
Thrifts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators said Monday they are
contributing $91 million to an Oakland, Calif, savings institution
to rescue two Ohio S&Ls.
   The Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp., which insures
deposits up to $100,000 in the nation's 3,000 S&Ls, is providing
Golden West Financial Corp., one of the largest S&L holding
companies in the nation, with $91 million in cash. It also is
purchasing bad loans of the failed institutions for $29 million and
guaranteeing Golden West against some future loss.
   The FSLIC is receiving back 75 percent of the gains on some of
the loans owned by the failed institutions _ Ohio Valley Savings and
Loan Association, Steubenville, and First Border Savings Bank of
Piqua, which have $318 million in combined assets.
   Also, Golden West is paying $8 million over three years to FSLIC
in exchange for tax benefits created by the deal. In addition, it is
pumping $20 million into the acquired thrifts, whose six offices
reopened Monday as branches of World Savings and Loan of Ohio.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, the parent agency of the FSLIC,
blamed the failure of Ohio Valley to losses on ``a large volume of
out-of-state commercial real estate loans and unsecured commercial
loans.'' It attributed First Border's insolvency to ``excessive
growth and speculation in financial futures markets.''
   The bank board so far this year has ``resolved'' the cases of 159
failed S&Ls, a post-Depression record, mostly through assisted
mergers. Bank board Chairman M. Danny Wall has said he wants to
finish another 40 cases in the next two weeks to take advantage of
expiring tax breaks.
</TEXT>
