<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-19 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow in the West, Rain in Texas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Uncompahgre is cq in 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A winter storm over the Rocky Mountains on Monday produced snow
across much of the West, and rain was reported from the Texas
Panhandle through Oklahoma and into Kansas.
   Snow continued falling during the afternoon in the southern
mountains of Colorado, with between 4 and 8 inches accumulating in
the San Juan and Uncompahgre mountains. The snow caused poor
visibility and slippery roads.
   Rain and snow also continued in parts of New Mexico. The
combination of heavy rainfall and runoff from the mountains caused
some creeks to swell near Ruidoso, and minor flooding was reported.
   Winds gusted to 63 mph at Ruidoso and 58 mph at Albuquerque, and
snow advisories were posted for mountain areas of New Mexico.
   Areas of northern Arizona picked up some snow overnight and into
Monday morning. Flagstaff received 3 to 4 inches, and Pinetop and
Lakeside reported 2 inches along with blowing snow.
   Snow also fell in parts of Utah, where up to 7 inches was
reported in Provo, Orem and Springville.
   The storm also sent snow in the mountainous regions of northern
California, where snowfall totals were expected between 3 and 5
inches in the higher elevations.
   Elsewhere, a winter storm watch was posted for Tuesday in parts
of Michigan. Some areas of the Upper Peninsula could receive more
than 8 inches of snow, the National Weather Service said.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST
included more than a third of an inch at Sacramento, Calif.; a third
of an inch at Crescent City, Calif.; and over a quarter-inch at
Ukiah.
   Snowfall during the same six hours included an inch at Kalispell,
Mont., and Winnemucca, Nev.
   Temperatures early Monday tumbled to well below the freezing mark
in parts of northern Florida. Considerable damage was reported by
some vegetable growers, but the citrus crop escaped with little or
no damage.
   Temperatures were in the teens and 20s in New York, New England
and parts of the northern and central Rockies, and from North Dakota
across Minnesota and into upper Michigan.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 7
degrees at Jackson, Wyo., to 79 degrees at Alice, Texas. The
nation's low Monday morning was 20 degrees below zero at Jackson.
   For Tuesday, the forecast called for a low pressure area moving
across the Mississippi Valley to spread rain across the Ohio Valley
and into the lower Great Lakes, with snow in Minnesota and upper
Michigan. A cold front trailing south from the low was expected to
trigger rain showers and a few thunderstorms from eastern Texas to
Missouri.
   Snow was forecast in in Utah and northern Arizona, in inland area
of the Pacific Northwest, and in Maine; rain showers in the
remainder of New England; and rain on the Pacific Northwest coast.
   Highs in the teens and 20s were forecast for the Dakotas,
Minnesota, Michigan, Montana, much of Wyoming and southeast Idaho;
in the 30s and 40s from the Pacific Northwest across the Great
Basin, much of the central and southern Rockies, the central Plains
and much of the upper Great Lakes; and in the 50s and 60s in most of
the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
