<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Palme     12-19 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Palme,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palme's Widow Identified Murder Suspect, TV Claims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of assassinated Prime Minister
Olof Palme picked out of a police lineup a 41-year-old Swede
suspected of his murder, Swedish TV reported Monday.
   The Channel 2 news program ``Rapport'' quoted an unidentified,
``well-connected'' source close to the investigation as saying that
Mrs. Lisbet Palme identified Christer Petterson as the killer.
   Palme was shot from behind on Feb. 28, 1986, on a central
Stockholm street as he and his wife were walking home unguarded from
a movie after saying good night to their son Marten, who saw the
movie with them.
   According to the broadcast, the source said both Mrs. Palme and
her son identified the suspect with varying degrees of certainty,
but it gave no details.
   After the murder, the son reported having seen a man who appeared
to be following his parents.
   Petterson's lawyer, Arne Liljeros; the prosecutor, and police
heading the investigation said they had no comment on the TV report.
``Rapport'' did not say when the lineup took place, but it
apparently would have been either Sunday or Monday.
   Petterson, who has a long criminal record including a
manslaughter conviction, was arrested on Wednesday. He pleaded
innocent, but a district court judge found the prosecution had shown
reasonable grounds to suspect him of Palme's murder and ordered him
held for investigation.
   Both sides agreed, however, that publication of Petterson's
picture in the foreign press and the fact that nearly three years
passed since the shooting assassination weakened the value of
witness identification. No reports emerged of any admissions made
during interrogation or that the police uncovered more tangible
evidence, such as the revolver used in the shooting.
   A scandal stemming from the murder investigation ended Monday
when the state awarded partial payment of a private investigator's
bill.
   The amateur detective, book publisher Ebbe Carlsson, will get
$4,107 of a $200,875 expense account he submitted, the national TT
news agency reported.
   The disclosure of Carlsson's private search and his attempt to
smuggle illegal surveillance equipment into Sweden triggered a
political crisis for the governing Social Democratic government. It
forced the resignation last June of Justice Minister Anna-Greta
Leijon, who secretly backed the project.
</TEXT>
