<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Steinberg     12-19 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steinberg,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Technician Testifies Hairs Forcibly Removed From Lisa's Head</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hairs that were yanked out of Lisa Steinberg's
head were found entangled in clothing fibers of the man accused of
beating her to death, a police laboratory technician testified
Monday.
   Detective Francis Callery said he also found hair from Joel
Steinberg's former live-in companion, Hedda Nussbaum, on the
exercise bar police confiscated during a search of the couple's
Greenwich Village apartment.
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, testified two weeks ago that Steinberg beat her
on her legs and head with the bar.
   Steinberg, a 47-year-old disbarred lawyer, is charged with
second-degree murder in the fatal beating of Lisa, a child he and
Ms. Nussbaum illegally adopted shortly after her birth.
   Another prosecution witness, a neighbor of the couple, testified
Monday that she heard slapping and screaming at various times coming
from the Steinberg apartment before the night Lisa was fatally
injured.
   Lisa's death in an affluent, well-educated household attracted
wide attention and raised the issue of the responsibility of
neighbors, teachers and social workers to recognize and report
evidence of child abuse.
   Callery said the hair found in Steinberg's clothing ``in my
opinion, came from Lisa Steinberg.'' He added that for hair to be
entangled in clothing fibers ``there is usually some kind of
struggle.''
   Adrian DiLuzio, one of Steinberg's two lawyers, said outside the
courtroom after he cross-examined Callery that the technician's
testimony was irrelevant.
   ``You can't put any times on when the hair came off the head or
even the circumstances under which it came off,'' DiLuzio said.
   Lisa was removed unconscious from Steinberg's apartment the
morning of Nov. 2, 1987, and taken to a nearby hospital where she
died three days later.
   Steinberg denies that he hit the girl, but Ms. Nussbaum,
Steinberg's former live-in companion, said he told her the night
Lisa was fatally injured that he had ``knocked Lisa down and she
didn't want to get up.''
   The former neighbor who testified Monday, Joan Bonano, said she
called police three or four times after hearing yelling and sounds
of violence coming from the Steinberg apartment two floors above her
ground-floor flat.
   ``I heard noises like slapping, screaming, loud male voices, like
yelling,'' she testified.
   Mrs. Bonano also testifed that Ms. Nussbaum appeared increasingly
battered in the years before Lisa died, and that by November 1987,
Ms. Nussbaum was limping. Charges against Ms. Nussbaum were dropped
after prosecutors concluded she was too badly battered to have
prevented Lisa's death.
</TEXT>
