<DOCNO> AP881219-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1937EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-S&Ls-Homeless     12-19 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-S&Ls-Homeless,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Regulators Offer Cities Foreclosed Properties To House
Homeless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators said Monday they are
offering to make foreclosed properties from failed savings
institutions available to house the homeless in a half dozen cities.
   Karl Hoyle, a spokesman for Federal Home Loan Bank Board Chairman
M. Danny Wall, said the agency, which regulates the nation's 3,000
S&Ls, is talking with six or seven cities in Texas and in the North
and Midwest. He declined to identify them.
   Hoyle said the bank board would lend the properties _ in some
cases commercial buildings near soup kitchens _ to municipal
governments, which in turn would pay to administer them as temporary
shelters.
   ``That ball is in their court at this juncture. They have to
decide if they have the funds,'' he said. ``We would like to get it
done in the winter when this housing would be most useful to the
homeless.''
   Discussions with the cities started several months ago, Hoyle
said. Another effort, to persuade private groups to purchase
foreclosed homes from the bank board and rehabilitate them for poor
families, began about a year ago, he said.
   Wall disclosed the homeless initiative in a speech to a group
called the National Housing Conference on the same day that
President-elect Bush, in announcing the appointment of Rep. Jack
Kemp, R-N.Y., as secretary of housing and urban development, said
his administration would seek innovative solutions to the problem of
homelessness.
   On another topic, Hoyle said the bank board late Monday forwarded
to the Treasury Department the outline of a plan for a ``reinsurance
agency'' that would serve as a mechanism for channeling funds to the
ailing S&L industry.
   The bank board's insurance fund, the Federal Savings and Loan
Insurance Corp., has been paying for a record number of S&L rescues
this year through its normal income, primarily an assessment on
still-operating institutions.
   Wall has argued previously that the fees paid by S&Ls to the
FSLIC, as well as by banks and credit unions to separate insurance
funds, were meant to cover a ``normal'' level of failures, not the
``catastrophic'' level of the current thrift crisis.
   Through Monday, regulators said they have resolved the cases of
159 insolvent thrifts this year. More than 400 insolvent S&Ls remain
open and hundreds of others are close to insolvency.
   According to an administration source, who declined to be named,
the Treasury Department estimates the cost of restoring the thrift
industry to health at $60 billion to $75 billion if interest rates
remain unchanged and as high as $105 billion if interest rates
increase by 2 percentage points.
   The reinsurance agency would have oversight over three insurance
funds _ for banks, S&Ls and credit unions. It could collect premiums
from all three agencies, using it when one of the funds got in
trouble. It also could serve as the mechanism for further borrowing
to pay for the thrift crisis or as the conduit for any money
Congress wanted to spend on the cleanup.
   Bank board member Lawrence White, in an interview, said the
proposal leaves open who will pay for the S&L cleanup and whether
the new agency's expenditures would be counted toward the budget
deficit.
   ``I don't think it is intended to a back door way off getting
them (banks and credit unions) to pay for the FSLIC's current
problems,'' White said. ``The concept is both a funding mechanism
and a forward looking means of dealing with catastrophic costs'' in
the future.
   Meanwhile, The New York Times reported in weekend editions that
the Reagan administration, in its 1990 budget, will acknowledge for
the first time that some taxpayer money must be spent on the problem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881219-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1944EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PLO-Dissent     12-19 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO-Dissent,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Executive Committee Member Disagrees With Arafat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Arafat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICK LUDINGTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the PLO's executive committee
said Monday that PLO leader Yasser Arafat's statements which led to
PLO-U.S. talks were only ``Arafat's personal opinion.''
   The statement could represent a serious policy split within the
ranks of the governing body of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   In Jerusalem, Israeli Premier Yitzhak Shamir told a conference on
the Nazi Holocaust on Monday that the latest PLO statements about
peace were a trick and said worldwide support for Israel was needed
to prevent ``a future holocaust.''
   Shamir said the United States and West Europe were deluded into
accepting the PLO and vowed that Israel would never negotiate with
the PLO, an umbrella organization which includes Arafat's mainstream
Fatah group. Shamir says the PLO is made up of terrorists bent on
driving Israel into the sea.
   Mustafa el-Zibri, a member of the PLO executive committee, said
Arafat's statements in Geneva explicitly recognizing Israel's right
to exist and renouncing all forms of terrorism, were ``incompatible
with the resolutions of the latest Palestine National Council
meeting.''
   He signed the statement with his guerrilla name, Abu Ali Mustafa.
The statement was telefaxed from Damascus, Syria, to The Associated
Press office in Nicosia. The office of the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine in Damascus confirmed that he issued the
statement.
   The statement could represent serious dissent because of Zibri's
seat on the PLO's 15-member governing body, which includes
representatives of six Palestinian guerrilla groups as well as
independents. Fatah has three seats.
   Zibri is the sole committee representative of the Popular Front,
a Marxist group headed by George Habash. It was not known
immediately whether Habash endorsed his statement.
   The Palestine National Council, the PLO's legislative arm, met in
Algeria last month to declare an independent Palestinian state. It
implicitly recognized Israel's existence and renounced terrorism,
but it said it would continue attacking Israeli military targets in
the occupied territories.
   Habash later told Arafat, ``We're backing your efforts because
this is what the majority wants. But we don't believe moderation
will pay.''
   Arafat said Wednesday that the PLO recognizes the right of all
parties to the Middle East conflict ``to exist in peace and security
... including the state of Palestine, Israel and other neighbors.''
   He also said, ``We totally and absolutely renounce all forms of
terrorism, including individual terrorism, group and state
terrorism.'' He uses the term ``state terrorism'' to refer to
activities by the Israeli defense forces.
   His statements led to a U.S. announcement that the PLO met U.S.
conditions for direct contact and to the opening of U.S.-PLO talks
in Tunisia on Friday.
   Habash said Thursday the U.S. decision was only taken to end
American isolation and said ``we urge our masses to keep up the
struggle to force Israel and the United States to recognize the
state of Palestine.''
   Zibry's statement Monday said, ``The statements made by ...
(Arafat) in Geneva were incompatible with the resolutions of the
latest PNC meeting and he (Arafat) expressed only his personal
opinion.''
   ``His statements only whetted the U.S. appetite to extort
(concessions from) the Palestinian revolution and the PLO. The
United States is still seeking to scuttle the intefadeh,'' he said,
using the Arabic word for the year-old uprising of Palestinians in
the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza strip.
   ``We shall continue to exercise our legitimate rights ... in
struggling against the occupation with all means available,
including armed struggle, until ... establishment of the independent
Palestinian state on soil of the homeland.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
