<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile-Novelist     12-19 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Novelist,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Best-Selling Novelist Allende Visits Homeland for First Time in 13
Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Novelist Isabel Allende declared Monday
that the defeat of military President Augusto Pinochet in a
political referendum was ``an historic moment'' and that democracy
has been restored to Chile.
   She made the comments at a news conference in Santiago during her
first trip back to her homeland after 13 years of self-imposed exile.
   The author of the best-selling ``House of the Spirits'' also said
Pinochet is a dictator like others who have ruled Latin American
countries.
   ``I'm not really interested in talking about him personally
because he's no different from other cases and is not a particularly
interesting person.''
   However, she said she wept when she learned in October that
Chileans rejected by 3.9 million to 3.1 million a proposal that Gen.
Pinochet remain in power until 1997.
   ``I believe the silent decision that every Chilean made on Oct. 5
is an historic moment in the return of democracy,'' she said.
   She was in Venezuela at the time and telephoned Santiago to
discuss the results with Hortensia Allende, widow of ousted civilian
President Salvador Allende. ``We couldn't talk, we just cried,'' she
said.
   Mrs. Allende's father was a cousin of Salvador Allende, the
Marxist who died when Pinochet toppled his elected government in a
bloody 1973 coup.
   Pinochet's referendum defeat obliged him to call elections for
next December. He is to hand over power in March 1990.
   Mrs. Allende, 46, has written three novels since she left Chile
in 1975 for self-exile in Venezuela, where she remained for 13
years. This year, she moved to San Francisco.
   She returned to Chile on Saturday for a two-week visit with
family and said of her homeland: ``It feels the same, like not a day
has passed.''
   But she said she had no plans to re-establish residence in the
country.
   She said that while abroad ``every time I've had a chance to talk
publicly about Chile and condemn the dictatorship I've done so.''
   ``I believe my mission ends with the arrival of democracy in
Chile,'' she said, adding: ``I believe it has arrived.''
   Mrs. Allende said she now is preparing a book of short stories,
including material culled from her third and latest novel, ``Eva
Luna.'' The book describes the experiences of an uneducated but
savvy peasant girl who seeks her fortune in a Venezuelan city.
   ``House of the Spirits,'' which was published in more than a
dozen languages, is the saga of several generations of a Chilean
family living in Santiago.
   Asked to comment on critics who compare her work with that of
renowned Colombian author Gabriel Garcia Marquez, she quipped:
``This must make Garcia Marquez unhappy.''
   She said she is influenced by Garcia Marquez and Pablo Neruda,
the late Nobel Prize-winning Chilean poet. She said her work and
Garcia Marquez' share only a style known as ``magical realism''
which mixes fantasy with reality.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
