<1ST_LINE>u i AM-France-Blast     12-19 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Blast,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Explosions Wreck Immigrant Housing, Kill One, Wound 12</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto CAN2</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   CAGNES-SUR-MER, France (AP) _ Two explosions wrecked a home for
immigrant workers Monday on the French Riviera, killing one resident
and injuring 12, police said. Authorities said they found evidence
that may link the blasts to Jewish extremists.
   They said the first pre-dawn blast demolished a car parked at the
entrance of the building, which housed 97 people, mostly North
African immigrants. Residents were rushing outside when a second
explosion minutes later ripped through a stairwell, killing a
Romanian immigrant.
   The victim was identified as Georghe Yordachescu, 50, a delivery
driver who had lived there about four years.
   Firemen said they found written tracts in the rubble from an
extreme right-wing Jewish group called Masada. The writings
contained the words ``Islam Must Be Beaten.''
   Tracts from Masada, named after a mountaintop fortress in Israel
held by Jews against Roman legions, were found last June outside
another immigrants' residence in nearby Nice when a bomb was
defused, police said.
   However, no explicit claim of responsibility was made by any
organization for Monday's explosions.
   The first blast hurled chunks of the parked car up to 300 feet
away, destroyed four other cars and damaged numerous vehicles. The
concussion broke windows in nearby buildings.
   President Francois Mitterrand condemned the attack, saying:
``Once again, the cowardice of a few struck immigrant workers. This
violence must be denounced and fought with the greatest firmness.''
   Foreign immigrants, especially those from North Africa, have
often been made targets of resentment and prejudice in France.
   An employee of a transportation company next door to the
residence reported, ``We were drinking coffee with a colleague when
the explosion blew out the door and all of the windows. We ran
outside and we saw that terrified residents of the center wanted to
jump from the windows.
   ``We shouted to them to remain in the building and we approached
it to help them. It was at that moment that the second explosion
happened. I was thrown 10 meters (about 33 feet) and my colleague
was hit full in the head by a piece of flying metal.''
   Six of those hurt required hospitalization. Cagnes-sur-Mer is
about six miles west of Nice on the French Riviera.
   The ground floor was badly damaged. Dozens of rooms were
destroyed and enormous pieces of concrete were sent flying.
   Some of those hurt suffered broken bones and cuts. Some had
jumped from the windows.
   Residents regrouped around a fire built in front of the building.
   ``We never received any threats,'' one said. ``Everything was
just fine at the center. We don't understand this attack.''
</TEXT>
