<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MineExplosion     12-19 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mine Explosion,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Killed When Boiler Explodes at Mine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN MANUEL, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boiler at a copper mine exploded
Monday, killing one man and injuring two others, authorities said.
   The boiler at Magma Copper Co.'s new smelter was being cleaned
when it exploded, said Sandra Gerdon, Magma's assistant industrial
relations officer.
   Ronald Riggs, 47, of San Manuel, a Magma engineer, was killed in
the explosion.
   Eric Walker, 34, an employee of N.B. Harty General Contractors of
Dexter, Mo., was listed in critical condition at Tucson Medical
Center, where he was being treated for burns, said Pinal County
Sheriff's Cpl. Leonard Holcombe.
   The other injured man, Daryl Stepp, was treated at the San Manuel
Health Center and released, Holcombe said. He also worked for the
contracting company.
   San Manuel is about 45 miles northeast of Tucson in southern
Arizona.
   The contracting company was working to dislodge waste buildup
within a boiler at the company's new $150 million furnace complex,
Ms. Gerdon said.
   The federal Occupational Safety and Health Administration is
investigating the explosion.
   Magma completed installation of a $150 million Finnish-built
state-of-the-art flash furnace complex earlier this year, and fired
it up during the summer.
   Bob Savedra, treasurer and smelter safety representative for
Steelworkers Local 937, said a furnace had been shut down for the
last week to clean a buildup of material inside the boiler.
</TEXT>
