<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CougarReward     12-19 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cougar Reward,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Offer Reward In Death of Three Cougars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reward of nearly $7,000 was announced
Monday in hopes of finding out who is responsible for the deaths of
three cougars that were part of a program to re-establish endangered
Florida panthers.
   U.S. Rep. Bill Grant said that he and state and private game
officials hope to raise more money to get the reward up to $10,000.
   Three of five cougars caught in Texas and released into the
Osceola National Forest in June have died, threatening the
state-federal program aimed at finding a new habitat for Florida
panthers.
   Hunters have been blamed in two of the cougar deaths, while the
cause of the third death could not be determined, said Tom Logan,
chief of wildlife research for the game and fish commission.
   The two remaining cougars are believed to be in good health.
   Fewer than 30 panthers are believed to be remaining in the swamps
and scrubland of central and southern Florida, as their natural
habitat is chipped away by development.
   That is why wildlife authorities are attempting to establish
panthers in the Osceola forest in north-central Florida. They
brought the five cougars, which have habits similar to those of the
endangered panthers, to the forest to see how well they adapt.
   State officials have no firm leads in the deaths but expect the
reward money may help, said Woody Darden, spokesman for the Florida
Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission.
   ``We think at this point, the only real possibility of getting a
conviction is if somebody comes forward,'' said Darden. ``Most of
the time when people do something like this, they're going to talk
about it.''
   Conviction of killing one of the cougars carries a possible
prison sentence of five years and fine of up to $5,000.
</TEXT>
