<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Rebels-Colombia     12-19 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rebels-Colombia,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Leftist Guerrilla Group Wants to be Political Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of Colombia's leftist guerrilla
groups wants to abandon armed rebellion and become a political
party, a Bogota newspaper reported on Monday.
   The report in the daily El Siglo follows President Virgilio
Barco's Sept. 1 offer of freedom of political activity to leftist
rebel bands who give up armed revolt.
   El Siglo quoted Sen. Ricardo Villa Salcedo as saying the April 19
Movement, or M-19, has proposed immediate talks with the government
and that the group wants to disband and organize a party within six
months.
   ``The conditions are right for achieving an agreement between the
government and the M-19 in the next three months,'' Villa Salcedo
was quoted as saying.
   The Associated Press tried to call Villa Salcedo at his office,
but there was no answer. Parliament adjourned last week.
   In the last two months, El Siglo has been the medium for several
announcements by leftist guerrilla groups proposing peace talks with
the government.
   Earlier this year, M-19 kidnapped Alvaro Gomez Hurtado,
Colombia's leading member of the Conservative Party and owner of El
Siglo, who ran against Barco for president two years ago.
   He was released after two weeks with a message from M-19 that it
was interested in peace talks with the government.
   Last week, Barco told the final session of Parliament that
members of his Cabinet have been in direct contact with M-19.
   M-19 made its proposal during such contacts this month, El Siglo
quoted Villa Salcedo as saying.
   The senator and Barco both belong to the governing Liberal Party.
   Right-wing death squads have ravaged the ranks of a political
party that was organized three years ago with the help of rebels
from the Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces. The squads killed 800
members of that party, the Patriotic Union, including its president,
Jaime Pardo Leal.
   The Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces made known last month
through another federal senator that it, too, would like to enter
into peace talks with the government.
   Two other rebel groups, the People's Liberation Army and the
National Liberation Army, said in communiques they will never give
up trying to overthrow the government.
   Those two groups launched a major offensive last January.
   There are an estimated 10,000 leftist guerrillas in Colombia.
   M-19 has been inactive for the last six months. It takes its name
from the date of a 1970 presidential election that dissidents say
was fraudulent.
   M-19's bloodiest operation was seizing the Supreme Court building
in Bogota in 1985. The army retook the building, but 11 Supreme
Court justices and 85 other people were killed.
</TEXT>
