<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RishSentencing     12-19 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rish Sentencing,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rish Sentenced To Life For Kidnap, Murder Of Businessman Stephen
Small</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANKAKEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman described by prosecutors as a
gold-digger who helped bury businessman Stephen Small alive in hopes
of sharing a $1 million ransom was sentenced Monday to life in
prison without parole.
   Nancy Rish was convicted Nov. 2 of murder and kidnapping for her
role in the 1987 abduction of Small, member of a prominent
publishing family, who suffocated in a homemade wooden box before
the money could be collected.
   Ms. Rish, 26, cried and hugged her mother when Circuit Judge John
Michela pronounced the sentence after a hearing in Kankakee County
Circuit Court.
   Her boyfriend, Daniel Edwards, was convicted of murder and
kidnapping in May and sentenced to die, but prosecutors said Ms.
Rish was not eligible for the death penalty.
   ``There was not one grain of remorse, not one grain of salt in
the tears of this woman for Stephen Small and his family,''
prosecutor Michael Ficaro, an assistant Illinois attorney general,
told the judge.
   Ms. Rish told Michela that witnesses against her lied and her
conviction was unfair. ``I just want to say I'm not guilty of those
charges and I never was,'' she said.
   Small, 40, was kidnapped Sept. 2, 1987 and buried in the box in a
remote area between Kankakee and the Indiana border. His body was
unearthed two days later.
   Small's late father was head of Mid-America Media Group, whose
broadcasting properties included 11 radio stations, and his uncle
was head of Small Newspapers Inc., and editor and publisher of the
Kankakee Daily Journal.
   Ficaro contended that Edwards and Ms. Rish wanted a lot of money,
``the big score,'' and decided kidnapping Small was the way to get
it. However, the defense maintained that Edwards' real accomplices
never were apprehended.
   During the trial, the jury saw photos of Small's body inside the
box, and heard chilling tapes of a kidnapper warning that Small
would die if the ransom was not paid. The ransom was never paid
because Small's wife could not understand the delivery instructions
on the muffled tape recording played to her over the telephone.
</TEXT>
