<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 2148EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Angola     12-19 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Angola,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Asks for 70 Peacekeepers to Oversee Cuban Withdrawal
from Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
on Monday asked the Security Council to approve a 70-member
peacekeeping force to monitor the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops
from Angola.
   The council is expected to give its approval by Thursday for the
U.N. Angola Verification Mission, which a report by the
secretary-general said would cost about $20.4 million during the
31-month phased pullout.
   Cuba and Angola are expected to sign on Thursday a final pact to
cooperate with the force and a final agreement with South Africa on
the southern Africa peace plan.
   Under the plan, South Africa is to allow independence to
South-West Africa, the former German colony known as Namibia; Cuban
troops are to withdraw from Angola, and South African troops from
Angola and Namibia. South Africa has controlled Namibia in defiance
of a 1966 U.N. resolution demanding the territory's independence.
   The 70-member U.N. force Perez de Cuellar asked for is separate
and officially unrelated to a much larger force of 7,500
peacekeepers and 2,000 military police and civilian administrators
planned to monitor Namibian independence.
   Perez de Cuellar's report did not suggest which nations would
provide military observers for the unarmed force.
   But Foreign Minister Francisco Fernandez Ordonez of Spain was
quoted by a Madrid newspaper as saying his country has agreed to
send troops to Angola and Namibia.
   U.S. spy satellites are expected to provide much of the
intelligence data that South Africa insists on during the Cuban
withdrawal.
   Angola's state news agency quoted President Jose Eduardo dos
Santos as saying that Perez de Cuellar is trying to create a fund to
finance the Cuban withdrawal.
   In a meeting in Havana with Cuban leader Fidel Castro, dos Santos
said it would cost about $800 million, the agency said.
   Cuban troops went to Angola in 1975 to help the Marxist
government fight attacks by South African forces and U.S.-backed
rebels of the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola.
   In a statement issued from their Lisbon headquarters Monday, the
rebels claimed they killed 13 Angolan soldiers and captured the
northwestern Angola town of Ucua, in Luanda province, last week.
   The rebels said they killed eight government soldiers Thursday
when they attacked a military column in the southern Huila province
and destroyed 12 tons of arms.
   One rebel died and seven were injured in the clashes, they said.
   There was no way to immediately verify claims of the rebels, who
are not party to the U.S.-sponsored peace agreement.
</TEXT>
