<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ChicagoMayoral 1stLd-Writethru a0701 12-19 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicago Mayoral, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0701,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>18 In Race for Chicago Mayor; Former Mayor Byrne Not Among Them</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT number of Republicans in race to 11 sted
9; INSERTS 1 graf after 9th graf pvs, `Other Democratic...', to add
detail on some Republican candidates. Picks up 10th graf pvs,
`Winning the...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK PERKISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven Democrats and 11 Republicans are now seeking
the mayor's office in Chicago, but the rumored candidacy of former
Mayor Jane Byrne did not materialize before the Monday deadline for
filing nomination petitions.
   Mrs. Byrne, a Democrat who was the city's mayor from 1979 to
1983, had been reported in recent days to be a potential Republican
candidate. But her daughter, Kathy, showed up at the Board of
Election Commissioners minutes before the deadline Monday with a
denial.
   ``Jane Byrne is not a candidate. Merry Christmas,'' Kathy Byrne
told reporters, then departed.
   Edward Vrdolyak, a former Democratic powerhouse turned Republican
who was also said to be thinking about running, sent an aide to tell
reporters minutes before the filing deadline that he, too, wasn't
interested.
   ``Leaders in the Republican Party urged me to consider a
candidacy and I did so as a courtesy to my party,'' Vrdolyak said in
a statement. ``Instead, I will concentrate my time and energy on my
law practice and on assisting to build the Republican Party in
Chicago and Cook County.''
   That left the Republicans without a big-name candidate for the
Feb. 28 primary.
   On the Democratic side, Mayor Eugene Sawyer, named to the post by
the city council after Harold Washington died in November 1987,
squared off against a field that included Cook County State's
Attorney Richard M. Daley, son of the legendary Mayor Richard J.
Daley, and Alderman Timothy Evans.
   Though the deadline for primary candidates ended Monday,
independent candidates have until mid-January to file for the
remaining two years in Washington's second term.
   Other Democratic candidates are aldermen Lawrence Bloom and Juan
Soliz; former state Sen. James Taylor; and Sheila A. Jones, a
follower of political extremist Lyndon LaRouche.
   Republican candidates include Herbert Sohn, a physician-lawyer
who ran unsuccessfully three times against veteran U.S. Rep. Sidney
Yates; Kenneth R. Hurst, who filed an unsuccessful lawsuit to try to
get the election put off until 1989; and John J. Holowinski, a
former Democrat employed by the city's Department of Economic
Development.
   Winning the Democratic primary has been tantamount to winning the
general election in Chicago's recent history, although a white
Republican made a strong showing against Washington, the city's
first black mayor.
   Mrs. Byrne was derailed in a 1983 re-election bid when she and
Daley split the white vote, making Washington the Democratic
candidate. He went on to win the general election and become the
city's first black mayor.
   The racial issue remains alive in the 1988 campaign. Sawyer and
Evans, who are black, are battling to represent the black community,
although Daley has begun campaigning hard for the black vote. Evans
has criticized Sawyer and said he is Washington's true political
heir.
   The city's population is a little more than 40 percent white, 40
percent black, 15 percent Hispanic and less than 5 percent of other
races.
</TEXT>
