<2ND_LINE>AM-US-PLO, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0667,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Says It Will Assess PLO on `Case-by-Case' Basis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th graf pvs bgng, `Our struggle,' and
ADDS 4 grafs at end to UPDATE with statement by member of PLO
executive committee saying Arafat's comments were just his own
personal opinion; NO pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department, which last week opened
talks with the Palestine Liberation Organization, said Monday it
would judge PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat's renunciation of terrorism
on a ``case-by-case'' basis.
   ``Terrorism has been renounced in words,'' spokeswoman Phyllis
Oakley said. ``We shall see what happens now.''
   Mrs. Oakley declined to comment directly on an assertion by Salah
Khalaf of the PLO that Arafat's renunciation of terrorism ``in all
forms'' did not include military attacks against Israel.
   ``Our struggle will continue until we raise the PLO flag over
Jerusalem,'' Khalaf, known also as Abu Iyad, said Sunday. He is
second-in-command to Arafat in Fatah, the mainstream body of the PLO.
   A member of the PLO executive committee, Mustafa el-Zibri, said
in a statement Monday that Arafat's statements explicitly
recognizing Israel's right to exist and renouncing all forms of
terrorism were ``incompatible with the resolutions of the latest
Palestine National Council meeting,'' and they were just Arafat's
``personal opinion.''
   Zibri's statement could represent a serious policy split within
the ranks of the 15-member governing body of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, which includes representatives of six
Palestinian guerrilla groups as well as independents.
   Meanwhile, President-elect Bush said Monday in a brief exchange
with reporters that ``we would not start off by showing any
tolerance of PLO terror and I don't care if it comes from a faction
of the left or right or the center or whatever. ... I am concerned
about it; I have been and will continue to be concerned about it.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater declined comment on
Khalaf's remarks, saying, ``I don't need to tell you of the
commotion that this development has made in Middle Eastern affairs,
and we just aren't going to prejudice the process in any way at this
point.''
   Arafat's renunciation of terrorism at a news conference Wednesday
in Geneva was one of the reasons cited by Secretary of State George
P. Shultz for deciding to hold U.S. talks with the PLO.
   This reversed a 13-year ban and dismayed Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir and other Israeli officials as a regrettable move that would
not advance prospects for peace in the area.
   The first U.S. session with the PLO was held Friday in Carthage,
an ancient city near Tunis founded by the Phoenicians. Mrs. Oakley
said ``we have no further meetings planned at this point.''
   On Saturday, Assistant Secretary of State Richard W. Murphy said
the ``dialogue'' with the PLO would be suspended in the event of
terrorism incidents that were traceable to the group.
   ``We would look at all this on a case-by-case basis,'' Mrs.
Oakley said. ``And I am not going to get into the area of
speculation about what specific views we might have.''
   At the same time, she said the Reagan administration was ``deeply
concerned'' about an upsurge of violence on the Israeli-held West
Bank. Troops killed three Palestinian Arabs on Sunday, raising to
eight the death toll over a bloody weekend. Authorities said Arabs
stoned three Jewish residents, including a 9-month-old girl and
4-year-old boy.
   Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said the U.S. move toward
the PLO had ``given legitimization to the uprising in the
territories.''
   Mrs. Oakley said there was no way to determine if the increased
violence was linked to the U.S. decision to meet with the PLO, which
Israel contends is behind the attacks on Israeli troops and settlers.
   However, the U.S. official admonished Israel not to engage in
``excessive use of force'' on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   Zibri's statement, issued from Damascus, Syria, said Arafat's
statements in Geneva ``expressed only his personal opinion.'' He
signed the statement with his guerrilla name, Abu Ali Mustafa.
   ``His statements only whetted the U.S. appetite to extort
(concessions from) the Palestinian revolution and the PLO,'' Zibri
said. ``We shall continue to exercise our legitimate rights ... in
struggling against the occupation with all means available,
including armed struggle, until ... establishment of the independent
Palestinian state on soil of the homeland.''
   Zibri is the sole representative on the executive committee from
the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a Marxist group
headed by George Habash. It was not known immediately whether Habash
endorsed his statement.
   State Department spokeswoman Nancy Beck declined comment Monday
night on Zibri's statement.
</TEXT>
