<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PolygamistTrial     12-19 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polygamist Trial,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polygamist Clan Murder Trial Goes To The Jury</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Addam is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COALVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a polygamist clan ``declared
war'' on the outside world when he began the confrontation that
ended in the death of a law officer, a prosecutor said Monday as the
case went to the jury.
   A jury retired for the evening after starting deliberations in
the trial of three clan members charged with second-degree murder in
the death of Utah Corrections Lt. Fred House, killed Jan. 28 during
a shootout that climaxed a 13-day standoff.
   In closing arguments, prosecutor Creighton Horton told state
district court jurors that clan patriarch Addam Swapp, 27; his
brother, Jonathan Swapp, 21; and brother-in-law, John Timothy
Singer, 22, deliberately chose a course of confrontation that led to
bloodshed.
   House was killed and Addam Swapp seriously wounded when the
shootout ended the police standoff at the clan's Marion farm. The
standoff began Jan. 16, when Addam Swapp bombed a Mormon chapel.
   Addam Swapp ``basically declared war on the church, state and
nation'' when he bombed the chapel, Horton said. Swapp contended he
was divinely inspired to commit the bombing, but Horton dismissed
the clan leader's claims.
   ``God didn't place those weapons in their hands. He didn't place
them around the house, he didn't load them, he didn't take the
safeties off, he didn't put his finger on the trigger and he didn't
fire,'' Horton said.
   Addam Swapp's attorney, John Bucher, countered that just because
clan members were well-armed did not mean they intended to use their
weapons.
   Singer has acknowleged firing the fatal bullet from his bedroom
window, but he maintains he was firing at the police dogs that House
was directing, not at the officer himself.
   Bill Morrison, Swapp's other lawyer, said his client has a
``deeply held religious belief in the sanctity of human life'' and
cried, ``Oh, Tim, why did you do it?'' after singer fired the shot.
   But prosecutor Dave Schwendiman said Singer and the Swapp
brothers had willfully and knowingly prolonged the confrontation and
could have accepted a peaceful compromise at any time during the
siege.
   The confrontation at the farm began after Singer and the Swapp
brothers bombed a nearby Mormon chapel on Jan. 16, the ninth
anniversary of the death of Singer's father, John Singer.
   John Singer's widow, Vickie, says her husband's death was the
result of a conspiracy between state authorities and church
officials angry at his open practice of polygamy and refusal to send
his children to public schools. The Mormon church officially
abandoned polygamy in 1890.
</TEXT>
