<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary     12-19 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Parties To Contest 1990 Elections Under New Constitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A law allowing political parties will be
adopted before parliamentary elections in 1990, but until then no
new parties will be permitted in Hungary, a junior minister said
Monday.
   Geza Kilenyi, the deputy justice minister, told reporters an
11-member constitutional court will be set up next year and will be
the only state organ competent to rule whether a political party is
constitutional or not.
   Parliament begins a winter session Tuesday that reportedly could
extend beyond the Christmas holidays _ extremely unusual in a
communist country.
   Hungary's parliament has grown increasingly lively this year,
with many deputies questioning the legislature's traditional
rubber-stamp role.
   Government spokesman Gyoergy Marosan said parliament's 15-point
agenda includes the 1989 budget and long-awaited laws on assembly
and association that will recognize, in principle, the right of
citizens to form political parties.
   Kilenyi said the law may not be considered until January because
of the large agenda.
   It is part of the government's ``package plan for democracy,''
including laws for a new constitution, presented to parliament last
month by Minister of State Imre Pozsgay, a leading reformer.
   The law on associations was ``a step forward,'' Kilenyi said,
that is needed to clear up ``legal uncertainties'' plaguing the
government and dozens of independent interest groups, associations
and trade unions that have mushroomed this year.
   Although these groups are legal, as their establishment does not
run counter to the constitution, there are no laws defining how an
organization can be established, what body is empowered to register
it or who is to exercise control over its operation, he said.
   A separate law would regulate the actual establishment,
registration and legal control of political parties.
   Referring to objections expressed by independent groups who feel
the associations laws should also apply to parties, Kilenyi
explained the party law would be directly linked to the new
constitution, likely to be adopted in 1990.
   The new constitution will not be committed to either a single or
multiparty system but also will not declare ``the leading role of
any party,'' Kilenyi said, referring to the traditional role of the
governing Communist Party.
   Still, it would leave no doubt that Hungary is a ``socialist
society,'' he said.
   A first draft of the party law is to be completed by Feb. 15,
Kilenyi said, but it would not be passed before the new constitution
is adopted. That is expected only by mid-1990, when elections are
scheduled.
   Among the communist states, Hungary always has been comparatively
tolerant of cultural freedoms and small enterprise.
</TEXT>
