<2ND_LINE>AM-Ceiling Collapse, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0684,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>32 Hurt at School When Part of Cafeteria Ceiling Collapses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with quotes and detail; CORRECTS number of injured
to 32 sted 29; CORRECTS names of hospitals to St. Luke's sted St.
Lukes and Marian sted Marion</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A school cafeteria's ceiling partially
collapsed Monday as pupils were eating lunch, and 32 were injured by
falling debris, authorities said.
   ``I heard it and looked up and then I saw it was cracked,'' said
13-year-old Carmell Suduth. She said she began running after hearing
a cracking sound and smelling dust.
   ``Something told me not to turn back,'' she said.
   None of the approximately 190 eighth-graders at West Middle
School was believed seriously hurt although several were treated at
hospitals and three were admitted.
   Officials at the school said material from one corner of the
ceiling came tumbling down. Students were struck by falling plaster
and a light fixture. The cafeteria is in the older section of the
70-year-old building.
   The school was evacuated and structural experts were called to
make sure the rest of the building was safe.
   Superintendent of Schools Thomas Brown said classes were called
off for the afternoon, and there would be no classes Tuesday. There
was no indication on what caused the collapse.
   Steve Molden said he shielded another student and took a blow
instead when he saw a chunk of plaster coming down.
   ``I was real shocked,'' he said. ``I saw a piece was going to hit
a girl who had already fallen down. I dove to prevent the piece from
hitting her and it hit me.''
   One student was listed in guarded condition and another in good
condition at St. Luke's Regional Medical Center. A spokesman for
Marian Health Center said another student was being kept there for
observation, but had not been formally admitted. The 29 other
injured students were treated at the two hospitals and released.
