<HEAD>Arafat Says He Is Confident Of Bush ``Professionalism''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Arafat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chairman Yasser Arafat hopes to be able one day
to turn to President-elect George Bush and call him ``brother
president,'' the Italian daily La Stampa quoted him as saying in an
interview released Monday.
   La Stampa correspondent Igor Mann said the Palestine Liberation
Organization leader told him recently in Tunis that ``in politics
one can believe only in onself and not much else.''
   But according to the interview, to be published in Tuesday's
editions, Arafat seemed to hold out hope for dealings with the Bush
administration.
   ``I say that President Bush is a professional, a WASP who has
behind him a nation born from an anti-colonial intefadeh,'' it
quoted him as saying, in an allusion to the Palestinian uprising in
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The United States last week reversed a 13-year ban on official
contacts with the PLO after Arafat renounced terrorism and accepted
Israel's right to exist. A meeting between PLO executive committee
member Yasser Abd Rabbo and U.S. Ambassador Robert Pelletreau took
place Friday in the Tunisian capital.
   U.S. officials have indicated the talks will not continue until
after Bush takes office on Jan. 20.
   ``I do not hold excessive illusions, the future is still to be
built,'' Arafat was quoted as saying. ``But I am confident in the
good sense of the American people, the famous common sense of Tom
Paine. I wish one day to be able to turn to Bush and call him
`brother president.'''
</TEXT>
