<2ND_LINE>AM-Rape Ordeal,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawsuit Alleges Neglect by Police Who Waited Outside As Girl Was
Raped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose 12-year-old daughter was raped in
her home as police waited outside for nearly half an hour filed a
lawsuit Monday against the officers and the cities that employ them,
a lawyer said.
   The lawsuit, which also names the man charged in the attack,
claims that the officials were ``intentional and reckless and
callously indifferent to the rights of the family'' when they did
not act to save the girl and her brother from attack, said Edward T.
Stein, an attorney for the family.
   On Dec. 20, 1987, police waited outside the family's Calumet City
apartment before rescuing the girl, even though her mother had
escaped and was begging police to go inside, the lawsuit states.
   The woman's 10-year-old son was also inside, and was ``slapped
around'' by the intruder, who repeatedly raped the girl, Stein said.
The civil lawsuit asks for an unspecified amount in damages, naming
only the minimum amount of $15,000, he said.
   Named as defendants are the suburb of Calumet City, former city
policeman James Horka, who was fired over the incident; and
patrolmen Daniel Surufka and Kevin Beasley, who each served
suspensions. Also named are the village of Burnham and a village
officer who was at the scene, Gregory Giglio.
   Horka said later he was waiting for the landlord to arrive with a
key, rather than kicking down the door, because he feared that the
girl would be in worse danger if police forced their way in during
the attack.
   Thomas Bobak, attorney for Calumet City, said he had not seen the
lawsuit, but said the city will ``defend the appropriate parties in
due course.''
   The current and former police officers had unlisted telephone
numbers and could not be reached. Burnham Police Chief J.D. Crull
said he and Giglio could not comment on the pending litigation.
   Ben Valentine, the man accused in the attack, is scheduled to go
to trial Feb. 17.
</TEXT>
