<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Truce     12-19 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Truce,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Guerrillas Propose Christmas Truce</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas proposed a
Christmas season truce Monday in the civil war they have fought for
nine years against the U.S.-backed government.
   The head of the joint chiefs of staff, Emilio Ponce, told
reporters the armed forces did not favor a cease-fire but would
abide by the civilian government's decision.
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte's administration made no immediate
response to the rebels' proposal for a cease-fire beginning Friday
and ending Jan. 2.
   In 1985, the civilian government said it would consider a truce,
but the armed forces high command rejected it and fighting continued
through the holidays. There was no Christmas truce last year or in
1986.
   In a broadcast Monday on clandestine Radio Venceremos, the rebels
called on El Salvador's armed forces to suspend all land, sea and
air operations and to restrict to barracks those troops not on
leave. The rebels also offered to cease their offensive action.
   They said if the armed forces agrees to a truce, delegations from
both sides should meet Wednesday or Thursday to work out details. If
the armed forces does not reply by Wednesday night or rejects the
overture, the rebels will continue fighting, the broadcast said.
   In November, the guerrillas declared a weeklong unilateral
cease-fire for the meeting of the General Assembly of the
Organization of American States in El Salvador.
   El Salvador's civil war has killed an estimated 65,000 people.
</TEXT>
