<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Judge-Perjury,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Denies New Trial for Convicted U.S. District Judge Walter
Nixon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Monday denied U.S.
District Judge Walter Nixon Jr. a new trial on a 1986 perjury
conviction.
   Nixon is the second federal judge ever to be convicted of a crime
while on the bench. He began serving a five-year prison term earlier
this year at Eglin Air Force Base near Pensacola, Fla.
   Nixon, who was based in Biloxi, Miss., was convicted of
committing perjury when he testified he never discussed a pending
drug case with a district attorney.
   At a hearing in September on Nixon's motion for a new trial, a
prosecution witness, Wiley Fairchild, testified that he had lied
during Nixon's trial.
   U.S. District Judge John Nangle said Monday that he had issued an
opinion denying the request for a new trial, but declined to give
details because the participants in the case had not received copies
of the ruling.
   In January, a U.S. House subcommittee is scheduled to continue
impeachment hearings on Nixon. Unless he is impeached, Nixon will
continue to receive his $89,500 annual federal judicial salary.
