<2ND_LINE>AM-Hotel Fire,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Residents Accounted For</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Jewellus cq in 8th graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two residents of a hotel who were
unaccounted for after fire swept through the building contacted
police Monday and said they were not home when the blaze broke out.
   Fire swept through the Morningside Hotel on Sunday, killing one
person and seriously injuring two others. Officials at first
expressed fears that the death toll would be higher, but gradually
the number of unaccounted-for residents dropped.
   The 105-room, four-story hotel, built in 1924, provided cheap
housing for transients and some long-term residents, many of whom
depend on Social Security or other limited income, authorities said.
   Fire Chief Luther Taylor said the fire was apparently started by
a discarded match in a third-floor apartment.
   Dawn Moore and her 2-year-old son, Matthew, were among the 120
residents forced out of the building Sunday.
   ``I lost everything _ dishes, clothes, a TV,'' she said. ``I
don't think we'll have much of a Christmas now. We'll manage the
best we can.''
   On Christmas morning last year, fire forced Ms. Moore and her son
out of an apartment on the city's west side. ``This being my second
fire, I was terrified,'' she said.
   St. Joseph County Coroner Louis Grwinski said Jewellus K. Wood,
49, a truck driver, died of smoke inhalation and burns.
   Two residents were hospitalized in serious condition. Philip
Scott, 39, was being treated for burns at Memorial Hospital of South
Bend, and Sue Davis, 36, was hospitalized at St. Joseph Medical
Center for smoke inhalation, said hospital representatives.
