<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Rocket,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Launches New Model Space Exploration Rocket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China successfully launched a new model space
exploration rocket from a recently opened space center on southern
Hainan Island, the official Xinhua News Agency said Tuesday.
   It said the space capsule put into orbit by Weaver Girl I floated
in the atmosphere for 2{ hours before returning to Earth 40 miles
from the launch site.
   Xinhua provided no details of the new rocket, which is named
after a Chinese legend.
   But it said the launch marked the first time Chinese scientists
gained direct access to mid-layer atmospheric data in a low-latitude
equatorial area.
   China has three other launch sites, all in medium latitudes. The
Hainan base was designed specifically for research into space
physical phenomena at low latitudes, Xinhua said in an earlier
report.
   Rockets launched from Hainan, about 19 degrees north of the
equator, will be used for space experiments from a height of about
74 miles above the Earth's surface, said the agency.
   Weaver Girl I was developed by the Chinese Academy of Sciences
and the University of Defense Science and Technology.
   Its predecessors, Long March II and Long March III, have logged
highly successfuly records of placing communications and research
satellites into orbit since the nation launched its first rocket in
1970.
   The U.S. State Department said Monday that China and the United
States had agreed on measures to prevent China from undercutting
private American launch services, opening the way for use of Chinese
rockets to launch American-made satellites for foreign companies.
</TEXT>
