<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0628 12-19 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0628,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Premier Tries Talking Soviets Into Territorial Concession</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with Japanese
prime minister meets Shevardnadze. No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Noboru Takeshita tried his hand on Tuesday
at coaxing the Soviet foreign minister into some movement on a
longstanding territorial dispute that blocks accord on a peace
treaty, a Foreign Ministry official said.
   Earlier, Japan for the first time indicated a willingness to
upgrade economic ties with Moscow despite the impasse.
   Rival claims over the tiny Kuril Islands off Japan's northern
Hokkaido Island has kept Moscow and Tokyo from signing a treaty to
formally end World War II hostilities. This has stalled
Soviet-Japanese relations and hampered economic cooperation between
the two countries.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze, heading into a
second day of talks with Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno and other
officials, met with Takeshita on Tuesday to deliver a letter from
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   On Monday, Shevardnadze and Uno failed to iron out disagreements
on the dispute during about 6{ hours of talks.
   The ministry official, who briefed reporters on the condition of
anonymity, quoted Takeshita as telling Shevardnadze that resolution
of the land dispute ``would be the basis for permanent and stable
relations.'' The premier ``hoped the Soviet side would give serious
consideration to the issue,'' he quoted Takeshita as saying.
   The official said Shevardnadze, without proposing a specific
date, said Gorbachev has put a trip to Japan on his political
schedule and that Takeshita was welcome to visit Moscow.
   Soviet and Japanese officials labored on an agreement that might
boost economic ties despite the row over the Kurils, which Moscow
has held since the end of World War II and which Tokyo wants back.
The Soviets ousted 17,000 Japanese residents and later consolidated
their occupation with 10,000 troops.
   Shevardnadze asked Takeshita what Japan's attitude would be if
the dispute is not solved, the Japanese official said, and Takeshita
replied that the problem should be tackled with eagerness.
   ``The Soviets have shown no basic change in their position'' on
what Japan calls the Northern Territories, the official said.
   But he saw hope in the continued meetings of the two foreign
ministers and their aides on the issue.
   Until now, Japanese officials said they expected no progress in
bilateral relations until the Kremlin agreed to negotiate the return
of the islands.
   But in his Monday meeting with Shevardnadze, Uno said: ``Japan is
prepared to develop ... economic relations'' with the Soviet Union,
a country he desribed as having ``great potential,'' the Foreign
Ministry official reported.
   Trade between the Soviet Union and Japan has been hindered by
sensitivity over the territorial dispute and by national security
concerns.
   Two-way trade reached $4.9 billion in 1987 _ about 1.8 percent of
Japan's trade _ and is expected to hit $4.98 billion this year.
   Gorbachev has ambitious plans to develop the vast Siberian
region, a feat that would require input from foreign investors,
including the Japanese.
   Before Shevardnadze's arrival, Japanese officials hinted at a
possible compromise on the territorial dispute, but a senior Foreign
Ministry official said Japan's demand for the islands' return
remains unchanged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
