<NOTE>$adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wednesday, Dec. 28</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Wednesday, Dec. 28, the 363rd day of 1988. There are
three days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In 1945, Congress officially recognized the Pledge of Allegiance.
   On this date:
   In 1694, Queen Mary II of England died after five years of joint
rule with her husband, King William III.
   In 1832, John C. Calhoun became the first U.S. vice president to
resign, stepping down over differences with President Andrew Jackson.
   In 1846, Iowa became the 29th state admitted to the Union.
   In 1856, the 28th President of the United States, Thomas Woodrow
Wilson, was born in Staunton, Va.
   In 1869, William Finley Semple of Mount Vernon, Ohio, patented
chewing gum.
   In 1937, composer Maurice Ravel died in Paris.
   In 1945, author Theodore Dreiser died in Hollywood.
   In 1973, Alexander Solzhenitsyn published ``Gulag Archipelago,''
an expose of the Soviet prison system that led to his expulsion from
the Soviet Union.
   In 1977, in a surprise move, President Jimmy Carter announced he
was replacing Arthur F. Burns as chairman of the Federal Reserve
Board with Textron Inc. Chairman G. William Miller.
   In 1982, Nevell Johnson Jr., a black man, was mortally wounded by
a police officer in a Miami video arcade, setting off three days of
racial disturbances that left another man dead.
   Ten years ago: A United Airlines DC-8 ran out of fuel and
crash-landed about six miles from Portland International Airport in
Oregon, killing ten and injuring 69 of the more than 180 people
aboard.
   Five years ago: A Pentagon commission criticized growing U.S.
military involvement in Lebanon, and called for a review of
alternatives, including more vigorous diplomacy, to achieve U.S.
goals.
   One year ago: In Arkansas' worst mass murder, the bodies of 14
relatives of R. Gene Simmons were found at his home near Dover after
Simmons went on a shooting spree in Russellville that claimed the
lives of two other people. (Simmons was convicted of the
Russellville killings; he has yet to be tried in the other deaths.)
   Today's birthdays: Actor Lew Ayres is 80. Actor Lou Jacobi is 75.
Actress Maggie Smith is 54. Pianist Richard Clayderman is 35.
   Thought for today: ``Our chief defect is that we are more given
to talking about things than to doing them.'' _ Jawaharlal Nehru,
Indian statesman (1889-1964).
</TEXT>
