<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv30,0479</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday, Dec. 30</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Friday, Dec. 30, the 365th day of 1988. There is one day
left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In 1853, the United States bought some 45,000 square miles of
land from Mexico in a deal that became known as the Gadsden
Purchase, for the man who engineered it, James Gadsden. (The area
became the southern part of Arizona and New Mexico.)
   On this date:
   In 1865, author Rudyard Kipling was born in Bombay, India.
   In 1894, suffragist Amelia Jenks Bloomer died. She had gained
notoriety for wearing in public a short skirt and baggy trousers
that became known as ``bloomers.''
   In 1903, about 600 people died when fire broke out at the
Iroquois Theater in Chicago.
   In 1911, Sun Yat-sen was elected the first president of the
Republic of China after the fall of the Chinese dynasties.
   In 1936, the United Auto Workers union staged its first sit-down
strike, at the Fisher Body Plant No. 1 in Flint, Mich.
   In 1944, King George II of Greece proclaimed a regency to rule
his country, virtually renouncing the throne.
   In 1947, King Michael of Romania agreed to abdicate, but charged
he was being forced off the throne by communists.
   In 1972, the United States halted its heavy bombing of North
Vietnam.
   In 1977, President Jimmy Carter held the first news conference by
an American president in Eastern Europe as he told reporters in
Warsaw that both Americans and Poles shared the same aspiration for
``complete preservation and enhancement of human rights.''
   Ten years ago: Ohio State University dismissed Woody Hayes as its
football coach, one day after Hayes punched Clemson University
player Charlie Bauman on a sideline of the Gator Bowl following
Bauman's interception of an Art Schlichter pass.
   Five years ago: West Germany's Defense Ministry announced that
recently deployed Pershing-2 missiles were ready to be fired on
command, but said they would be ``immediately destroyed'' if the
Soviet Union were to scrap its own medium-range missiles.
   One year ago: Manufacturers of all-terrain vehicles agreed to
withdraw the three-wheel model from dealers' inventories, but
stopped short of a recall, as demanded by consumer and medical
groups who felt the vehicles were too dangerous, especially when
driven by children.
   Today's birthdays: Actress Jeanette Nolan is 77. Former beauty
pageant host Bert Parks is 74. Actress Jo Van Fleet is 69. Singer Bo
Diddley is 60. Actor Jack Lord is 58. Actor John Hillerman is 56.
Baseball hall-of-famer Sandy Koufax is 53. Singer-musician Michael
Nesmith is 46. Actress Tracey Ullman is 29.
   Thought for today: ``No government ought to be without censors;
and where the press is free, none ever will.'' _ President Thomas
Jefferson (1743-1826).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
