<DOCNO> AP881219-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1340EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--Kenny'sStyle ADV01   12-19 0991</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Kenny's Style, ADV 01,1025</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Jan. 1</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ He was deformed at birth and when he was 2 his
legs were amputated up to the pelvis. But Kenny Easterday, 15,
thumbs his nose at his handicap and ignores the stares of strangers,
preferring to walk on his hands rather than ride in a wheelchair.
His spunk inspired a French-Canadian filmmaker to make a movie about
his life, called ``Kid Brother.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen-year-old Kenny Easterday knows the
sight of a 2-foot-tall boy with half a body walking on his hands or
zooming down the street on a skateboard causes heads to turn.
   Kenny's been stared at for so long, friends say he gets perturbed
if people fail to notice him.
   It's part of his cockiness, part of what has helped him to
survive.
   Kenny calls it his ``style,'' a tough, spunky veneer to protect
the kid inside him who has been poked, prodded, inspected and
rejected all his life. He insists _ by example more than words _
that he's no different from any other teen-age boy.
   ``I like torn-up shirts, jean jackets with holes in them, long
hair, earrings and hard-rock music _ and getting in trouble,'' he
says, his straight brown hair hanging limply over the collar of his
denim jacket.
   Kenny walks on long, calloused hands instead of using a
wheelchair, as if to prove he can be faster and tougher than people
without disabilities. He refuses to wear a prosthesis, insisting it
hampers his mobility while only serving to make his appearance more
acceptable to the public.
   Kenny was born Dec. 7, 1973, with mangled legs and sacral
agenesis, a disease that left a gap between the upper part of his
body and pelvis and legs.
   His backbone, incomplete at birth, was re-formed in an operation
when he was 6 months old. Before he was 2, his legs were amputated
up to his pelvis, reducing him to a height of about 2 feet.
   Despite appearances, there is little Kenny can't do, or at least
doesn't think he can do.
   He almost purposefully ignores questions focusing on the handicap
but quickly answers those generic to teen-agers.
   Ask him, for instance, about the two rhinestones in his left ear,
and he'll proudly boast about how he pierced his ears himself.
   Ask him what kind of music he likes, and he'll proffer a host of
rap and hard-rock groups. ``I like Motley Crue, AC-DC, Black
Sabbath, Bon Jovi, Def Leppard, Led Zeppelin ...'' and the list goes
on.
   Ask him what he wants to be when he gets older.
   ``I'd like to be a music teacher, or I might be a gym teacher, or
president of the United States,'' he says, laughing like he's being
tickled.
   ``He switches it all the time,'' taunts his 17-year-old brother,
Eddie. ``First he wanted to be a lawyer, then he wanted to be a
doctor.''
   ``I might be all these things, Eddie,'' Kenny retorts.
   It is that spirit that inspired French-Canadian filmmaker Claude
Gagnon to make a movie about Kenny.
   ``From the first moment I met him, I knew I wanted to make the
film with him,'' says Claude Gagnon, director of the movie, ``Kid
Brother,'' which premiered in November in Pittsburgh.
   ``I really wanted to be close to that kid and work with him. He
can fool around and be childish, but he's got a very serious side to
his personality.
   ``I think the thing that helped Kenny the most is that his family
never tried to overprotect him. When Kenny is around I never think
of things he can't do.''
   As an example of Kenny's ability, the director mentions a scene
in the movie in which Kenny swings with amazing agility from
playground monkey bars.
   ``Kenny can do so many things I'll never be able to do in my
life, and he knows it,'' Gagnon says. ``He's very proud of it. He
wants to show the world, `Here I am. Here's what I can do. Can you
do it?'''
   Gagnon says Kenny's mother, Sharon, didn't object to the film as
long as the family was portrayed accurately _ ``not everything in
pink and beautiful.''
   That's because Kenny's life hasn't been neat and pretty.
   Kenny grew up in a second floor apartment over a storefront _
with no elevator _ in nearby West Aliquippa, a rough, Ohio River
steel town shadowed by the 7-mile-long LTV Steel Corp. plant.
   His father, Jesse, is an unemployed maintenance worker who does
odd jobs, and his mother works evenings at a geriatric convalescent
center.
   His sister, Sharon, 20, hasn't lived at home for many years and
the two aren't on speaking terms, while Eddie grew up resenting
Kenny for not being a ``normal'' brother.
   In the midst of this have come a herd of reporters and
photographers to document Kenny's life. His parents usually decline
to talk to reporters.
   Reporters can be rude when they don't like what they hear, Kenny
says.
   During an interview in October in Seoul, South Korea, where Kenny
carried the torch for the International Paralympics, ``this reporter
got mad and walked out when we told him we don't go to church,'' he
says.
   Over the years Kenny has gotten accustomed to rudeness and
staring.
   ``He knows he surprises people and he's not scared by that
fact,'' Gagnon says. ``He tries to get the best out of it.''
   Prior to the movie and publicity about Kenny, however, ``people
would see him in the street and either cross or run away,'' the
director says.
   ``Today they ask to kiss him or shake his hand. All of a sudden,
they appreciate him. He's finally getting a lot of the love and
tenderness he deserves.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881219-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1341EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--OrganicOasis ADV01   12-19 1161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Organic Oasis, ADV 01,1195</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Jan. 1</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ They established their organic farm four decades
ago, shunning pesticides and chemical fertilizers at a time when
agriculture was rushing pell-mell in the opposite direction. But
Paul Keene and his late wife, Betty, held to their convictions and
today their chemical-free food products have found markets around
the world.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENNS CREEK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The seed of the idea was planted in 1939
when Paul Keene, a young missionary to India, met Mohandas Gandhi.
   It eventually grew into Walnut Acres Farm, an oasis of natural
food in a fast-food world, a place frequented by people such as
naturalist Euell Gibbons, who lived 10 miles away until he died in
1975.
   The organic farm, one of the oldest in the country, has blossomed
into a $5 million-a-year business in the four decades since Keene
and his wife, Betty, put down roots in central Pennsylvania and
began tending the land without pesticides or other man-made
chemicals.
   ``You don't see the birds that are going to steal your grain from
you,'' Keene says. ``They need food, too.''
   The 108-acre farm the Keenes bought in 1946 is now nearly five
times that large and yields about 300 organic products that are sold
worldwide. The top sellers include preservative-free peanut butter,
granolas and other sugarless cereals, and freshly ground,
whole-grain flours.
   The basic tenet at Walnut Acres, according to Keene, is that
``food should be _ is _ the most important thing in life and one
should be more concerned about what one eats than anything else.''
   ``All joys and all outreach can only be appreciated if you're
healthy and don't have to worry about your insides and your
outsides,'' adds Keene, 78.
   George DeVault, editor and publisher of The New Farm, a magazine
published by the Regenerative Agriculture Association, acknowledges
Walnut Acres is a pioneer in organic farming.
   ``I think that in the very near future, that's going to be the
conventional way of farming,'' DeVault says. ``The present
chemical-intensive system we have now is not sustainable _ the
economics, the environment, the health concerns, the residue...
   ``People like Paul Keene have helped pave the way for a healthier
future for all of us.''
   Keene's desire to enrich the earth and its people was nourished
by Gandhi, whom he met nearly 50 years ago in British-ruled India.
Keene, the Yale-educated son of a minister, had gone there the year
before as a missionary.
   ``I said to him, `I'm teaching mathematics in a school in
America. I'm here and I'm learning a lot about India and I'm not
satisfied with this work I'm doing. What would you suggest?'
   ``He said, `Well, I can't advise you on the details. But the
first thing you should do when you get back is give away everything
you have.'''
   An inspired Keene returned to the United States in 1940 with his
wife, a British missionary's daughter, and taught one more year at
New Jersey's Drew University before quitting.
   The couple spent the next several years at organic farming
schools that stressed the need to ``go back to the soil.'' In 1946,
they borrowed $5,000 to buy their Penns Creek farm, 55 miles north
of Harrisburg.
   They worked the land without electricity, tractors or insurance.
They also refused to spray their crops and soil, a criterion in the
fledgling field of organic farming.
   Within a few years, Walnut Acres, the business, was born.
   ``We immediately said, `Well, it's not right that we own this
whole business and get all the profits,''' Keene says. ``So we gave
the business away.''
   The private, employee-owned business now encompasses 500 acres,
free of synthetic chemicals and tilled by modern methods, and a
full-time staff of 95. Mail-order business has grown 17 percent in
the past year alone, according to Bob Anderson, 43, Keene's
son-in-law and the company's vice president and general manager.
   As business flourishes, so does Walnut Acres' philanthropy.
   About $7,000 to $8,000 in donations from customers and employees
will be funneled this year into a community center in tiny Penns
Creek, built and run by Walnut Acres Foundation Inc., a non-profit
offshoot.
   Another $8,000 will go to a home and school for orphaned and
unwanted children in India that was ``adopted'' by the foundation 12
years ago. Last year, $33,500 was raised for an all-purpose building
at the school in memory of Betty Keene, who died in May 1987 at age
74.
   The lean, robust Keene uses his ``Greetings from the Farm''
essays in Walnut Acres' bimonthly catalog to muse over farming,
nature ``and the oneness of all life.'' Fifty-nine of his essays,
written over the past 30 years, were released by The Globe Pequot
Press in late November in a book entitled ``Fear Not To Sow Because
of the Birds.''
   Anderson says people are becoming more interested in diet and
nutrition, in part because of Surgeon General C. Everett Koop's
warnings about high cholesterol, smoking and obesity. ``Going
together with this has been a little bit more interest in gourmet
foods, and gourmet cooks start looking for purer ingredients,'' he
says.
   ``We're leaders in the field in letting people understand what
healthy eating is and what it means,'' says his wife, Ruth Keene
Anderson, 43, secretary and treasurer for Walnut Acres.
   Although exact figures are not available, experts say organic
farms account for 1 percent to 5 percent of the nation's farms. The
definition of organic varies from state to state, however, and the
ensuing confusion has prompted some to call for federal standards.
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture in 1980 defined organic
farming as a production system that avoids or largely excludes the
use of synthetic fertilizers, pesticides, growth regulators and
livestock feed additives. Organic farms rely on crop rotation, crop
residues, animal manure and mechanical cultivation.
   ``There is a need for greater uniformity,'' says Patrick Madden,
professor of agricultural economics at Pennsylvania State University.
   Vegetables, grain and other crops native to Pennsylvania are
grown at Walnut Acres. Rice, nuts, dried fruits and other
non-indigenous products are furnished by organic farms elsewhere
that meet Walnut Acres' standards.
   Chickens and Holstein cattle are raised naturally on neighboring
farms, with access to the outdoors, pesticide-free feed and no
growth stimulants. The meat is used for soups, stews and sauces.
   Walnut Acres products are sold at a store on the premises and in
health food shops around the country, as well as through the mail.
The items are by no means cheap. Peanut butter costs $3.29 a pound,
for example, while a 16-ounce can of chicken gumbo soup retails for
$2.75.
   Emma Mattern, 57, a 29-year employee who's now marketing manager,
tells workers not to pack or ship anything they wouldn't put in
their own pantry.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881219-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1343EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--Mutter'sMusic ADV01   12-19 1140</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Mutter's Music, ADV 01,1189</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Jan. 1</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ When she won a national competition for young
musicians in her native Germany at age 7, the government allowed her
to drop out of regular school and be tutored at home so she could
spend more time practicing the violin. Today, at age 25, Anne-Sophie
Mutter is more than a child prodigy. She's an international star in
classical music.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In her strapless Dior gown with a Stradivarius
tucked under her chin, Anne-Sophie Mutter is the glamour girl among
today's young classical violinists.
   The German-born musician is in the fast lane, zipping around in a
Porsche 911 convertible at up to 100 mph-plus on the Autobahn,
vacationing in her apartment in Monte Carlo. A fan club always
greets her in Japan.
   But aside from fashion, there is a practical reason for the
strapless Dior.
   ``I discovered the violin sounds much better on bare skin and it
is not so slippery,'' she says.
   The 25-year-old Miss Mutter indeed is serious about her music,
and she has the ear of serious musicians, such as Herbert von
Karajan, music director of the Berlin Philharmonic, and Mstislav
Rostropovich, cellist and music director of the National Symphony in
Washington, D.C.
   ``Miss Mutter's gifts include a consummate control of her
instrument, gleaming intonation, ripe sound and an assured,
nerveless stage demeanor,'' wrote Time magazine.
   Last spring, Miss Mutter made her sixth concert tour of the
United States, performing with major orchestras. In December, she
made her first American recital tour, playing solo in 12 cities, all
of the 14 appearances sold out.
   In January she will marry a fellow German, Detlef Wunderlich, a
lawyer. After the honeymoon, she will resume her schedule of 120
concerts a year.
   Miss Mutter started violin lessons at age 6. She won a national
competition for 6- to 24-year-old musicians at age 7 and the German
government gave permission for her to drop out of regular school and
be tutored at home in Wehr, near the southern tip of the Black
Forest. While she did play with her two older brothers and other
children, most of her time was spent with the violin.
   ``I just loved to play the violin and I wanted to play well
because I liked the sound,'' she recalls. ``So I practiced. I grew
up with music as something very precious and something very pure.
   ``My father took care I did not have a child prodigy career. What
can you decide yourself at the age of 6, 8 or 13?''
   Today she has an agent in each country and her father, a
newspaper publisher, coordinates them. Like most classical
musicians, she won't divulge her income.
   Miss Mutter only played a few concerts a year until she started
performing with Karajan.
   After that, she says, ``I didn't have to play with bad orchestras
or audition for each conductor or go through competitions.''
   She had her first personal contact with Karajan in 1976 at age 13
after she performed at an international music festival in Lucerne,
Switzerland. Karajan heard about it and invited her to audition.
   ``I didn't want to go,'' she recalls. ``For such a genius, what
could I do? I pursuaded my parents to postpone. We went on a holiday
to Spain.
   ``In December I flew to Berlin with my father and teacher. Both
were really nervous. I was not nervous. I understood there was not
the slightest bit of hope. Because I had nothing to lose, that is
why I survived this moment.
   She played a Bach ``Chaconne'' and afterward Karajan told her,
``I will be happy to play with you next year in Salzburg.''
   Miss Mutter made her first recording at 15, with Karajan, playing
a Mozart concerto in one take.
   She made four recordings in 1988 for release early in 1989,
including Tchaikovsky's ``Concerto for Violin and Orchestra in D
major,'' with Karajan and the Vienna Philharmonic and Witold
Lutoslawksi's ``Chain 2'' and ``Partita,'' the latter dedicated to
her by Lutoslawski.
   For the past three years Miss Mutter has been playing a 1710 Lord
Dunraven Strad. ``I like the sound,'' she says, ``very silvery and
quick responding, very good projecting.''
   Four years ago, she says with a twinkle, ``I made a very good
step. My parents were against my driving a sports car, saying,
`Don't risk your life.' I decided I will ask Maestro Karajan in
front of my father. He said it was a great idea.''
   Karajan helped her select and order the white 911 Porsche, with
its red leather interior and black convertible top.
   Since 1985, Miss Mutter has played chamber music with
Rostropovich and violist Bruno Giuranna.
   ``Shortly after I made my debut in Washington eight years ago,
with Rostropovich conducting, he said he wanted to return to chamber
music,'' she says. ``He had stopped playing with a string trio 30
years ago.
   ``We've played everywhere in Europe. It was a dream, to play this
repertory, apart from playing it with the greatest cellist and
greatest viola player. You can imagine what a lesson each concert
is. Every phrase you hear from both of them pushes you forward.''
   Krzystof Penderecki is composing a concerto for the
Mutter-Guiranna-Rostropovich Trio.
   The strapless stage dresses didn't begin as a trademark, Miss
Mutter says. She started needing gowns at 14, to perform with
Karajan in Salzburg. But where, at that age, would she find them?
She tried bridemaid's dresses, but found that the sleeves got in the
way. So she bought peasant blouses with elastic necklines so she
could pull the sleeves down on her arms.
   ``I only was looking for comfort. My neck is short, which is
perfect for violin playing without support under the instrument.
   ``One day I felt grown up enough to buy real dresses, not this
child stuff.''
   So she went to Paris and immediately found two dresses she liked
at Chanel.
   ``After I discovered how comfortable it is to have dresses made
for you _ everything fits _ I couldn't go back to a compromise.
   ``After I got a taste of it, I went to Dior. I prefer Dior, much
more simple. I have shoes made in different colors like the dress,
always the same style.''
   For her performances with the trio, Dior designers fashioned a
woman's tuxedo. ``I want to look as my partners look,'' she says.
``I needed different sleeves and a lot of volume in the back of the
jacket. We worked on that outfit for days.
   ``It's comfortable but you can't compare it to the liberty you
have in a dress. And it's so hot.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
