<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1357EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek ADV01   12-19 1116</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, ADV 01,1147</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Jan. 1</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 0 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Greenberg, a genial 30-year-old
playwright, has written a comedy that includes such topics as
yuppies, AIDS and the homeless _ all set against a backdrop of New
York in the late 1980s.
   It's a surprising mixture. Even more surprising, it works.
   The play, ``Eastern Standard,'' arrived on Broadway after a
sold-out run at off-Broadway's Manhattan Theater Club. Its cast
consists mostly of unknown young actors. The exception is Anne
Meara, who plays a foulmouthed bag lady almost redeemed by these
upwardly mobile youngsters.
   ``Almost'' is the key word here because nothing, these baby
boomers learn, is as easy or as black-and-white as it seems.
Stephen, an architect, loves Phoebe, a stockbroker. Drew, an artist,
loves Peter, a television producer. Peter has AIDS. Ellen, a
waitress, wants to help Mae, the bag lady. And Mae dupes them all.
   Ask Greenberg to explain how he put together this unlikely
combination of people and themes, and he launches into an extended
history of the play.
   ```Eastern Standard' was a collection of several different
impulses,'' says the author, relaxing in his agent's apartment.
   The play grew out of Greenberg's last full-length work, ``The
Maderati,'' a stylized farce about the Big Apple's young literary
set. Greenberg thought it would be his farewell to New York as a
playwright.
   ``I'm constantly saying `I'm never writing about New York
again,''' he says. ``But when `The Maderati' didn't quite come off,
I thought, `Well, all right, one more.' And I wanted to write it in
such a way that wasn't so brittle and artificial. I decided that
instead of inventing a world, I'd sort of figure out what the
strains and tensions of the real world were and bring them
together.''
   Putting such topics as AIDS or the homeless in a comedy has
perplexed _ and even angered _ some audiences.
   ``When you have a homeless person and a person with AIDS in a
play and you're funny, it really ruffles some feathers,'' he says.
``I think there's an idea that seriousness is the same thing as
sentimentality and unless you show what a devastating thing AIDS is
and dwell on that, people get very wary.''
   The comedy also has an ambiguity about its characters that can be
unsettling, Greenberg says.
   ``The thing about this play is that every character at one point
seems to be right and at another point seems to be wrong,'' he adds.
``You can really be in a quandary as to what you are supposed to
feel about them. There's a comfort in being told what you are
supposed to think. In `Eastern Standard,' you constantly have to
change your mind.''
   Especially, if most of the characters are yuppies, the one group
America loves to hate the most. Greenberg doesn't even like to use
the word.
   ``I call them the upper class or the upper-middle class now,'' he
says.
   Some critics didn't even think they were worthy of a play.
   ``I felt that some of the people who have launched these attacks
are living exactly the same way and the only thing that separates
them from the people they are attacking is that they are
attacking,'' the playwright says. ``I think there's an element of
hypocrisy in that.''
   Greenberg, who resembles a slightly disheveled preppie, looks and
talks a lot like the people he writes about.
   ``I know a lot of people like those in the play,'' he says, ``but
no character is directly based on anyone I know.''
   Greenberg began working on ``Eastern Standard'' in March 1987,
the day after ``The Maderati'' closed off-Broadway. Writing 20 to 25
pages a day, he had a first draft ready in a few weeks.
   ``I've worked harder on `Eastern Standard' than I've worked on
any other play, although it came very quickly in that first draft,''
Greenberg says. ``The arch, where it started and where it went to,
always has been the same, but the journey there has changed a lot.''
   The journey took the playwright to the Seattle Repertory Theater
where the play had its first full production last spring. Audiences
there were enthusiastic, although local reviews were mixed.
   ``Eastern Standard'' got to Broadway through the persistence of
producer Jessica Levy. It was Levy who first commissioned Greenberg
to write a play specifically for the commercial theater.
   ``I was flabbergasted by the idea that this was a commercial
commission and not for an institutional theater program,'' the
playwright recalls. ``Then I began thinking, `What makes plays
commercial?' and ended up creating the most abstruse, inaccessible,
unproducible thing I'd ever written.''
   He finally gave that play up and then started work on ``Eastern
Standard'' which Levy licensed to Seattle Rep before it came to the
Manhattan Theater Club and then Broadway.
   The playwright springs from the middle class, the split-level
suburbs of Long Island's Nassau County where his father was a movie
theater executive. His education was decidedly upper crust.
Greenberg went to Princeton and then tried the Ph.D. program in
English at Harvard before ending up at the Yale Drama School to
write plays.
   ``When I finally became a playwright, I thought, `Oh, this works.
I like it. This puts things together nicely,''' he recalls with a
smile.
   While in his third year at Yale, Greenberg had two one-act plays
accepted at Ensemble Studio Theater, a tiny but well-respected New
York theater company. One was a big hit.
   ``So I started being employed as a writer, doing TV and film
scripts, right out of school,'' he says. ``I don't know what I
thought I was going to do, but somehow I've managed to support
myself as a writer.''
   It's the writing for TV and films that drains Greenberg primarily
because they involve so much collaboration.
   ``Plays excite me. They wake me up,'' he says, although he's
never thought of himself as a Broadway playwright.
   ``I think for playwrights of my generation, Broadway has never
been a specific goal,'' he says. Greenberg thought he'd write plays
and have them done at small institutional theaters in New York or
beyond and maybe some of them would move off-Broadway.
   ``Now there is all sorts of attention, from all sorts of
directions, maybe because the play is controversial,'' Greenberg
says. ``The only way to have a play that isn't controversial is to
write about nothing. But it's odd having everything so public. The
idea of reveling in all that attention is very weird to me.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
