<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview ADV00   12-19 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Film Review, ADV 00,0492</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Dangerous Liaisons''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sexual depravity among the French aristocracy was depicted in
Choderlos De Laclos' 1782 novel ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses'' with
such sordid detail that it has been the target of censors ever
since. In recent times it has been converted into a hit play by
Christopher Hampton, who has now written a film version with the
anglicized title of ``Dangerous Liaisons.''
   Directed with zest by Stephen Frears, the movie marks a welcome
return to the traditional storytelling of films, playing dramatic
events against the convincing backdrop of a historical era. Even the
plot is pleasingly old-fashioned: The wrongdoers receive their
comeuppance at the curtain.
   ``Dangerous Liaisons'' ignores the political ferment of late
18th-century France to concentrate on the bedroom games of jaded
aristocrats. The plotters of the intrigue are a pair well-matched in
cool evil. The Marquise de Merteuil (Glenn Close) is brainy but
sex-obsessed, eager to avenge rejection by a former lover. Her aim:
to assure deflowering of his 16-year-old future bride (Uma Thurman).
   The notorious rake, Vicomte de Valmont (John Malkovich), greedily
accepts the challenge, but he decides that the conquest is too easy.
So he also proposes a greater achievement: seducing Madame de
Tourvel (Michelle Pfeiffer), a devout, married woman. Valmont's
prize if he succeeds: a long-postponed night with his co-plotter.
   The scene moves to the country estate of Valmont's indulgent aunt
(Mildred Natwick), where he plots his campaign. Both missions
completed, he is thrown off his game by falling in love with the
saintly de Tourvel. Meanwhile, the Marquise has taken a young lover
(Keanu Reeves). All this intrigue is resolved in a surprisingly
moralistic manner.
   ``Dangerous Liaisons' is made more accessible by straight-forward
American-style acting, and the language sounds contemporary despite
an overflow of aphorisms (``Vanity and happiness are
incompatible''). Glenn Close is inspired casting, displaying
calculated mischief in contrast to her ``Fatal Attraction''
dramatics.
   The Valmont role might better have been played by Tyrone Power or
Errol Flynn, but what Malkovich lacks in romantic dash he
compensates with intense dramatic skill. Michelle Pfeiffer delivers
another of her splendid performances, and newcomer Uma Thurman is
impressive as she moves from virgin to wanton.
   Norma Heyman and Hank Moonjean produced the Warner Bros. film,
which is superbly mounted. The rating is R for sexual content.
Running time: 120 minutes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
