<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1941EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo ADV00   12-19 1189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Home Video, ADV 00,1243</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Videos reviewed this week: ``Big Top Pee-wee,'' ``Casual Sex?,''
``Paramedics'' and ``Stormy Monday.''
   
   ``Big Top Pee-wee'' (Paramount Home Video; VHS-Beta,
$89.95-$29.95; Rated G)
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Pee-wee Herman had a farm, e-i-e-i-o.
   And on this farm he had a talking pig named Vance, a pony who
could make pancakes and an entire circusful of strange but
good-hearted performers.
   Here is Pee-wee practicing animal husbandry and agricultural
science with smashing success but failing miserably at making
friends with the local townsfolk, a bunch of certified sourpusses
who clearly would like to string up our hero by his red bowtie.
   The one exception is Winnie, the local school marm, who seems
truly smitten with the androgynous Pee-wee. Something is wrong,
though; her blond tresses snarl painfully under Pee-wee's caress,
and she persists in making him detestable egg-salad sandwiches for
their lunch dates.
   The problem becomes clear when the circus, led by Kris
Kristofferson, drops in his yard a la Oz, after a storm. Here is the
girl of his dreams: Gina the trapeze artist, played by the comely
Italian actress Valeria Golino. Pee-wee's in love.
   Pee-wee, who is already a man-turned-boy, doesn't exactly turn
back into a man in this picture, but he does seem to be growing up.
Whereas ``Pee-wee's Big Adventure'' saw him curling a painted lip at
the prospect of a date with the local bike-shop bimbo, ``Big Top''
finds him as a full-blown romantic leading man, with lots of girl
trouble, a real make-out scene and even _ gasp! _ sex, represented
in a discreet yet cornball way.
   The story of how he wins over the poopy townspeople and helps the
circus put on the best show ever is classic Pee-wee, as written,
produced and performed by his alter ego, Paul Reubens. Full of all
the fun stuff that makes his Saturday morning show so enchanting,
the message here is that it's OK to be different. ``Big Top'' will
make kids of all ages feel good about themselves.
   _ By Lisa Levitt Ryckman, AP National Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Casual Sex?'' (MCA Home Video; VHS, $89.95; Rated R)
   
   ``Casual Sex?'' was an OK idea for a movie. Two single women _
one frightened of sex because of AIDS, her friend just plain
frightened of sex _ go off to a spa for a vacation of free-wheeling
manhunting.
   But ``Casual Sex?'' is not an OK movie. It's silly, predictable
and rarely funny.
   Melissa (Victoria Jackson) and Stacy (Lea Thompson) despair of
finding men with whom they can develop meaningful relationships.
Melissa nearly married the wrong man, but otherwise has avoided much
experience with men. Stacy counts off her former boyfriends, though
her sexual exploits came to a screeching halt with the AIDS scare.
   So they talk about having sex for the fun of it (Stacy recalls
the time when she'd say to a lover, ``Wow, that felt great. What's
your name again?''). But what they really search for is romance and
true love.
   At the ``Oasis Spa,'' Melissa and Stacy have the requisite number
of run-ins with awful, wrong men before true love strikes with the
men they both had overlooked.
   Jackson has an endearing deadpan delivery, and she and Thompson
hit it off as pals. Andrew Dice Clay brings comic relief playing an
oafish pickup artist with a heart of gold.
   Directed by Genevieve Rovert, ``Casual Sex?'' does try to deal
with the sexual mores of the 1980s and with AIDS in a mature and
humorous manner. It is probably an admirable effort _ but only
occasionally a successful one.
   _ By Mary MacVean, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Paramedics'' (Vestron Video; VHS-Beta, $79.98; Rated PG-13)
   
   Don't even bother to read this review let alone buy or rent
``Paramedics.'' You will only be wasting your time, unless you find
sophomoric double entendres about bimbos and chicks amusing, or
tired ethnic jokes a big laugh.
   Using the ``Police Academy'' format, this Stuart Margolin hybrid
dabbles in every formula of the trade. But where ``Police Academy''
had hilarity with its special breed of outrageous characters and
situations, ``Paramedics'' just crawls along squeezing laughs from a
dead storyline and lifeless characters.
   It stars George Newbern (``Adventures in Babysitting'') as Uptown
and Christopher McDonald (``Grease 2'') as Mad Mike, two rowdy
paramedics who use their custom-made city van to cruise the street
for women, much to the horror of their dreadful boss. He reassigns
the undynamic duo from their run in the posh part of town to a
rundown area where they stumble into a street gang war and get
involved in a heart transplant caper. In a fairly predictable
sequence of events, Uptown and Mad Mike emerge as heroes.
   But for all the action, ``Paramedics'' merely shuffles along.
   Also featured are Lawrence-Hilton Jacobs, Ray Walston and the
voice of Sally Kellerman as a dispatcher.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Stormy Monday'' Paramount Home Video; VHS-Beta, $89.95-$29.95;
Rated R
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   It's America Week in Newcastle, and all that's tacky and
distasteful about the United States has come to persuade this
English industrial city to embrace the invasion.
   A clever setting for a romantic thriller, and ``Stormy Monday''
often is clever, as well as sultry and stylish. But it also can be
too elusive and too violent _ there are beatings, shootings,
bombings.
   Cosmo (Tommy Lee Jones) leads the Americans, while Finney (Sting)
is determined not to be pushed around and has brought the Krakow
Jazz Ensemble to mark America Week at the nightclub he owns and the
Americans want to buy.
   The musicians and the Americans all end up at the same hotel, as
do the movie's love interests, Brendan (Sean Bean), who works for
Finney, and Katie (Melanie Griffith), who had been involved with and
seems to work for Cosmo.
   Much of the goings on are shadier than the shady characters. Why
does Cosmo want control of Newcastle? At one point, he explains:
``We can't be shooting people around here. We are supposed to
improve the quality of life, provide jobs and make a lot of money.''
Yes, but ...
   Much of the cleverness involves the Polish musicians. When the
Americans are about to hold a flag-waving reception, Cosmo learns
his band is a no-show. So, the East Bloc band performs a Jimi
Hendrix-like ``Star Spangled Banner.''
   Writer-director Mike Figgis gets impressive performances from his
actors but makes too much of the violence and too little of the
motives for the knock-down, drag-out fight over Newcastle.
   _ By Mary MacVean, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
