<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 2259EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews ADV00   12-19 0991</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, ADV 00,1033</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Christmas Now Is Drawing Near'' (Saydisc) _ Sneak's Noyse.
   ``Thys Yool'' (Nimbus) _ The Martin Best Ensemble.
   ``Christmas Night'' (Collegium) _ The Cambridge Singers and the
City of London Sinfonia, John Rutter conducting.
   
   Sneak's Noyse, a British early music group, promises that its
carol collection is done with original instruments _ rebecs,
penny-whistles, citterns and such _ and at first it may sound as if
the consort includes a cat doing its death rattle.
   ``Oh Christmas now, is drawing near,'' the singers drone, doing
their best to sound like tipsy amateurs out yowling for drinks and
mince pies.
   Patience, however, will be rewarded. Among the 28 tunes is a
lovely version of ``Sweet was the song the Virgin sang,'' a
little-heard carol written down in the early 17th century. There's
an unfamiliar tune, collected in 1952, for ``The holly and the
ivy,'' and some delightful instrumentals: ``Fy, Nay, prithee John,''
and ``The Furry Day Carol.''
   If you must know what Furry Day is, the brief notes are no help.
To get the most from the recording, the listener ought to be reading
along in ``The Oxford Book of Carols,'' the handiest source of
seasonal musical lore. The book explains that ``furry'' is from the
Latin ``feria,'' which means holiday _ also the root of the word
``fair,'' as in village fair.
   Lucie Skeaping, the soprano for Sneak's Noyse, also appears on
Thys Yool, a more austere Christmas recording from the Martin Best
Ensemble.
   One of the jewels in this collection is a 14th-century song, ``As
I lay on Yoolis night,'' in which the narrator imagines being
present at the Nativity. ```Sing now, mother,' said the child,
`about what shall befall me hereafter when I become old.'''
   The mother responds with an eloquent shrug: ``Sweet son,
wherefore should I sing? I never knew anymore about you but what
Gabriel told me in his greeting.''
   On the rollicking side, there's the song ``Tapster, Drynker,''
which is simply an appeal for one more round.
   After the austerities of authentic antiquity, as presently
understood, John Rutter's polished collection of standards is balm
for the ears. Rutter, one of the rising stars in British choral
music both as a composer and conductor, serves up familiar favorites
starting with ``In dulci jubilo'' and on through ``Adam lay
ybounden,'' ``The Cherry Tree Carol'' and even, one dreads, ``O
Tannenbaum.''
   Wretched sentimentality is avoided, however, by the
professionalism and the sincerity of the performances.
   _ By Robert Barr, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Everything's Different Now'' (Epic) 'Til Tuesday
   
   ``No one wants to be happier more than I do,'' Aimee Mann sings
on ``Everything's Different Now,'' the third album by her band, 'Til
Tuesday.
   It's an awful thing to say, but music fans have a vested interest
in seeing she doesn't get her wish. Mann has built a pretty good
career on romantic torment.
   She recently broke up with boyfriend Jules Shear, himself a
songwriter with the band Reckless Sleepers, providing her with a
mother lode of new material.
   Side 1 is a five-song suite that begins with the cautious
optimism of the title tune, co-written with Shear, and ends with the
angry Mann adding an expletive to the line ``life could be great''
that concludes ``(Believed You Were) Lucky.''
   The natural temptation is to run in panic when you hear one of
the songs is titled ``J for Jules'' and features a french horn.
Somehow, she makes it work. Mann is an imaginative writer, able to
give a new twist to an old subject, and her mournful voice is
brightened by strong pop melodies.
   ``I was counting to forever and never even got to 10,'' she sings
at one point. ``When we found a rip in heaven, we should have just
ascended then.''
   Side 2 strays slightly from the dominant theme. ``Limits to
Love'' is about a troubled girl who doesn't respond to the love of
her friends. On ``The Other End (Of the Telescope),'' Mann duets
with another noted wordsmith, Elvis Costello.
   If you think Mann has a tough life, consider Shear, whose band
released its debut album a few months ago. Not only is all his dirty
laundry being aired in public, but his ex-girlfriend's record far
outshines his.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``This Woman'' (RCA) _ K.T. Oslin
   
   K.T Oslin, who began her recording career at the age of 45, has
soared to country music stardom on the basis of her excellent
songwriting and a strong, expressive voice.
   Those strengths, as well as a glaring weakness _ squeaky-clean,
middle-of-the-road pop arrangements that undercut the gritty
real-life images of her lyrics _ are served up in equal measures on
``This Woman.''
   The follow-up to ``80's Ladies,'' her smash 1987 debut, ``This
Woman'' features nine songs that look knowingly at the good times,
bad times and silly games that make and break relationships.
   The best songs include ``Jealous,'' in which the singer fumes
over a man who doesn't know she's alive, while he runs after another
woman who doesn't know he's alive. Oslin's growling, angry vocal,
burning through a gorgeous piano melody, cannot be ignored.
   And ``Where Is a Woman to Go'' offers a hangin' out at the bar
tale from a woman's perspective. ``You know my daddy would die if he
knew his baby was seekin' refuge in a little 'ol bar 'cross town,''
she sings. ``But tell me where is a woman to go when she's feeling
low?''
   In fact, there's not a number on the album that really can be
called bad. But a nagging feeling persists _ how would these songs
sound with a nice little rough-edged band behind Oslin?
   Next time out, someone get This Woman such a band.
   _ By Marc Rice, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
