<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 2344EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Chicago ADV30-01   12-19 0960</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Chicago, ADV 30-01,1002</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30-01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec 30-Jan 1, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Chicago Still Strong</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-one years ago, the Chicago Transit
Authority came to mean a rock band as well as elevated trains around
the Loop. But the group had to shorten its name to Chicago when sued
by the Windy City's Mayor Richard J. Daley.
   Now the seven-man Chicago, which numbers its record albums rather
than names them, has ``19'' in the Top 100 on Cashbox magazine's
best-selling chart. A single from ``19'' _ ``Look Away'' _ moved
into the Top 10. The first single from the album, ``I Don't Wanna
Live Without Your Love,'' charted in the Top 10 in August.
   Chicago, having survived the death of guitarist Terry Kath, Peter
Cetera's leaving for a solo career and a slump, is going strong.
   ``I think you have a sophisticated and educated listener,'' said
Woodwinds player Walt Parazaider. ``More people are musical than in
the late '60s and '70s. Whether the crowd knows a B flat from a Z
diminished, they know if you're not playing well.''
   Chicago has had time to learn to play well. ``As we sit here 21
years later, five of the six originals are still in the band. Six
months after we began, we added Peter Cetera as bassist and lead
vocalist,'' Parazaider said.
   ``The idea Danny (drummer Danny Seraphine) and I had was, let's
put together a rock 'n' roll band with horns. We'd incorporate horns
as more than background licks. I think we've kept up with that.''
   The group has had time to get jaded, too, but Parazaider says
that hasn't happened. ``They say we've sold 80-to-100 million
records and had something like 33 top 40 hit singles.
   ``Every time I hear about a hit record, that's a thrill. Here's
people buying your music, something that you create. There's no
jaded part to Chicago. We are thoroughly pleased that people enjoy
what we're doing.''
   From their first album in 1969, ``Chicago Transit Authority,''
the group became a big underground success and became known as a
touring band.
   ``Janis Joplin and Jimi Hendrix took us on tour as opening act
before we had a record,'' Parazaider said, recalling that Hendrix
told him, ``Your horn section is like one set of lungs and your
guitar player is better than me.'' Joplin told him, ``When you get
as famous as I'm going to be, and you will, don't take it too
serious.''
   ``It meant a lot to me, a link to people that are legends,''
Parazaider said. ``That they respected us is great; I feel fortunate
we touched base with them at all. We take it serious but this isn't
brain surgery.''
   Touring, he said, has always been one of Chicago's strengths.
``The music we play on stage is free. But traveling, they can't pay
us enough for that. We do tours of 130 shows in 150 days. ... We're
always out there playing for whoever wants to hear us. You get
instant reviews.''
   Of course, album sales haven't been constant for two decades.
   ``Glitter rock hit, punk and new wave. We stuck to the music we
played and changed a little with the times. Around the 13th and 14th
albums, in the late '70s, there was a lull. The 13th was gold. Up to
then, they'd been multi-platinum. The 14th wasn't gold.
   ``After selling 50 or 60 million records for Columbia, they ran
for cover when things went bad.'' Columbia dropped Chicago in 1983.
   ``It hurt my feelings,'' Parazaider said. ``It's like you can hit
a grand slam last night and strike out tonight and they're going to
boo. Fame is a transient thing.''
   But he said he wasn't bitter. ``It was a learning experience. Now
I'm happy it happened. ... We got a slap in the face of reality and
we needed it.''
   At that time Chicago's management company advised the band to
produce its own album to be shopped around.
   ``After we finished the 16th album, the response at the different
record companies was tepid at best,'' Parazaider said. ``One label
said, `We'll get rid of the horns and sign a rhythm section.' That
hurts your feelings and makes you mad.
   ``Our manager, Howard Kaufman, said, `After the first single is a
hit the rest of the companies are going to be banging their heads.'
Our next single was No. 1, `Hard to Say I'm Sorry.''' ``16'' was a
gold album and ``17'' was platinum.'' Chicago records on the Reprise
label now.
   Parazaider, whose trumpet-playing Croatian father lives in
Chicago and whose mother was Czech, graduated from DePaul University
in 1968 in clarinet performance. He was inspired at 9 by seeing
Benny Goodman on television. ``Money wasn't abundant,'' Parazaider
recalled, ``but my father got me a teacher. When I was 14 the
teacher said I had surpassed him.
   ``He put me under the tutelage of the clarinetist in the Chicago
Symphony. The relationship lasted until he died in the '70s. He saw
the first big wave the band had in the early '70s and was quite
proud. He played in Carnegie Hall the week before we first played
there. He left me a note backstage, `OK, kid, just play in tune and
don't play too loud.'''
   The clarinetist plays saxophone, flute, keyboards and guitar but
not clarinet for Chicago.
   ``James Pankow (trombonist) arranges. Lee (trumpeter Lee
Loughnane) and I sightread the parts. I think our musicianship has
grown because of the stuff he has written that has challenged us,''
he said. Other members are Robert Lamm, Jason Scheff, who replaced
Cetera, and Bill Champlin.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Dec. 30-Jan. 1</NOTE>
