<HEAD>BRIDE & GROOM: Gift Briefs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY705, NY706</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Clocks rank high as a contemporary gift for young marrieds, says
Barbara Tober, editor of Bride's magazine.
   ``Clocks are great, memorable gifts which help newlyweds avoid
friction during those sensitive first few years,'' she says. ``They
enable them to better synchronize the rhythm of their new life
together.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The solitaire, or single-diamond ring, is the most popular style
of engagement ring, says Lloyd Jaffe, chairman of the American
Diamond Industry Association. Thirty-seven percent of the rings
received by newly-engaged women last year had two or more diamonds,
he says.
   Jaffe says that there were an estimated 2,410,000 marriages last
year and 75 percent of the brides received a diamond engagement ring.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Gibson girl was the fashionable, young American woman of the
``Gay '90s,'' as depicted by illustrator Charles Dana Gibson.
   That image returns as a Gibson girl bride doll authorized by Dana
Gibson, the illustrator's great-granddaughter, available from
Franklin Heirloom Dolls, the Franklin Mint.
   The doll is described as sculpted in hand-painted bisque
porcelain, with a gown of satin, lace and tulle, accented with faux
pearls and 24 karat gold. She wears a hand-painted gold wedding band
on her finger.
