<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Repeating for all needing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Board approved new capital
guidelines designed to push banks into safer investments or force
them to put more of their stockholder's money behind riskier
activities.
   The Fed, by a 6-0 vote on Friday, approved the regulations, which
reward institutions for directing their deposits into prudent
investments such as government securities and home mortgages.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Veterans Administration is raising its
maximum interest rate for federally backed VA home mortgages by
one-half percentage point to 10.5 percent, effective Monday.
   VA spokeswoman Pam Siciliano said Friday the agency was making
the change to reflect recent increases in interest rates in
financial markets.
   Meanwhile, the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. said the national
average for 30-year, conventional mortgages _ those without
government guarantees _ rose to 10.71 percent this week from 10.46
percent last week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street is a house divided as Christmas
approaches, with merger specialists raking in big year-end bonuses
after a year of mega-deals while brokers fear layoffs because of the
slump in stock trading.
   ``There's a euphoria on one side of the house and there's
legitimate, basic concern for the survival of certain other
businesses because of margin compression,'' PJ Johnson, a spokesman
for Nomura Securities International Inc., said Friday,
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new B-2 stealth bomber will carry a price
tag of $516 million per plane, making it by far the most expensive
aircraft ever built.
   Air Force Secretary Edward C. Aldridge, lifting one more veil of
secrecy that has surrounded the project, said Friday the design,
development and construction of 132 planes was expected to cost
$68.1 billion by the time production ends in mid-1995.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BETHPAGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grumman Corp., rocked by a Pentagon
decision to cancel a major bomber project, says it will eliminate
3,100 jobs.
   The cutbacks, to include 1,800 layoffs in January, will be
completed by the end of 1989, the company said Friday. Grumman also
announced layoffs in January 1987 and March 1988.
   Grumman's board of directors met and approved the layoffs after
getting the decision to kill funding for Grumman's A-6G bomber
aircraft in the 1990 federal budget, according to Grumman spokesman
Bob Harwood.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market chalked up a broad gain Friday, as the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials rose 17.71 to 2,150.71, finishing the week
with a net gain of 7.22 points.
   The dollar rose, strengthened by speculation about higher U.S.
interest rates and increased yearend demand for the currency by
multinational companies.
   Platinum futures prices plunged the permitted limit of $25 an
ounce for the second straight day but cash prices steadied.
   Bond prices finished little changed.
</TEXT>
