<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 0919EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Korea-Economy     12-19 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Korea-Economy,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Koreans Release Key Economic Goals For 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea said one of its goals for
1989 is to pare down its current account surplus to $9.5 billion
from this year's projected $13.8 billion.
   The Economic Planning Board said in its economic management plan
Monday that the proposed reduction would be achieved partly through
more liberal import regulations.
   South Korea has pledged to further open its markets to foreigners
to avoid trade friction from the United States and other countries
that have trade deficits with the nation.
   The planning board predicted that imports will rise about 24
percent next year to $65 billion, while exports will increase about
17 percent to $70 billion.
   The board also predicted the economy would grow by about 8
percent next year, compared with the 12.1 percent forcasted for this
year. It attributed the decline to the anticipated slowdown in
exports.
</TEXT>
