<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Ld - Writethru,f0022,0594</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS first take of f0022; UPDATES with Grand Met winning
Pillsbury's agreement to takeover.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC won its 2{-month battle
for Pillsbury Co. after the food and restaurant company agreed to an
increased offer of $66 a share or $5.68 billion from the big British
conglomerate.
   Pillsbury's board voted to endorse the new bid, which was raised
from a previous offer of $63 a share, two days after a Delaware
judge struck down its ``poison pill'' takeover defense.
   Retired Justice William Duffy of Chancery Court in Wilmington,
Del., also issued an order Friday blocking Pillsbury's plan to spin
off its Miami-based Burger King Corp., another key element of the
company's defense against Grand Met.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors have stepped up pressure on
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. to settle as-yet unfiled securities
fraud charges, expanding the scope of their original inquiry and
exacting cooperation from at least three employees of the
beleaguered Wall Street firm.
   ``There's no question the investigation has shifted into other
areas,'' said one source, who spoke Friday on condition he not be
identified. ``They've probably come to the realization they don't
have enough.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite large November increases for gasoline
and heating oil, the government says wholesale prices continue to
rise at an annual rate of less than 4 percent, confounding
predictions of a mounting inflation problem.
   Wholesale prices edged up just 0.3 percent in November as food
costs at the wholesale level showed no increases for the second
straight month, the Labor Department said Friday.
   The November increase, if it persisted for 12 months, would
amount to an annual inflation rate of just 3.3 percent, lower than
the 3.8 percent annualized rate for the first 11 months of 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction in November reached its
highest level in seven months, the government said in a report
viewed as a sign of a robust economy.
   The Commerce Department said Friday new homes and apartments were
built at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.56 million units
last month, up from the 1.54 million rate in October.
   It was the third increase in a row and the highest level of
construction activity since April. Housing starts soared 5.1 percent
in October and rose 0.4 percent in September.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators said they were providing
$118.3 million in assistance to a subsidiary of Ford Motor Co. to
rescue two Michigan savings institutions.
   The two _ First Dearborn and Bloomfield Savings and Loan
Association _ are being acquired by First Nationwide Bank, which is
based in San Francisco but is owned by Ford Motor Co.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Express Corp. has agreed to buy the
parent of the Flying Tigers air freight line in an $880 million deal
that would give the overnight-package company a foothold in the
international air cargo business.
   Under an agreement approved Friday by the boards of directors of
both companies, Federal Express will make a $20.87{ a share cash
tender offer Dec. 20 for all Tiger International's 40.8 million
common shares and equivalents.
   The purchase of Tiger International Inc. would combine Memphis,
Tenn.-based Federal Express, the nation's biggest express package
shipper, with the cargo carrier founded by American pilots who
volunteered to fly for China in the early years of World War II.
</TEXT>
