<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined slightly today amid
continuing worries about the outlook for interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped .89 to 2,149.82
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 7 to 4 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 311 up, 556 down and
512 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 19.41 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said the Federal Reserve appeared likely to continue
tightening credit to restrain economic growth that keeps exceeding
most people's expectations.
   Consumer spending is generally described as strong going into the
last week of the Christmas selling season.
   The Fed has not raised its discount rate since Aug. 9, when it
increased the charge it imposes on loans to private financial
institutions from 6 percent to 6{ percent.
   But brokers said the Fed has taken other measures to tighten
credit conditions as recently as last week, and may be planning a
new discount-rate increase in the first few weeks of 1989.
   ``While consumers spread holiday cheer, the Fed is casting itself
as Scrooge,'' said Donald Straszheim, chief economist at Merrill
Lynch, in a weekend bulletin to the firm's clients.
   Among actively traded blue chips, International Business Machines
rose [ to 121]; Ford Motor was unchanged at 50}, and General
Electric dropped [ to 44~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.24 to 154.92. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .05 at 297.32.
   On Friday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 17.71 to
2,150.71, finishing the week with a net gain of 7.22 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 2 to 1 on the
NYSE, with 1,008 up, 448 down and 496 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 196.48 million shares, against 136.82
million in the previous session. The NYSE's composite index added
.99 to 155.16.
