<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   12-19 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0275</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mixed to
mostly lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Traders cited three factors for slipping prices, but singled out
confirmation of a big export deal to the Soviet Union as the main
culprit.
   Rumors that the Soviets would buy 400,000 tons of soymeal and 2.5
million tons of corn pushed prices higher on Friday. That in turn
prompted increased farmer selling over the weekend _ a second factor
pressuring prices today.
   But commodities also were hurt by reports of rain over the
weekend in the bean growing regions of South America and a forecast
calling for more during the week ahead.
   On the opening, wheat was 1{ cents lower to \ cent higher, with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.36 a bushel; corn was 1\
cents to \ cent lower, with December at $2.73 a bushel; oats were
unchanged to 1 cent lower, with March at $2.29 a bushel; and
soybeans were 1 cent lower to 1\ cents higher, with January at
$7.85{ a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures prices were mostly higher at the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent lower to .40 cent higher, with December
at 73.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .27 cent
higher, with January at 84.30 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent
lower to .33 cent higher, with December at 44 cents a pound; and
frozen pork bellies were .40 cent to .53 cent higher, with February
at 45.65 cents a pound.
