<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1441EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-YE--Mergers-Junk Adv00   12-19 0841</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-YE--Mergers-Junk, Adv 00,0876</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release in Yearend Editions</NOTE>
<HEAD>LBO `Junk' Is In the Eyes Of the Holder</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-YE--Mergers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporate America's reliance on borrowed money
was never more prevalent than in 1988, when a flood of takeover
activity was unleashed.
   Businesses swallowed each other up with a vengeance, regardless
of size; and those that tried to resist were forced to make drastic
structural changes. To finance these acquisitions, leveraged buyouts
or restructurings many firms turned to the $180 billion public
``junk'' bond market _ where companies whose credit ratings are
below investment grade offer high interest rates to compensate for
bigger risks.
   Once a last resort in public financing, junk bonds played a
pivotal role in the wave of takeovers this past year and have gained
wider acceptance, and perhaps even more respect in the eyes of
investors and corporate executives.
   ``As more and more companies use high-yield debt to finance their
growth ... it becomes a regular alternative in terms of raising
capital,'' said Robert S. Waill, managing director for high-yield
research at L.F. Rothschild & Co. ``It's almost commonplace.''
   But all that has come at the expense of the high-grade corporate
market, which includes the elite 5 percent of U.S. companies with
investment-grade ratings, the nation's bread-and-butter
manufacturers. Fears of large corporate takeovers, and even bigger
debt loads, scared many investors away from bonds of indust~
companies this past year.
   Non-investment-grade companies are drawn to the junk bond
market's seemingly endless supply of funds, especially since it has
enabled them to offer a price high enough to persuade a target
company's shareholders to sell.
   Tax laws also have made junk bond financing attractive by
allowing interest payments to be deducted as a cost of doing
business. Companies that raise money through issuing new stock can't
do the same with stock dividends.
   And it costs less to borrow from the public than banks, even
though junk bond yields are usually around four percentage points
higher than comparable Treasury bonds.
   As of mid-December there were 148 public junk bond issues valued
at $27.17 billion, 56 percent of which were used primarily for
financing LBOs or acquisitions, according to the independent
financial-research firm Securities Data Co. Just three years ago,
about 27 percent of the $13.19 billion in junk bond issues were used
toward acquisitions, it said.
   Bond investors and traders are bracing for a deluge of big issues
in 1989, largely as a result of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.'s
record $24.5 billion buyout of consumer products giant RJR Nabisco
Inc.
   While the bulk of the financing, $14 billion, will come from a
commercial bank syndicate, $5 billion will be through junk bonds.
Another $5 billion of existing RJR bonds is certain to be downgraded
to junk since the enormous debt load will make it harder for RJR to
pay off previous debts, therefore increasing the risk factor.
   It was that deal and other megadeals and proposals _ including
Philip Morris Co.'s $12.9 billion acquisition of Kraft Inc. _ that
sent the industrial bond market into a frenzy this past year. Bond
prices plummeted and trading came to a virtual standstill on fears
that any company, regardless of size, could become a takeover target
or aggressor, and in the process load itself up with new debt.
   The so-called ``event risk'' fears consequently have hurt
supplies. In November alone domestic industrial corporations sold
only two new bond issues in the United States, totaling about $250
million. That was down sharply from six bond issues totaling $1
billion the previous month.
   While investors suffered some losses on industrial bonds, they've
seen their rate of return on junk go up.
   Marshall B. Front, who manages mutual funds for the investment
banking firm Stein Roe & Farnham, said the high-yield bond portfolio
has a rate of return of 11.25 percent, compared with 7.2 percent for
the investment-grade bond portfolio and 17 percent for equities.
   ``The interest rates are very high and to some extent high-yield
paper represents less volatile surrogates to equities,'' said Gene
Wong, a managing director at Prudential-Bache Securities.
   Although mutual funds, insurance companies and pension funds hold
most of the outstanding junk bond issues, around 70 percent, foreign
interest has increased significantly. Foreign market share now
totals around 3 percent, compared to just a small fraction a few
years ago, according to a General Accounting report released in
February and analysts.
   The last six years of economic expansion have been a boon to the
junk market by helping to keep defaults down, but many portfolio
managers worry that an economic turndown will reverse that trend.
   ``We're concerned that the junk bond default rate has not been
tested in recent conditions and therefore we're not certain that the
total returns from junk are what they appear to be,'' said Philip R.
Roberts, a senior vice president for Aetna Life and Casualty Co.
   Aetna's $65 billion investment portfolio includes only $200
million of junk bonds.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
