<DOCNO> AP881219-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1410EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-NorthropPayouts 1stLd-Writethru   12-19 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northrop Payouts, 1st Ld-Writethru,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Northrop Officials May Have Received Money Intended For
Koreans</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `There was ...' with company comment; SUBS 11th
graf, `Northrop has...' to CORRECT spelling to Northrop, sted
Northrup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department is investigating
whether Northrop Corp. officials received some of the $7.75 million
the company paid to South Koreans in 1984 in a failed attempt to
obtain a jet fighter contract, a newspaper reported today.
   It is unclear which Northrop executives are under investigation,
the Los Angeles Times reported.
   However, a grand jury earlier this year subpoenaed Northrop's
chairman, as well as four former Northrop executives who left the
Los Angeles-based aerospace company following disclosures about a
Korean hotel deal to be funded by Northrop.
   The Times, citing unidentified sources, also reported that a
Northrop consultant, once paid to introduce company officials to
Korean leaders, may have received as much as $1 million of the
payments.
   In Seoul, South Korea, authorities today arrested a South Korean
businessman and charged him with taking $3.5 million in bribes from
Northrop to promote the sale of the F-20 Tigershark fighter planes.
   The businessman, Lee Min-ha, allegedly collaborated with a former
Korean presidential bodyguard, Park Jong-kyu, who acted as an agent
for Northrop in trying to sell 200 F-20s to South Korea, prosecutors
said. Park, a relative of Lee, died in 1985.
   Tony Cantafio, a spokesman for Los Angeles-based Northrop,
declined to comment on the reports of broadened grand jury and IRS
investigations.
   The Internal Revenue Service has begun its own investigation of
Northrop's 1984 payments to the Koreans, apparently to determine
whether American recipients of the money properly reported the
income, the Times said.
   The federal grand jury here is investigating whether Northrop
violated the U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act by making with
various payments to at least three organizations controlled by
Korean political operator Park Chong Kyu. The act bars U.S.
companies from making direct or indirect payments to foreign
government officials.
   Most of the payments apparently were made to build a hotel in
Seoul as an indirect way to help the Korean government finance
purchases of the F-20 fighters, the Times said.
   Northrop has said it invested in the hotel venture as part of a
legal ``offset'' agreement to demonstrate that in return for the jet
contract, the company was willing to help boost the Korean economy.
   Northrop also funded two other South Korean groups controlled by
Park, the Dong Yang Express Group and Bankaborrow, which apparently
were involved to help sell and finance the F-20, the newspaper
reported.
   But the aerospace firm never sold any of the fighters, the hotel
never was built and the money is unaccounted for.
   Northrop has filed a civil lawsuit in South Korea, alleging it
was defrauded in the deal. But the company never registered the deal
with South Korean authorities, and a former Northrop consultant has
alleged the payments were part of a lobbying fund.
   A parallel investigation of the funds by a panel of the House
Energy and Commerce Committee has uncovered evidence indicating that
Northrop consultant Jimmy Shin, a former Honolulu night club
operator, may have received $1 million of the money, the Times said.
   Through a subpoena, the subcommittee on oversight and
investigation obtained information on a $1 million bank draft to
Shin drawn on the Korea Exchange Bank's account with Manufacturers
Hanover Trust Co. That account is believed to be part of Northrop's
hotel fund, the newspaper said.
   Northrop has paid Shin $102,000 a year for several years for his
consulting work, including introducing Northrop officials to South
Koreans.
   The grand jury has subpoenaed Northrop Chairman Thomas V. Jones,
former Executive Vice President Welko Gasich, former Chief Financial
Officer William J. McGagh, former Vice President James Dorsey,
former Vice President Donald Foulds and Shin.
   The four executives resigned after the Korean hotel deal was made
public early this year. All declined comment on the latest
investigation, the Times said.
</TEXT>
