<HEAD>London Shares Fall in Dull Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates throughout with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices fell slightly in a lackluster session on the
London Stock Exchange Monday as the approaching holidays and
upcoming balance of payments data for November gave little reason
for activity.
   ``There just hasn't been much trade around to speak of,'' one
market maker said. ``People are simply loath to do anything'' before
the Christmas holiday and the announcement of British trade figures
scheduled for Friday, he added.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index fell 3.2
points or 0.18 percent, to 1770.5, also the intraday low.
   Volume was a subdued 369.3 million shares, compared with the
473.9 million shares which changed hands Friday.
   Although Wall Street opened on sound footing, it did llittle to
shore up support in the London market, dealers offered. By the close
of the London session, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up a
healthy 12.68 points at 2163.39.
   Commentators cautioned that trade figures due for release Friday
would likely keep players anxious and sidelined during the coming
week, unless unexpected news emerges to draw them off the fence.
</TEXT>
