<DOCNO> AP881219-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1517EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CSXT-Crews     12-19 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CSXT-Crews,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rail Company Says Crew-Reduction Contract Ratified</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CSX Transportation Inc. announced
Monday members of the United Transportation Union have ratified a
labor agreement that will immediately reduce the size of train crews
on about 30 percent of its operations.
   The agreement covers CSXT employees on the former Louisville &
Nashville, Clinchfield, and Nashville, Chattanooga and St. Louis
lines, the company said.
   Under the deal, one of the two brakeman on most trains will be
eliminated.
   ``This breakthrough agreement is unique among major railroads
because we can now immediately run freight trains in the covered
areas with a locomotive engineer, a conductor and one breakman
without phasing in the reduced crews through attrition of the
workforce,'' said John Snow, CSX president and chief operating
officer.
   He said the result would be a more-efficient freight service.
   The agreement says employees in active service may elect to
receive a separation allowance of $50,000, transfer to another
location and receive up to $20,000 in relocation expenses, or accept
a furlough with rights to return, plus a $15,000 payment.
   Snow said the contract efforts are part of CSXT's goal of
reducing employment on its 19-state rail system to 30,000 employees,
while reducing its route milage to 15,000 from 20,000 miles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
