<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain and Soybeans Post Modest Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mixed to
mostly higher Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   ``The market acted much better than anybody expected, given the
bearish news we started with,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Traders said both pits opened under pressure because of a lack of
confirmation of a big export deal to the Soviet Union that set up
Friday's rally.
   Rumors the Soviets would buy 400,000 tons of soymeal and 2.5
million tons of corn also was behind increased farmer selling over
the weekend. That selling was a second factor pressuring prices.
   On top of that, the market reacted early to reports of rain over
the weekend in the soybean growing regions of South America and a
forecast calling for more during the week ahead.
   ``Even though the bears pushed it down a little bit, they never
really broke it,'' Lespinasse said.
   He said buying came from traders who discounted the bad news and
had faith in the underlying values in the commodities.
   On the close, wheat was { cent lower to 4\ cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.37 a bushel; corn was 3}
cents lower to 1\ cent higher, with December at $2.70{ a bushel;
oats were 1 cent to 3{ cents higher, with December at $2.25 a
bushel; and soybeans were 5{ cents to 13{ cents higher, with January
at $7.94 a bushel.
</TEXT>
