<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1615EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Cutbacks     12-19 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Cutbacks,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smith Barney, Citicorp Cutting Back London Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citicorp and Smith Barney Harris Upham
International Inc. said Monday they were cutting back their equity
trading operations in Britain.
   Several brokerage firms recently have trimmed their British
operations, citing low trading volume following last year's stock
market crash and strong competition among market makers in the wake
of the Big Bang, the 1986 deregulation of Britain's financial
markets.
   Smith Barney said it was ending its fixed-income sales and
trading and other operations at its London office. Fifty employees,
some of whom will be reassigned, would be affected, the company said.
   The company said the move reflected a ``strategic refocus of its
major business sectors.''
   Citicorp's London brokerage firm, Citicorp Scrimgeour Vickers,
said it reduced the number of British stocks in which it makes
markets from 600 to 400.
   Citicorp's latest move would not involve any job losses, said
Martin Burton, head of market making at the firm. However the number
of market makers has already been halved this year from 80 to 40,
Burton said.
   Earlier this month, Morgan Grenfell Group PLC withdrew completely
from market making in British equities and government bonds, cutting
450 jobs. Last week, Kleinwort Benson Group PLC cut 35 staff from
its equity department.
   Market makers are the specialist brokers that continuously quote
prices in certain stocks on the London market's screen-based trading
system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
