<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Denny's Doors, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wanted: Holiday Locks for 'Round-the-Clock Eatery</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd-3rd grafs to CORRECT that some doors had locked but
keys were missing.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LA MIRADA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Denny's restaurants, which boast an
``Always Open'' sign at each location, will change policy for one
day to allow employees to have Christmas off. But there's one
problem.
   Since the restaurants are always open, they never have to lock
the doors. In fact, some don't have locks on the doors and others
have locks that have never been used and for which keys cannot be
found, said Joe Herrera, director of marketing.
   This week, the chain is installing new locks on about 700
restaurants, Herrera said.
   ``This is all new to us,'' said Jerry Richardson, president of TW
Services, Denny's parent company.
   The La Mirada-based food chain also has to come up with closing
policies, but Richardson said the dilemma is the price to be paid
for holiday spirit.
   ``Since management has the day off, we thought our thousands of
field employees deserved the same courtesy,'' he said.
   About 200 of Denny's 1,221 restaurants are franchise operations
and about 50 or 60 of them will stay open, said Judy Lynes, a
publicist for Denny's.
   All the others will close at 7 p.m. Christmas Eve and stay closed
through Christmas Day for the first time since the chain of
restaurants was founded 35 years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
