<DOCNO> AP881219-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1640EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MediaGeneral     12-19 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Media General,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Media General Gets Back Sugarman-Controlled Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Media General Inc. acquired California
investor Burt Sugarman's stake in the publishing company on Monday,
swapping a California paper mill for Sugarman-controlled Media
General stock.
   The $100 million deal also included a $44 million payment by
Media General to companies controlled by Sugarman.
   In a joint announcement, James S. Evans, president of Media
General, and Sugarman said an agreement was reached to sell Media
General's Pomona, Calif., paper mill to Sugarman's Giant Group Ltd.
and Barris Industries Inc., in exchange for Media General stock held
by Giant and Barris.
   The deal was part of a complete redemption of the 2.8 million
Media General shares held by Sugarman's companies, or 10 percent of
Media General's outstanding shares. Sugarman had said earlier that
the shares cost him $111.6 million, or an average of $40.14 per
share.
   Earlier this year, Sugarman failed in a bid to take over Media
General, whose publications include the Richmond Times-Dispatch, The
Richmond News Leader and several other daily and weekly newspapers.
Sugarman also unsuccessfully sought a seat for himself and two
associates on the nine-member Media General board at the company's
annual meeting in May.
   Sugarman offered $70 per share, or $1.8 billion, for the company.
   David L. Jordan, Media General's vice president, said Sugarman
has agreed to drop remaining attempts to take over the company,
including an appeal of a court decision that upheld the legality of
Media General's dual stock structure.
   D. Tennant Bryan, Media General chairman, and J.Stewart Bryan
III, vice chairman, control Media General's Class B shares, which
have more than 70 percent of the stock voting power. A merger
involving Media General would require approval of two-thirds of the
closely-held Class B stock.
   Evans said the agreement, subject to certain conditions that
could include a third-party purchase of the California paper mill,
represented Media General's continued shift toward communications
properties.
   However, the company will retain its interests in three other
newsprint mills.
   Sugarman is a Hollywood movie and television producer whose
programs include game shows such as The New Dating Game.
   George F. Shipp, vice president and stock analyst at Investment
Corp. of Virginia in Norfolk, said the deal announced Monday allowed
Media General to get rid of Sugarman by sacrificing an asset that
was not critical to its operations and without leveraging its
balance sheet.
</TEXT>
