<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1641EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Pepperell-Farley     12-19 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pepperell-Farley,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pepperell, Farley Proxy Fight For Board Set</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hostile suitor Farley Inc. has succeeded in
forcing West Point-Pepperell Inc. to call a shareholders' meeting to
vote on a new board of directors, the threatened textile giant said
Monday.
   Pepperell said in a statement from its West Point, Ga.,
headquarters it had confirmed that holders of about 27 percent of
the company's common stock _ including Farley's 9.8 percent stake _
had called for the meeting.
   The Pepperell board was required to call the meeting if requested
to do so by holders of 25 percent of its common stock. The statement
said the board, which probably would meet later this week, was
expected to schedule the meeting for Feb. 25.
   On Oct. 25, Farley offered $1.4 billion, or $48 per share, for
Pepperell, an offer which the company's directors dismissed as
inadequate. They claimed Farley's bid was an effort to get the
company befgs from a then-incomplete
takeover of J.P. Stevens & Co. Inc.
   Farley, the Chicago-based manufacturer of Fruit of the Loom
underwear and Acme boots, asked other stockholders on Dec. 1 to join
in requesting the meeting in an attempt to thwart management's
resistance to the tender offer.
   Farley's request for the meeting said it would propose to remove
Pepperell's 11 current directors, replacing them with an entirely
new slate.
   A Farley-backed board would be expected to rescind certain
``poison pill'' anti-takeover provisions from Pepperell's bylaws
that would increase the cost of the billion takeover attempt.
   However, the scheduling of a meeting does not guarantee Farley's
efforts to oust the board would succeed. Farley still must seek
support for its as-yet-unnamed nominees.
   Farley spokesman Jack Albertine said Monday the company's stake
in Pepperell, plus shares already tendered to Farley, give the
hostile suitor about 56 percent of Pepperell's outstanding stock.
However, the tenders do not carry voting rights.
   Farley objects to recent changes in the bylaws that allowed
management to purchase additional shares, resulting in a possible
$1.9 million profit to Pepperell Chairman Joseph L. Lanier Jr. and
$1.2 million to President Don J. Keller.
   Other changes benefiting management, including so-called ``golden
parachutes'' for directors, have ``effectively prohibited any
acquisition proposal or tender offer which lacks management's
support, no matter how beneficial to shareholders,'' Farley's
request for the meeting said.
   Farley also has filed lawsuits challenging Georgia's
anti-takeover statutes.
   Pepperell, the country's largest publicly held textile
manufacturer, has countered with lawsuits claiming Farley's bid
violates security and banking regulations because it is financed
with too much debt.
   It also charges that Farley's financial adviser, Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc., improperly has used information gained during
Pepperell's takeover this year of Stevens and that Drexel is a
full-fledged bidder in the deal and has failed to disclose that to
regulators.
   A federal district judge has agreed with portions of both
lawsuits, sending the case to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, where a hearing is scheduled Jan. 11.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881219-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1647EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Britain-GrandMet Bjt   12-19 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Grand Met, Bjt,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury Fits Well Into Grand Met's Strategy, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. fits Grand Metropolitan PLC's
international expansion strategy, even though some Grand Met
shareholders have been concerned that Pillsbury was an ailing target
that nobody else apparently wanted, analysts said Monday.
   Mineapolis-based Pillsbury, which has suffered poor earnings,
management turmoil and discontent among franchisees of its Burger
King fast-food chain, said Sunday it agreed to be taken over by
Grand Met for $5.68 billion cash, or $66 a share.
   Grand Met originally offered $60 a share on Oct. 4 and no other
suitor stepped in during the 2{-month takeover battle, which largely
was fought in the courts and the newspapers.
   ``We see Pillsbury as a real opportunity and very much look
forward to get into it and work with the people there,'' Tim
Halford, a Grand Met spokesman, said Monday.
   Chairman Allen Sheppard was not available for an interview,
Halford said.
   When completed, the acquisition would be the largest, non-oil
foreign acquisition by a British company. British buyers _ already
among the biggest foreign purchasers of American properties _ have
stepped up purchases of U.S. companies in recent years, spurred by
the weaker dollar.
   Grand Met has been one of the more active buyers, engaging in
several billion dollars worth of transactions in the United States
and elsewhere in the past year.
   Also on Monday, Grand Met announced it acquired two European
restaurant chains for a total of about 20 million pounds, or about
$37 million at current exchange rates. They are the West German
Wienerwald, which operates 231 outlets, and the Spaghetti Factory,
with five restaurants in Switzerland.
   Pillsbury, whose products include Green Giant vegetables, Van De
Kamp's frozen fish, and Haagen-Dazs ice cream, fits in well with
Grand Met's strategy of focusing on foods, liquor and retailing and
expanding those businesses worldwide, analysts said.
   Grand Met's own brands include J and B Scotch whisky, Smirnoff
vodka, Alpo pet foods and Pearle vision care products.
   Andrew Buchanan, an analyst with Hoare Govett Ltd., said:
``Pillsbury represents a great deal for them, even at the higher
price.''
   ``It's a good strategy,'' Buchanan said. ``Number one brands in
the largest domestic market in the world should be susceptible to
internationalization.''
   Grand Met's strong liquor operations have little room for
improvement, said Ron Littleboy, an analyst with the investment firm
Nomura Securities in London.
   ``The other two areas, retailing and food, particularly food,
were starting to look like they were left behind, very much U.K.
oriented, very strong brands in the U.K., with no international
presence. That's what Pillsbury does.
   ``Pillsbury should give them those opportunities to see just how
good they are in food,'' Littleboy said.
   Although the analysts said they were confident Grand Met could
turn Pillsbury around, Grand Met's share price has been depressed by
shareholder concern over the acquisition.
   Grand Met's shares fell the equivalent of 1.8 cents to finish at
$7.89 in Monday trading on the London Stock Exchange.
   ``With so many people in the U.S. saying how badly managed
Pillsbury was, it has been harder for Grand Met to convince its own
shareholders what a good deal it is,'' Littleboy said.
   Grand Met's shares would be trading 15 percent higher had it not
been for the takeover, Littleboy estimated, which he said ``implies
skepticism, to say the least.''
   But ``given their (Grand Met's) record and their management,
personally I have confidence they can'' get Pillsbury on the right
track, Littleboy said.
   Here are details of other recent Grand Met acquisitions and a
disposal:
   On Friday, Grand Met announced the purchase of Sears PLC's
William Hill betting chain for $606 million cash.
   Grand Met lost in November a takeover battle for Irish Distillers
Co. PLC, which makes Irish whiskey. Irish Distillers was taken over
by friendly suitor Pernod Ricard SA, the French liquor company.
   In early October, Grand Met announced the sale of its 100-hotel
Inter-Continental chain to the Seibu Saison Group of Japan for $2.27
billion.
   Grand Met acquired the U.S. distiller Heublein Inc. for $1.3
billion last year. It bought U.S.-based Liggett Group Inc., a
tobacco company, for $450 million in 1980.
</TEXT>
