<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed; Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against some foreign currencies
and fell against others Monday in light trading as major traders
prepared to close their books at the end of the year.
   Corporate customers and banks that deal in currencies are
unlikely to take big positions for or against the dollar in the last
two weeks of the year for fear of guessing wrong and spoiling their
year-end financial statements, said Frank Conte, vice president for
foreign exchange in the New York office of Barclays Bank PLC.
   ``Why risk it?'' Conte said.
   Dealers said there was still some talk in the market that the
Federal Reserve would hike its discount rate, although few believed
a Fed move will occur before the beginning of the new year. The
discount rate is what the central bank charges commercial banks for
loans.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.08 yen to a closing 124.02 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 124.05 yen. In New York, it fell to 124.08
yen from 124.14 yen.
   The dollar fell against the British pound in London and New York.
In London it cost $1.8230 to buy one pound, dearer than $1.8150 late
Friday. In New York the pound rose to $1.8209 from $1.8193.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
prices, included: 1.7645 West German marks, up from 1.7584; 1.4891
Swiss francs, up from 1.4820; 1.1998 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2305; 6.0270 French francs, up from 6.0090; and 1,300.75 Italian
lire, up from 1,296.50.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday's
prices, included: 1.7625 West German marks, down from 1.7635; 1.4870
Swiss francs, down from 1.4895; 6.0235 French francs, up from
5.9950; 1.9895 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9805; 1,296.50 Italian
lire, unchanged; and 1.1995 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2035.
   In Hong Kong, gold bullion rose 38 cents to close at a bid
$415.62 a troy ounce.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $414.25 a troy ounce
from $412.25 bid late Friday. In Zurich, gold closed at a bid
$412.25, unchanged from late Friday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $414.40 a troy ounce, up from $414 on Friday.
   Later, Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at
$414 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from $413.50 an ounce late
Friday.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.08 a troy ounce, compared with
Friday's $6.12. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery closed at $6.110 a troy ounce, up from $6.082.
</TEXT>
