<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0537</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market climbed to a two-month high
Monday, extending its yearend rally despite worries about the
outlook for interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 21.97 to 2,172.68,
not far short of the 1988 closing high of 2,183.50 it reached on
Oct. 21.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 5 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
841 up, 598 down and 538 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 162.25 million
shares, down from 196.48 million Friday, when the total was swollen
by a ``triple witching hour'' involving expiring stock-index futures
and options.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 196.36 million shares.
   Analysts said the market benefited from talk of more takeovers
and buyouts, and from buying by program traders engaged in multiple
strategies.
   At the same time, market-watchers said the Federal Reserve
appeared likely to continue tightening credit to restrain economic
growth that keeps exceeding most people's expectations.
   Consumer spending was generally described as strong going into
the last week of the Christmas selling season.
   The Fed has not raised its discount rate since Aug. 9, when it
increased the charge it imposes on loans to private financial
institutions from 6 percent to 6{ percent.
   But brokers said the Fed has taken other measures to tighten
credit conditions as recently as last week, and may be planning a
new discount-rate increase in the first few weeks of 1989.
   ``While consumers spread holiday cheer, the Fed is casting itself
as Scrooge,'' said Donald Straszheim, chief economist at Merrill
Lynch, in a weekend bulletin to the firm's clients.
   Pillsbury gained 3[ to 65]. The company ended a long battle by
agreeing to Grand Metropolitan's offer to acquire it for $66 a share.
   Tiger International picked up { to 19~ on top of a 2{-point gain
Friday, when the company agreed to be taken over by Federal Express
for $20.875 a share.
   General Motors was up 2 at 87}. The company said it was
considering buying some of its Class H stock from the Howard Hughes
Medical Institute.
   Among other actively traded blue chips, International Business
Machines rose 1{ to 122}; American Telephone & Telegraph { to 30;
Exxon | to 46[, and General Electric 1 to 46.
   Microsoft, which drew a recommendation from Shearson Lehman
Hutton, climbed 1 to 50} in the over-the-counter market.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $17.62 billion, or 0.65
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
1.22 to 156.38.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 3.27 to 321.97, and S&P's
500-stock composite index was up 2.62 at 278.91.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market added
.59 to 376.39. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 298.70, up 1.33.
