<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1815EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-19 0863</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0892</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Platinum Takes Another Big Hit; Coffee Continues Percolating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum futures prices closed sharply lower for the third
consecutive session Monday, but recovered some ground after key
South African producers implied the use of Ford Motor Co.'s
platinum-free catalytic converters might be limited to the United
States.
   On other markets, coffee futures prices continued to rise as a
dockworkers' strike in the major producing country of Brazil
promised scarce supplies during the peak consumption season; energy
futures dipped as temperatures rose; and grain and soybean futures
prices fought off early pressures to register modest gains.
   After platinum plunged the daily trading limit of $25 an ounce
for two straight sessions, officials at the New York Mercantile
Exchange increased the limit to $37.50 early Monday and the January
contract promptly hit the new floor.
   That's when South African producers mounted a counterattack,
implying to analysts that Ford's revolutionary catalytic converters
had replaced platinum with palladium _ a metal the plaqtinum
producers contend will be ineffective in dealing with the leaded gas
still very much in use outside the United States.
   ``That may have helped shore up platinum,'' said Bette
Raptopolous of Prudential-Bache Securities, New York, ``but it's a
good guess how much and how long.
   ``The U.S. market was responsible for 55 percent (of the platinum
used in catalytic converters), so if it's not a catastrophe for
platinum,'' she added, ``it's not far from one either.''
   Most of the West's supply of platinum comes from South African
mines. Ford, which announced its technological breakthrough last
week, has declined so far to reveal the new materials in its
converters.
   Platinum rose $4.50 for the spot month, with the contract for
delivery in December reaching $529.30 a troy ounce. But the precious
metal declined $29.20 to $30.70 an ounce for the deferred months.
Palladium, also traded at the New York Mercantile Exchange, was down
$2.15 to $4.40.
   Gold, meanwhile, was up 40 cents to 50 cents an ounce, with
December at the Comex at $414.40 a troy ounce. Silver was up 2.5
cents to 2.8 cents an ounce, with December at $6.11 an ounce.
   Coffee futures enjoyed a fourth straight session of gains at the
New York, Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa Exchange as a dockworkers' strike
in Brazil approached the one-week mark and other Central American
exporters and South American rival Colombia were saddled with
problems of their own.
   ``Either there's harvest delays because of bad weather, or
transportation problems getting to port,'' said Sandra Kaul, analyst
with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   ``And even those that have the coffee in port are having trouble
because they're only allowed to export so much during each quarter
and they're already at quota,'' she added.
   Coffee futures climbed 3.13 cents to 5.89 cents, with December at
145.38 cents a pound.
   A turnaround in weekly weather forecasts was called the main
culprit in an across-the-board drop in energy futures at the New
York Mercantile Exchange.
   ``They got slapped down a notch because everybody was calling for
colder-than-usual temperatures and they got turned around,'' said
Jim Ritterbusch, vice president for trading and research at Carson
Petroleum Inc. in Chicago. ``Traders bailed out of their long
positions in heating oil and pulled everything else down.''
   Crude oil slipped 0.14 to 0.41 cents, with January at $16.31 a
barrel; heating oil was down 0.75 cent to 1.27 cents, with January
at 50.75 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was 0.45 cent lower
to 0.22 cent higher, January at 45.35 cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mixed to mostly higher on
the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Traders said both pits opened under pressure because of a lack of
confirmation of a big export deal to the Soviet Union that set up
Friday's rally.
   Rumors the Soviets would buy 400,000 tons of soymeal and 2.5
million tons of corn also was behind increased farmer selling over
the weekend _ a second factor pressuring prices.
   And on top of that, the market reacted early to reports of rain
over the weekend in the soybean growing regions of South America and
a forecast calling for more during the week ahead.
   ``Even though the bears pushed it down a little bit, they never
really broke it,''said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Wheat was unchanged to 3{ cents higher, with December at $4.36{ a
bushel; corn was 3} cents lower to 1\ cent higher, with December at
$2.70{ a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 3} cents higher, with December
at $2.25\ a bushel; and soybeans were 7 cents to 13{ cents higher,
with January at $7.93{ a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures prices were mixed at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .38 cent lower to .45 cent higher, with December
at 73.65 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .03 cent to .32 cent
lower, with January at 83.85 cents a pound; live hogs were .35 cent
lower to .83 cent higher, with December at 44.65 cents a pound; and
frozen pork bellies were unchanged to .90 cent higher, with February
at 45.40 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
