<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Eastern-Trump 3rdLd-Writethru   12-19 0904</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern-Trump, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0931</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Approves Sale of Eastern Air Shuttle to Trump</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 8th graf, ``Trump already,'' with Trump
comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Monday approved the sale of
Eastern Airlines' Northeastern shuttle service to real estate
magnate Donald Trump, a $365 million deal that labor leaders had
challenged as a union-busting effort.
   Texas Air Corp., the Houston-based holding company that is
Eastern's parent firm, has been trying to sell off the profitable
shuttle, arguing that struggling Eastern needs the cash to survive.
   But the carrier's unions have argued that the shuttle sale is
simply a guise for Texas Air's true motive: to dismantle Eastern,
whose 30,000 workers are represented by three militant unions, and
eventually reconstruct it as a non-union airline.
   ``There is no doubt that an ongoing struggle has and will
continue to exist between Eastern and its'' unions, U.S. District
Judge Barrington D. Parker wrote in his opinion. ``However, the
court feels that equally plausible is the idea that management is
seeking to rebuild the company and place it on a sound financial
footing.''
   The transaction must still be approved by the Department of
Transportation, which must affirm that Trump can operate the shuttle
safely and manage it properly.
   The flamboyant Trump announced his agreement to purchase the
shuttle for cash on Oct. 12, saying he would turn the shuttle, which
makes hourly flights among Boston, New York and Washington, into
``an absolute diamond.''
   He said he would rename the service ``The Trump Shuttle,'' and
redecorate its 17 Boeing 727 jetliners, including painting them with
gold, red and black stripes.
   Trump already owns casinos in Atlantic City, N.J., a helicopter
service that flies between the gambling center and New York, the
Plaza Hotel in New York and other prestigious properties.
   Speaking from his New York office, Trump said he planned to begin
service on the new shuttle in February.
   ``This is now a business deal that does not have obstacles in its
path,'' he said.
   Phil Bakes, Eastern's president and chief executive officer, said
the carrier was ``gratified at the court's decision today.''
   ``We're committed to focusing our energies on solving the real
problems at Eastern,'' Bakes added. ``We want to resolve our
economic problems at the bargaining table and would welcome the
presence of the union leaders at the bargaining table to join us in
moving this airline forward.''
   Jack Bavis, chairman of the Air Line Pilots Association, said:
``We're diappointed in the outcome but we'll continiue to do
everything we can to secure the rights and future of Eastern
pilots.''
   Bavis also said the decision ``is not a major setback in our
efforts to prevent Texas Air from dismantling Eastern Airlines. We
are studying the options still available to us and will continue to
pursue this issue in Congress and elsewhere.''
   Joseph Guerrieri Jr., the Washington attorney for the
International Association of Machinists, said the union was
disappointed in Parker's ruling and would appeal it.
   ``Our concern is for the employees who remain with Eastern,''
Guerrieri said. ``We believe this is the death knell for Eastern.''
   The Transport Workers Union, representing Eastern's flight
attendants, also joined the suit.
   On Dec. 2, the unions asked Parker to block the deal, saying it
violated federal labor laws by undermining employees' working
conditions without bargaining over them first with union leaders.
   But Parker ruled that the shuttle deal did not trigger the labor
law's protections. He noted that in September, the courts had
approved a far more severe scheduling constriction by Eastern that
involved 4,000 layoffs, the elimination of service to 14 cities and
the curtailment of 15 percent of the carrier's flights.
   ``The impact of the sale to Trump Shuttle pales in comparison to
the impact of the September 1988 schedule change,'' the judge wrote.
   The shuttle, which employs 850 people and makes 62 flights daily,
has been one of Eastern's few profit-makers, earning an annual
average profit of $17 million over the last five years, according to
Eastern spokesman Robin Matell. Overall, Eastern lost $233.7 million
over the first nine months of 1988, he said.
   Parker wrote that if the unions are right and the airline is not
truly trying to improve itself, ``then Eastern's executives are
acting out a cruel hoax'' upon the government and the public.
   ``The passage of time should prove whether this is true,'' he
said.
   Trump, who testified before Parker on Dec. 7, has vowed to boost
morale at the shuttle and to recognize the unions but has declined
to guarantee current wages for the employees. Eastern has offered to
retain any shuttle workers who wish to remain with the company.
   Texas Air announced in February that it would sell the shuttle
for $225 million to a new subsidiary it planned to form. But
Eastern's unions blocked that transaction in the courts, and Texas
Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo announced in July that the deal had been
canceled.
   Since he acquired Eastern, the nation's sixth largest carrier, in
1986, Lorenzo has been embroiled in bitter disputes with the unions
representing the carrier's mechanics, pilots and flight attendants.
Lorenzo has sought wage concessions, while the unions have countered
with lobbying before Congress and public relations campaigns.
   The sale would give Trump all 17 aircraft, landing and takeoff
slots at airports in Boston, New York and Washington, 14 airport
gates and ground equipment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881219-0294 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-88 1833EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BurgerKing 1stLd-Writethru   12-19 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burger King, 1st Ld-Writethru,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Owner Expected To Help Fast-Food Giant</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new grafs 5-6 with comment from Burger King chairman.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British owner-to-be of Burger King is expected
to beef up the chain's standing in the sizzling U.S. fast-food
competition but rivals aren't conceding anything yet, franchisees
and securities analysts said Monday.
   ``They've been almost rudderless. I see these guys from England
coming in and ending (Burger King's) state of confusion,'' said John
P. Uphoff, an analyst in St. Petersburg with Raymond James &
Associates.
   London-based Grand Metropolitan PLC succeeded in its 2{-month
effort to take over Minneapolis-based Pillsbury Co., Burger King's
parent, on Sunday when Pillsbury's board agreed to stop fighting and
accept a $5.68 billion offer for the entire company.
   Grand Met executives have indicated they will move quickly to
improve Miami-based Burger King, which has been criticized by
franchise owners and other industry figures as the company has
slipped further behind kingpin McDonald's.
   ``We're very optimistic,'' Burger King Chairman Jerry Levin said
Monday.
   He said management had not received any word directly from Grand
Met, but ``we believe they are committed to Burger King. We seem to
be performing relatively even with the industry and I certainly
anticipate we will now out-perform the market.''
   Upstart Hardee's and struggling Wendy's have also had
more-positive performances lately than No. 2 Burger King, which last
fiscal year totaled $5.4 billion in sales.
   ``I think that they really believe that Burger King is a diamond
in the rough,'' said Steve Lewis, who owns 23 Burger King
restaurants in the Northeast. ``Amid this whole takeover we (Burger
King) were the key to making this whole thing work.''
   Thomas Ferguson, president of Miami's Beacon Council, which
promotes the area's businesses and community, said: ``We see Grand
Met as a savior.''
   ``Pillsbury kind of treated Burger King like a stepchild and
didn't know what to do with it,'' Ferguson told The Miami News on
Monday.
   Ian Martin, Grand Met's chief executive for U.S. operations,
called Pillsbury ``a perfect fit'' in helping Grand Met become a
world leader in food, drink and retailing.
   ``Pillsbury foods and Burger King will play a vital role in
helping us to realize these objectives,'' Martin said in a
statement. ``The merger will greatly expand Grand Metropolitan's
established presence in the huge U.S. marketplace, while enabling us
to open new business opportunities for Pillsbury in global markets.''
   Burger King, founded in Miami 34 years ago by James McLamore and
David Edgerton, was sold to Pillsbury in 1967 for $18 million. It
had 274 restaurants. It now has 5,578.
   The subsidiary's profits have skidded from $119.2 million in the
1986 fiscal year to $48.2 million in fiscal 1988. It averages $1
million a year in sales per store, compared to $1.5 million for
McDonald's, $920,000 for Hardee's and $786,000 (in 1987) for Wendy's.
   McDonald's total sales for fiscal 1987 were $14.3 billion in its
more than 10,000 restaurants.
   Uphoff suggested the new ownership will want to improve Burger
King's marketing, in the aftermath of much-criticized campaigns such
as the ``Find Herb'' promotion of a few years ago.
   Jay H. Freedman of Kidder Peabody & Co. in New York said to play
catch-up with McDonald's, Burger King must improve consistency.
   ``Even if you can convince them to come in, if you don't give
them an acceptable visit with consistently speedy service, clean
restaurant and restrooms, they're not going to come back,'' Freedman
said.
   Burger King's competitors said they didn't expect the takeover to
have a major impact immediately on their business.
   ``It's going to take some time. Nothing's going to happen
overnight,'' said Dennis Lynch, spokesman for Wendy's, based in
Dublin, Ohio. ``Having a new owner will clarify at least who's
calling the shots, but that doesn't mean there's a strategic plan in
place.''
   For Wendy's, which has been recovering after slipping financially
the past two years, Lynch said the confused situation at Burger King
has ``given us an opportunity to tell our message positively.''
   Hardee's, based in Rocky Point, N.C., has been growing fastest
among the industry's leaders, said spokesman Jerry Singer, and
should hold its own against any new Burger King initiatives.
   From McDonald's Oak Brook, Ill. headquarters, spokesman Chuck
Ebeling said the successful recipe of good service, good value and
cleanliness is what the industry leader concerns itself with.
   ``We don't talk about our competitors or the industry,'' Ebeling
said. ``We speak only of McDonald's. Just because they change
ownership ... they're still Brand X.''
</TEXT>
