<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PA-Wheeling-Pittsburgh     12-19 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PA-Wheeling-Pittsburgh,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board Approves Reorganization Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of directors of Wheeling-Pittsburgh
Steel Corp. on Monday approved the filing of a draft plan of
reorganization, a major step toward the company's emergence from
bankruptcy, the steelmaker said.
   A majority of the directors at a special meeting voted in favor
of filing the plan to U.S. Bankruptcy Court, Wheeling-Pitt said in a
statement.
   The company has been restructuring its debts and operations under
Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Code since April 1985.
Creditors were owed about $890 million at the time of the bankruptcy
filing.
   The plan was drafted by the board's reorganization committee,
said Wheeling-Pitt Chairman Lloyd Lubensky, whose ownership of about
34 percent of the company's stock makes him Wheeling-Pittsburgh's
largest stockholder.
   The draft plan does not consider the claims of the United
Steelworkers or the effects of a new basic labor agreement which
must be negotiated, the company said in a written statement.
   The company said it anticipates negotiations will ultimately
result in a final plan of reorganization to be submitted to
creditors and stockholders for their vote and then filed in
Bankruptcy Court for approval.
</TEXT>
