<1ST_LINE>r f AM-KrohSentence     12-19 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kroh Sentence,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Developer Receives Prison Sentence in Kansas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge rejected a plea
agreement from developer John A. Kroh Jr. Monday and sentenced him
to two years in prison and ordered him to pay $650,000 in
restitution for bank fraud.
   The case is similar to one that resulted in a 10-year prison term
for Kroh Thursday in Missouri. U.S. District Judge Earl E. O'Connor
sentenced the former president of Kroh Brothers Development Co. to
serve the two-year term consecutively with the 10-year sentence he
received last week.
   In the Kansas case, Kroh pleaded guilty to two counts of an
eight-count indictment on Oct. 14. Under a plea agreement reached
with federal prosecutors, Kroh admitted he understated his
liabilities in financial statements to two Kansas banks from which
he was seeking loans.
   Prosecutors agreed to recommend probation, but O'Connor said he
could not go along with the recommendation, which he called a
tremendous break for Kroh.
   ``The defendant, in all likelihood, judging from the Missouri
case, would more than likely have been convicted here on all counts
just as he was there,'' O'Connor said. ``And in all likelihood a
sentence on the order of what was imposed there in Missouri would
probably have been appropriate here.''
   The judge ordered Kroh to make restitution of $400,000 to Capital
City Bank & Trust of Topeka and $250,000 to Kansas National Bank &
Trust of Prairie Village.
   The cases in the two states stem from the collapse of the Kroh
real estate empire.
   Kroh's brother, George Kroh, pleaded guilty in May to bank fraud
and conspiracy. He served two months in a federal prison. His
original three-year sentence was reduced in July, partly because he
agreed to testify against his brother.
</TEXT>
