<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SecurityPacific     12-19 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Security Pacific,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules Against Bank's Sale of Mortgage-Backed Securities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge ruled Monday against Security
Pacific National Bank and the U.S. Comptroller of the Currency in a
dispute with securities dealers over the bank's sale of
mortgage-backed securities.
   U.S. District Judge Kevin Duffy in New York, ruling in a suit by
the Securities Dealers Association, rejected the comptroller's
decision to allow the bank to sell mortgage-backed securities backed
by its own mortgage loans.
   Bank spokeswoman Martha Goldstein said Security Pacific, the main
unit of the nation's sixth-largest bank holding company, was
considering an appeal. She didn't know if the decision would force
the bank to stop selling mortgage-backed securities pending appeal.
   Duffy ruled that the bank's sale of such securities would violate
the Glass-Steagall Act, Depression-era legislation that, among other
things, limits the rights of banks to enter the securities business.
The association's suit is against the comptroller, and Security
Pacific intervened on behalf of the defendant.
   The dispute centers on the decade-old practice of banks and
savings and loans to sell packages of mortgages on the so-called
secondary market, rather than selling single loans.
   The association maintained in its suit that banks should offer
the mortgage-backed securities through a dealer rather than
packaging and selling the securities themselves.
   In an unrelated matter, a Security Pacific official disclosed
that the bank had added $100 million worth of loans on Arizona real
estate to its list of non-performing loans in the fourth quarter.
The change is balanced by positive developments elsewhere and
doesn't affect the bank's predictions that fourth-quarter earnings,
scheduled for release Jan. 17, will show an increase over the third
quarter, said the official, Senior Vice President Jay Gould.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
